{"title_page": "Red meat", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Primary sources|article|date=January 2017}}\n[[File:Raw beef slices.jpg|thumb|Thinly sliced [[raw beef]] is red.]]\n[[File:Roastbeef.jpg|thumb|[[Roast beef]] is a darker color after being cooked.]]\nIn [[culinary|gastronomy]], '''red meat''' is commonly red when raw and a dark color after it is [[cooking|cooked]], in contrast to [[white meat]], which is pale in color before and after cooking.<ref name=\"red\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/red+meat |title=Red Meat |publisher=thefreedictionary.com}}</ref><ref name=\"white\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/white+meat |title=White Meat |publisher=thefreedictionary.com}}</ref> In culinary terms, only flesh from mammals or fowl (not fish) is classified as red or white.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foodandnutrition.org/January-February-2013/Color-Confusion-Identifying-Red-Meat-and-White-Meat/ |title=Color Confusion: Identifying Red Meat and White Meat |accessdate=2017-04-29 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230162203/http://www.foodandnutrition.org/January-February-2013/Color-Confusion-Identifying-Red-Meat-and-White-Meat/ |archivedate=2016-12-30 |date=2013-01-02 }}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[[Larousse Gastronomique]], first edition</ref> In [[nutritional science]], ''red meat'' is defined as any meat that has more of the protein [[myoglobin]] than white meat. White meat is defined as non-dark meat from fish or chicken (excluding the leg or thigh). The health effects of red meat are unclear as of 2019.<ref name=John2019 /> Some meat, such as [[pork]], is classified as ''white meat'' under the common or gastronomic definition, but as ''red meat'' under the nutritional definition.\n\n==Definition==\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\"\n|-\n|+ Concentration of myoglobin by percentage of mass\n! scope=\"col\" | Name\n! scope=\"col\" | Myoglobin\n! scope=\"col\" | USDA category\n|-\n| Chicken breast || 0.005%<ref name=\"Iowa State Animal Science\">{{cite web |url=http://www.anslab.iastate.edu/Class/AnS460-560/Class%20Notes/E-ChemistryofMeatProtein-5.ppt |title=Iowa State Animal Science |accessdate=2009-09-16 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090324234102/http://www.anslab.iastate.edu/Class/AnS460-560/Class%20Notes/E-ChemistryofMeatProtein-5.ppt |archivedate=2009-03-24 }}</ref> || White meat <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| Chicken thigh || 0.18 - 0.20%<ref name=\"Iowa State Animal Science\"/> || Dark meat\n|-\n| Turkey thigh || 0.25 - 0.30%<ref name=\"Iowa State Animal Science\"/> || Dark meat\n|-\n| Pork || 0.10 - 0.30%<ref name=\"Iowa State Animal Science\"/> || Red meat<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| Veal || 0.10 - 0.30%<ref name=\"Iowa State Animal Science\"/> || Red meat<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| Beef || 0.40 - 1.00%<ref name=\"Iowa State Animal Science\"/> || Red meat<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| Old beef || 1.50 - 2.00%<ref name=\"Iowa State Animal Science\"/> || Red meat<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|}\n\n[[File:Duck breast, smoked and panfried.jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|Cooked duck with potatoes, showing the red color of the meat]]\nUnder the culinary definition, the meat from adult or \"gamey\" mammals (for example, beef, horse meat, mutton, venison, boar, hare) is red meat, while that from young mammals (rabbit, veal, lamb) is white. Poultry is white, as well as duck and goose. Most cuts of pork are red, others are white.<ref>''Larousse Gastronomique'', 1961, ''s.v.'' pork</ref> [[Game (food)|Game]] is sometimes put in a separate category altogether. (French: ''viandes noires'' \u2014 \"dark meats\".)<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Some meats (lamb, pork) are classified differently by different writers.\n\nAccording to the [[United States Department of Agriculture]] (USDA), all meats obtained from mammals (regardless of cut or age) are red meats because they contain more [[myoglobin]] than fish or white meat (but not necessarily dark meat)<ref name=\"Iowa State Animal Science\"/> from chicken.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fsis.usda.gov/wps/portal/fsis/topics/food-safety-education/get-answers/food-safety-fact-sheets/meat-preparation/fresh-pork-from-farm-to-table/CT_Index |title=USDA-Safety of Fresh Pork...from Farm to Table |publisher=Fsis.usda.gov |date=2008-05-16 |accessdate=2009-09-16 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918111427/http://www.fsis.usda.gov/wps/portal/fsis/topics/food-safety-education/get-answers/food-safety-fact-sheets/meat-preparation/fresh-pork-from-farm-to-table/ct_index |archivedate=2013-09-18 }}</ref> Some cuts of pork are considered white under the culinary definition, but all pork is red in nutritional studies. The [[National Pork Board]] has [[Positioning (marketing)|positioned]] it as \"[[Pork. The Other White Meat|the other white meat]]\", profiting from the ambiguity to suggest that pork has the nutritional properties of white meat, which is considered more healthful.<ref>Dougherty, Philip H. [https://www.nytimes.com/1987/01/15/business/advertising-dressing-pork-for-success.html \"ADVERTISING; Dressing Pork for Success\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214230836/http://www.nytimes.com/1987/01/15/business/advertising-dressing-pork-for-success.html |date=2017-02-14 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]'', January 15, 1987. Accessed April 22, 2009.</ref><ref>Hall, Trish. [https://www.nytimes.com/1991/11/13/garden/and-this-little-piggy-is-now-on-the-menu.html \"And This Little Piggy Is Now on the Menu\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214225719/http://www.nytimes.com/1991/11/13/garden/and-this-little-piggy-is-now-on-the-menu.html |date=2017-02-14 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]'', November 13, 1991. Accessed April 22, 2009.</ref>\n\n=== Cultural and social aspects ===\nAcross many cultures, it is traditional to eat meat at gatherings or celebrations.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Smil|first=Vaclav|date=2002|title=Eating Meat: Evolution, Patterns, and Consequences|journal=Population and Development Review|volume=28|issue=4|pages=599\u2013639|jstor=3092782|doi=10.1111/j.1728-4457.2002.00599.x}}</ref> Consumption in the United States increased in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ers.usda.gov/amber-waves/2018/june/per-capita-red-meat-and-poultry-disappearance-insights-into-its-steady-growth/|title=USDA ERS - Per Capita Red Meat and Poultry Disappearance: Insights Into Its Steady Growth|website=www.ers.usda.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-12-03}}</ref>\n\n== Nutrition ==<!-- This section is linked from [[Paleolithic diet]] -->\nRed meat contains large amounts of [[iron]], [[creatine]], minerals such as [[zinc]] and [[phosphorus]], and B-vitamins: ([[niacin]], [[Cobalamin|vitamin B<sub>12</sub>]], [[thiamine|thiamin]] and [[riboflavin]]).<ref>Kansas State University Agricultural Experiment Station and Cooperative Extension Service, ''Red Meats: Nutrient Contributions to the Diet'', September 20 BC, [http://www.oznet.ksu.edu/library/fntr2/mf974.pdf] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060912003940/http://www.oznet.ksu.edu/library/fntr2/mf974.pdf|date=September 12, 2006}}</ref>  Red meat is a source of [[alpha lipoic acid|lipoic acid]].\n\nRed meat contains small amounts of [[vitamin D]].<ref>[http://ro.uow.edu.au/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1053&context=hbspapers Nutritional composition of red meat] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110310231338/http://ro.uow.edu.au/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1053&context=hbspapers |date=2011-03-10 }}</ref>  The [[liver]] contains much higher quantities than other parts of the animal.\n\nIn 2011, the USDA launched MyPlate, which did not distinguish between kinds of meat, but did recommend eating at least 8 oz (227 grams) of fish each week.<ref name=HSPHshould>Harvard School of Public Health, 2012. [http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/nutritionsource/what-should-you-eat/pyramid-full-story/index.html Food Pyramids: What Should You Really Eat] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416231207/http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/nutritionsource/what-should-you-eat/pyramid-full-story/index.html |date=2009-04-16 }}</ref><ref>USDA [http://www.choosemyplate.gov/food-groups/protein-foods.html MyPlate Protein foods] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116120159/http://www.choosemyplate.gov/food-groups/protein-foods.html |date=2013-01-16 }} Page accessed February 27, 2015</ref> In 2011, the Harvard School of Public Health launched the Healthy Eating Plate in part because of the perceived inadequacies of the USDA's recommendations.<ref name=HSPHshould/> The Healthy Eating Plate encourages consumers to avoid processed meat and limit red meat consumption to twice a week because of links to heart disease, diabetes, and colon cancer. To replace these meats it recommends consuming fish, poultry, beans or nuts.<ref name=HSPHshould/>\n\n==Health effects==\n{{see also|Beef#Health concerns|Meat#Health}}\n\nThe health effects of red meat are unclear as of 2019.<ref name=John2019>{{cite journal |display-authors=3 |last1=Johnston |first1=Bradley C. |last2=Zeraatkar |first2=Dena |last3=Han |first3=Mi Ah |last4=Vernooij |first4=Robin W.M. |last5=Valli |first5=Claudia |last6=El Dib |first6=Regina |last7=Marshall |first7=Catherine |last8=Stover |first8=Patrick J. |last9=Fairweather-Taitt |first9=Susan |last10=W\u00f3jcik |first10=Grzegorz |last11=Bhatia |first11=Faiz |last12=de Souza |first12=Russell |last13=Brotons |first13=Carlos |last14=Meerpohl |first14=Joerg J. |last15=Patel |first15=Chirag J. |last16=Djulbegovic |first16=Benjamin |last17=Alonso-Coello |first17=Pablo |last18=Bala |first18=Malgorzata M. |last19=Guyatt |first19=Gordon H. |title=Unprocessed Red Meat and Processed Meat Consumption: Dietary Guideline Recommendations From the Nutritional Recommendations (NutriRECS) Consortium |journal=Annals of Internal Medicine |date=1 October 2019 |doi=10.7326/M19-1621 |pmid=31569235 |volume=171 |page=756|doi-access=free }}</ref> Understanding the health impact of red meat is difficult because it is not a uniform product, with effects varying based on fat content, processing and preparation. One analysis showed that processed red meat is linked to slightly higher mortality, mainly due to [[cardiovascular disease]]s and cancer.<ref name=\"BMC03713\">{{cite journal |author1=Sabine Rohrmann |author2=Kim Overvad |title=Meat consumption and mortality \u2013 results from the European Prospective Investigation into Cancer and Nutrition |journal=BMC Medicine |date=7 March 2013 |volume=11 |doi=10.1186/1741-7015-11-63 |author3=European Prospective Investigation into Cancer and Nutrition |author3link=European Prospective Investigation into Cancer and Nutrition |quote=The results of our analysis support a moderate positive association between processed meat consumption and mortality, in particular due to cardiovascular diseases, but also to cancer. |issue=1 |pages=63 |display-authors=etal |pmid=23497300 |pmc=3599112 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Processed meat===\n{{see also|Processed meat}}\nIn 2015, the [[International Agency for Research on Cancer]] of the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) classified ''processed meat'' (bacon, ham, hot dogs, sausages) as [[Carcinogen|carcinogenic]] to humans (Group 1), based on \"sufficient evidence in humans that the consumption of processed meat causes [[colorectal cancer]].\"<ref name=\"who\">{{cite web |title=Q&A on the carcinogenicity of the consumption of red meat and processed meat |url=https://www.who.int/features/qa/cancer-red-meat/en/ |publisher=World Health Organization |accessdate=7 August 2019 |date=1 October 2015}}</ref> \n\nMost processed meat contains at least some red meat.<ref name=IARC2015PR/> To enhance flavor or improve preservation meat is treated by salting, curing, fermentation, smoking, or other processes to create processed meat.<ref name=IARC2015PR/> Nitrates and nitrites found in processed meat (e.g. bacon, ham, salami, pepperoni, hot dogs, and some sausages) can be converted by the human body into nitrosamines that can be carcinogenic, causing mutation in the colorectal cell line, thereby causing tumorigenesis and eventually leading to cancer.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rapha\u00eblle|first1=Santarelli|title=Processed Meat and Colorectal Cancer: A Review of Epidemiologic and Experimental Evidence.|journal=Nutrition and Cancer|doi=10.1080/01635580701684872|pmid=18444144|pmc=2661797|volume=60|issue=2|pages=131\u2013144|df=|year=2008}}</ref> In its Press Release 240 (16 Oct. 2015) the International Agency for Research on Cancer, based on a review of 800 studies over 20 years, concluded that processed meat is definitely carcinogenic (Group 1) and found that for each additional 50g of processed meat consumed per day, the risk of  [[colorectal cancer]] increased by 18% (up to a maximum of approximately 140g);<ref name=\"chan2011\"/> it also found that there appeared to be an increase in [[gastric cancer]] but this was not as clear.<ref name=IARClancet/>\n\nA 2016 literature review found that for the each additional 50g per day of [[processed meat]] (e.g., bacon, ham, hot dogs, sausages) consumed, the risk increased 4% for total prostate cancer, 8% for cancer mortality, 9% for breast cancer, 18% for colorectal cancer, 19% for pancreatic cancer, 13% for stroke, 24% for cardiovascular mortality and 32% for diabetes.<ref name=Wolk2016rev/>\n\n===Red meat===\nIn 2015 the [[International Agency for Research on Cancer]] concluded that red meat is probably (Group 2A) [[carcinogenic]] to humans<ref name=IARC2015PR>{{citation |author=International Agency for Research on Cancer |title=IARC Monographs evaluate consumption of red meat and processed meat |issue=Press Release N\u00b0 240 |date=26 October 2015 |url=https://www.iarc.fr/en/media-centre/pr/2015/pdfs/pr240_E.pdf |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151110184724/http://www.iarc.fr/en/media-centre/pr/2015/pdfs/pr240_E.pdf |archivedate=10 November 2015 }}</ref>.\n\nStudies that differentiate between processed and fresh red meat have failed to find a link between unprocessed red meat consumption and heart disease. A meta-analysis published in 2010 involving around one million people who ate meat found that only processed meat had an adverse risk in relation to [[coronary artery disease|coronary heart disease]] (CHD).<ref name=Micha2010>{{cite journal|last1=Micha|first1=R.|last2=Wallace|first2=S. K.|last3=Mozaffarian|first3=D.|title=Red and Processed Meat Consumption and Risk of Incident Coronary Heart Disease, Stroke, and Diabetes Mellitus: A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis|journal=Circulation|date=1 June 2010|volume=121|issue=21|pages=2271\u20132283|doi=10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.109.924977|pmid=20479151|pmc=2885952|df=}}</ref> The review suggested that the \"differences in salt and preservatives, rather than fats, might explain the higher risk of heart disease and diabetes seen with processed meats, but not with unprocessed red meats.\"<ref name=Micha2010/>\n\nSeveral studies have found a correlation between unprocessed red meat and the occurrence of CHD and certain types of stroke and have controlled for various confounding risk factors.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=TH|first=Leung|year=2012|title=Red Meat Consumption: The Good and the Bad|url=http://www.chp.gov.hk/files/pdf/ncd_watch_aug2012.pdf|journal=Non-Communicable Diseases Watch|volume=5|pages=1\u20137|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230201847/http://www.chp.gov.hk/files/pdf/ncd_watch_aug2012.pdf|archivedate=2015-12-30}}</ref> A study of 84,000 women, over a period of 26 years, finds that those with the highest intake of unprocessed red meat have a 13% increased risk of CHD.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nUnprocessed red meat intake is tentatively associated with an increased risk of [[type II diabetes]], but the link is weaker and less certain than the link between processed red meat and diabetes.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Micha|first1=Renata|last2=Michas|first2=Georgios|last3=Mozaffarian|first3=Dariush|title=Unprocessed Red and Processed Meats and Risk of Coronary Artery Disease and Type 2 Diabetes \u2013 An Updated Review of the Evidence|journal=Current Atherosclerosis Reports|date=22 September 2012|volume=14|issue=6|pages=515\u2013524|doi=10.1007/s11883-012-0282-8|pmid=23001745|pmc=3483430}}</ref> Other findings have suggested that the association may be due to [[saturated fat]], [[trans fat]] and [[dietary cholesterol]], rather than red meat per se.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Hu | first1 = F. B. | last2 = Van Dam | first2 = S. | last3 = Liu | first3 = R. M. | title = Diet and risk of Type II diabetes: the role of types of fat and carbohydrate | journal = Diabetologia | volume = 44 | issue = 7 | pages = 805\u2013817 | year = 2001 | pmid = 11508264 | doi = 10.1007/s001250100547| doi-access = free }}</ref> \n\n==== Cancer ====\n{{Prose|section|date=March 2020}}\n* In 2015, the [[International Agency for Research on Cancer]] of the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) classified ''red meat'' as \"probably carcinogenic to humans (Group 2A), based on limited evidence that the consumption of red meat causes cancer in humans and strong mechanistic evidence supporting a carcinogenic effect.\"<ref name=\"WHO-20151026\">{{cite web|title=Press release: IARC monographs evaluate consumption of red meat and processed meat |url=http://www.iarc.fr/en/media-centre/pr/2015/pdfs/pr240_E.pdf |publisher=[[International Agency for Research on Cancer]], World Health Organization|accessdate=26 October  2015|date=15 October 2015 }}</ref> \n\n* A 2011 study reported that for each additional 100g (up to a maximum of approximately 140g)<ref name=\"chan2011\">{{cite journal |last=Chan |first=DS |last2=Lau |first2=R |last3=Aune |first3=D |last4=Vieira |first4=R |last5=Greenwood |first5=DC |last6=Kampman |first6=E |last7=Norat |first7=T |date=2011-06-06 |title=Red and processed meat and colorectal cancer incidence: meta-analysis of prospective studies. |journal=PLOS ONE |volume=6 |issue=6 |pages= e20456|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0020456 |pmid=21674008 |quote=In non-linear models, colorectal cancer risk appears to increase almost linearly with increasing intake of red and processed meats up to approximately 140 g/day. Above this level, the risk increase is less pronounced.. |pmc=3108955|bibcode=2011PLoSO...620456C }}</ref> of red meat consumed per day, the risk of  [[colorectal cancer]] increased by 17%; there also appeared to be increased risk of [[pancreatic cancer]] and [[prostate cancer]] but the association was not as clear.<ref name=IARClancet>{{cite journal|last1=Bouvard|first1=V|display-authors=etal|last2=International Agency for Research on Cancer Monograph Working Group.|title=Carcinogenicity of consumption of red and processed meat.|journal=The Lancet. Oncology|date=December 2015|volume=16|issue=16|pages=1599\u2013600|pmid=26514947|doi=10.1016/s1470-2045(15)00444-1|url=https://www.statsarecool.com/data/uploads/journal-articles/who_declares_reds_meat_carcinogeniclancet_oct_2015.pdf}}</ref>  Put in perspective, in the UK, 56 out of 1000 people who eat the lowest amount of red meat will develop colorectal cancer (5.6%) while 66 out of 1000 high-red meat eaters will develop colorectal cancer (6.6%) (1.17 x 5.6 = 6.6).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://scienceblog.cancerresearchuk.org/2015/10/26/processed-meat-and-cancer-what-you-need-to-know/|title=Processed meat and cancer \u2013 what you need to know|website=Cancer Research UK - Science blog|access-date=2016-12-29|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170109195400/http://scienceblog.cancerresearchuk.org/2015/10/26/processed-meat-and-cancer-what-you-need-to-know/|archivedate=2017-01-09}}</ref>\n\n* A 2012 meta-analysis found an increased risk of gastric cancer with higher consumption of red or processed meat.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Zhu|first1=H|display-authors=etal|title=Red and processed meat intake is associated with higher gastric cancer risk: a meta-analysis of epidemiological observational studies.|journal=PLOS ONE|date=2013|volume=8|issue=8|pages=e70955|pmid=23967140|pmc=3743884|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0070955|bibcode=2013PLoSO...870955Z}}</ref>  Red meat itself contains certain factors that, under certain conditions, produce carcinogens like N-nitroso compounds (NOCs).<ref>{{cite web|title=Inherited Bowel Cancer|url=http://www.geneticseducation.nhs.uk/genetic-conditions-54/677-inherited-bowel-cancer-new|website=geneticseducation.nhs.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225011653/http://www.geneticseducation.nhs.uk/genetic-conditions-54/677-inherited-bowel-cancer-new|archivedate=2014-12-25}}</ref>\n\n* A 2016 literature review reported that for 100g or more per day of red meat consumed, the risk increased 11% for each of stroke and for breast cancer, 15% for cardiovascular mortality, 17% for colorectal cancer, and 19% for advanced prostate cancer.<ref name=Wolk2016rev>{{cite journal |last1=Wolk |first1=A |title=Potential health hazards of eating red meat. |journal=Journal of Internal Medicine |volume = 281|issue=2 |pages=106\u2013122 |date=6 September 2016 |pmid=27597529 |doi=10.1111/joim.12543 |df= }}</ref>\n\n* A 2017 review indicated there are numerous potential carcinogens of colorectal tissue in red meat, particularly those in processed red meat products, such as [[N-nitroso]] compounds, [[polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon]]s, and [[heterocyclic amine]]s.<ref name=\"jeyakumar\">{{cite journal | last=Jeyakumar | first=Arunan | last2=Dissabandara | first2=Lakal | last3=Gopalan | first3=Vinod | title=A critical overview on the biological and molecular features of red and processed meat in colorectal carcinogenesis | journal=Journal of Gastroenterology | volume=52 | issue=4 | date=1 April 2017 | issn=0944-1174 | pmid=27913919 | doi=10.1007/s00535-016-1294-x | pages=407\u2013418}}</ref>\n\n====Cardiovascular disease and diabetes====\nA 2017 [[systematic review]] and [[meta-analysis]] of [[clinical research]] on [[stroke]] outcomes associated with meat consumption showed that total meat consumption, red meat consumption, and processed red meat consumption increased the risk of stroke by 18%, 11%, and 17%, respectively, while consuming white meat (chicken) reduced the risk of stroke by 13%.<ref name=\"Kim\">{{cite journal | last=Kim | first=Kyuwoong | last2=Hyeon | first2=Junghyeon | last3=Lee | first3=Sang Ah | last4=Kwon | first4=Sung Ok | last5=Lee | first5=Hyejin | last6=Keum | first6=NaNa | last7=Lee | first7=Jong\u2010Koo | last8=Park | first8=Sang Min | title=Role of total, red, processed, and white meat consumption in stroke incidence and mortality: A systematic review and meta\u2010analysis of prospective cohort studies | journal=Journal of the American Heart Association | volume=6 | issue=9 | date=2017-09-22 | issn=2047-9980 | doi=10.1161/jaha.117.005983 | page=e005983|pmid=28855166|pmc=5634267}}</ref> Factors associated with increased stroke risk from consuming red meat include [[saturated fat]]s that increase levels of [[blood cholesterol]], [[LDL cholesterol]], [[triglyceride]]s, and [[heme]] [[iron]], which may precipitate [[atherogenesis]] in cerebral arteries, leading to stroke.<ref name=Kim/>\n\nA 2017 review found that consuming a one-half serving of red meat daily was not associated with [[cardiovascular disease]] [[risk factor]]s, such as total cholesterol, LDL, and [[hypertension]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=O'Connor |first1=LE |last2=Kim |first2=JE |last3=Campbell |first3=WW |title=Total red meat intake of \u22650.5 servings/d does not negatively influence cardiovascular disease risk factors: a systemically searched meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials. |journal=American Journal of Clinical Nutrition |date=January 2017 |volume=105 |issue=1 |pages=57\u201369 |doi=10.3945/ajcn.116.142521 |pmid=27881394|pmc=5183733 }}</ref> One study estimated that \u201csubstitutions of one serving of nuts, low-fat dairy, and whole grains per day for one serving of red meat per day were associated with a 16\u201335% lower risk of type 2 diabetes\u201d.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Pan | first1 = A. | last2 = Sun | first2 = Q. | last3 = Bernstein | first3 = A. M. | last4 = Schulze | first4 = M. B. | last5 = Manson | first5 = J. E. | last6 = Willett | first6 = W. C. | last7 = Hu | first7 = F. B. | doi = 10.3945/ajcn.111.018978 | title = Red meat consumption and risk of type 2 diabetes: 3 cohorts of US adults and an updated meta-analysis | journal = American Journal of Clinical Nutrition | volume = 94 | issue = 4 | pages = 1088\u20131096 | year = 2011 | pmid =  21831992| pmc =3173026 }}</ref>\n\nRed meat consumption has been associated with higher [[fasting glucose]] and [[insulin]] concentrations, which are risk factors for [[type 2 diabetes]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fretts |first1=Amanda |title=Consumption of meat is associated with higher fasting glucose and insulin concentrations regardless of glucose and insulin genetic risk scores: a meta-analysis of 50,345 Caucasians |journal=American Journal of Clinical Nutrition |date=November 2015 |volume=102 |issue=5 |pages=1266\u201378 |pmid=26354543|pmc=4625584 |doi=10.3945/ajcn.114.101238 }}</ref> Daily consumption of 85 grams of red meat and 35 grams of processed red meat products by European and American consumers increased their risk of type 2 diabetes by 18-36%, while a diet of abstinence of red meat consuming whole grains, vegetables, fruits, and dairy was associated with an 81% reduced risk of diabetes.<ref name=\"Schwing\">{{cite journal | last=Schwingshackl | first=Lukas | last2=Hoffmann | first2=Georg | last3=Lampousi | first3=Anna-Maria | last4=Kn\u00fcppel | first4=Sven | last5=Iqbal | first5=Khalid | last6=Schwedhelm | first6=Carolina | last7=Bechthold | first7=Angela | last8=Schlesinger | first8=Sabrina | last9=Boeing | first9=Heiner | title=Food groups and risk of type 2 diabetes mellitus: a systematic review and meta-analysis of prospective studies | journal=European Journal of Epidemiology| volume=32 | issue=5 | date=2017-04-10 | issn=0393-2990 | doi=10.1007/s10654-017-0246-y | pages=363\u2013375|pmid=28397016|pmc=5506108}}</ref>\n\n====Cooking====\n[[File:Delmonico_steak.jpg|thumb|right|Meat with a dark exterior, common in high temperature cooking]]\nCooking any meat at a high temperature or smoking meat produces [[carcinogen]]ic [[polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon]] compounds (PAHs) and [[heterocyclic amines]] (HCAs).<ref>{{cite web|title=Chemicals in Meat Cooked at High Temperatures and Cancer Risk|url=http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/factsheet/Risk/cooked-meats|website=National Cancer Institute|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106080003/http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/factsheet/Risk/cooked-meats|archivedate=2011-11-06|year=2018}}</ref> The subgroups of heterocyclic amines compounds are amino-dimethylimidazo-quinoxaline (MelQx), amino-dimethylimidazo-quinoxaline (DiMelQx), and amino-methyl-phenylimidazo-pyridine (PhIP), which are mostly formed when meat is cooked at high temperatures.  [[Benzo(a)pyrene|Benzo[a]pyrene]] (B[a]P) is another compound found in meat cooked at extremely high temperatures. Likely because of these factors, marinating fresh lean red meat and thoroughly cooking it at a low temperature will reduce the production of carcinogenic compounds and thereby lower the risk of [[colorectal cancer]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Marinades Reduce Heterocyclic Amines from Primitive Food Preparation Techniques|url=http://naturalmedicinejournal.com/journal/2010-07/marinades-reduce-heterocyclic-amines-primitive-food-preparation-techniques|publisher=Schor J|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225012038/http://naturalmedicinejournal.com/journal/2010-07/marinades-reduce-heterocyclic-amines-primitive-food-preparation-techniques|archivedate=2014-12-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Seer Stat Fact Sheets: Colon and Rectum Cancer|url=http://seer.cancer.gov/statfacts/html/colorect.html|website=Seer.cancer.gov|publisher=National Cancer Institute|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140624140833/http://seer.cancer.gov/statfacts/html/colorect.html|archivedate=2014-06-24}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Food}}\n* [[White meat]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.iarc.fr/en/media-centre/pr/2015/pdfs/pr240_E.pdf International Association for Research on Cancer, press release 240, 26. October 2015]\n*[http://www.iarc.fr/en/media-centre/iarcnews/pdf/Monographs-Q&A.pdf IARC Monographs Q&A]\n*[http://www.iarc.fr/en/media-centre/iarcnews/pdf/Monographs-Q&A_Vol114.pdf IARC Monographs Q&A on the carcinogenicity of the consumption of red meat and processed meat.]\n\n{{sisterlinks}}\n\n{{Meat product navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Red Meat}}\n[[Category:Meat]]\n[[Category:IARC Group 2A carcinogens]]\n\n[[sv:K\u00f6tt#R\u00f6tt och vitt k\u00f6tt]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Primary sources|article|date=January 2017}}\n[[File:Raw beef slices.jpg|thumb|Thinly sliced [[raw beef]] is red.]]\n[[File:Roastbeef.jpg|thumb|[[Roast beef]] is a darker color after being cooked.]]\nIn [[culinary|gastronomy]], '''red meat''' is commonly red when raw and a dark color after it is [[cooking|cooked]], in contrast to [[white meat]], which is pale in color before and after cooking.<ref name=\"red\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/red+meat |title=Red Meat |publisher=thefreedictionary.com}}</ref><ref name=\"white\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/white+meat |title=White Meat |publisher=thefreedictionary.com}}</ref> In culinary terms, only flesh from mammals or fowl (not fish) is classified as red or white.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foodandnutrition.org/January-February-2013/Color-Confusion-Identifying-Red-Meat-and-White-Meat/ |title=Color Confusion: Identifying Red Meat and White Meat |accessdate=2017-04-29 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230162203/http://www.foodandnutrition.org/January-February-2013/Color-Confusion-Identifying-Red-Meat-and-White-Meat/ |archivedate=2016-12-30 |date=2013-01-02 }}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[[Larousse Gastronomique]], first edition</ref> In [[nutritional science]], ''red meat'' is defined as any meat that has more of the protein [[myoglobin]] than white meat. White meat is defined as non-dark meat from fish or chicken (excluding the leg or thigh). The health effects of red meat are unclear as of 2019.<ref name=John2019 /> Some meat, such as [[pork]], is classified as ''white meat'' under the common or gastronomic definition, but as ''red meat'' under the nutritional definition.\n\n==Definition==\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\"\n|-\n|+ Concentration of myoglobin by percentage of mass\n! scope=\"col\" | Name\n! scope=\"col\" | Myoglobin\n! scope=\"col\" | USDA category\n|-\n| Chicken breast || 0.005%<ref name=\"Iowa State Animal Science\">{{cite web |url=http://www.anslab.iastate.edu/Class/AnS460-560/Class%20Notes/E-ChemistryofMeatProtein-5.ppt |title=Iowa State Animal Science |accessdate=2009-09-16 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090324234102/http://www.anslab.iastate.edu/Class/AnS460-560/Class%20Notes/E-ChemistryofMeatProtein-5.ppt |archivedate=2009-03-24 }}</ref> || White meat <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| Chicken thigh || 0.18 - 0.20%<ref name=\"Iowa State Animal Science\"/> || Dark meat\n|-\n| Turkey thigh || 0.25 - 0.30%<ref name=\"Iowa State Animal Science\"/> || Dark meat\n|-\n| Pork || 0.10 - 0.30%<ref name=\"Iowa State Animal Science\"/> || Red meat<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| Veal || 0.10 - 0.30%<ref name=\"Iowa State Animal Science\"/> || Red meat<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| Beef || 0.40 - 1.00%<ref name=\"Iowa State Animal Science\"/> || Red meat<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| Old beef || 1.50 - 2.00%<ref name=\"Iowa State Animal Science\"/> || Red meat<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|}\n\n[[File:Duck breast, smoked and panfried.jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|Cooked duck with potatoes, showing the red color of the meat]]\nUnder the culinary definition, the meat from adult or \"gamey\" mammals (for example, beef, horse meat, mutton, venison, boar, hare) is red meat, while that from young mammals (rabbit, veal, lamb) is white. Poultry is white, as well as duck and goose. Most cuts of pork are red, others are white.<ref>''Larousse Gastronomique'', 1961, ''s.v.'' pork</ref> [[Game (food)|Game]] is sometimes put in a separate category altogether. (French: ''viandes noires'' \u2014 \"dark meats\".)<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Some meats (lamb, pork) are classified differently by different writers.\n\nAccording to the [[United States Department of Agriculture]] (USDA), all meats obtained from mammals (regardless of cut or age) are red meats because they contain more [[myoglobin]] than fish or white meat (but not necessarily dark meat)<ref name=\"Iowa State Animal Science\"/> from chicken.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fsis.usda.gov/wps/portal/fsis/topics/food-safety-education/get-answers/food-safety-fact-sheets/meat-preparation/fresh-pork-from-farm-to-table/CT_Index |title=USDA-Safety of Fresh Pork...from Farm to Table |publisher=Fsis.usda.gov |date=2008-05-16 |accessdate=2009-09-16 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130918111427/http://www.fsis.usda.gov/wps/portal/fsis/topics/food-safety-education/get-answers/food-safety-fact-sheets/meat-preparation/fresh-pork-from-farm-to-table/ct_index |archivedate=2013-09-18 }}</ref> Some cuts of pork are considered white under the culinary definition, but all pork is red in nutritional studies. The [[National Pork Board]] has [[Positioning (marketing)|positioned]] it as \"[[Pork. The Other White Meat|the other white meat]]\", profiting from the ambiguity to suggest that pork has the nutritional properties of white meat, which is considered more healthful.<ref>Dougherty, Philip H. [https://www.nytimes.com/1987/01/15/business/advertising-dressing-pork-for-success.html \"ADVERTISING; Dressing Pork for Success\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214230836/http://www.nytimes.com/1987/01/15/business/advertising-dressing-pork-for-success.html |date=2017-02-14 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]'', January 15, 1987. Accessed April 22, 2009.</ref><ref>Hall, Trish. [https://www.nytimes.com/1991/11/13/garden/and-this-little-piggy-is-now-on-the-menu.html \"And This Little Piggy Is Now on the Menu\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214225719/http://www.nytimes.com/1991/11/13/garden/and-this-little-piggy-is-now-on-the-menu.html |date=2017-02-14 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]'', November 13, 1991. Accessed April 22, 2009.</ref>\n\n=== Cultural and social aspects ===\nAcross many cultures, it is traditional to eat meat at gatherings or celebrations.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Smil|first=Vaclav|date=2002|title=Eating Meat: Evolution, Patterns, and Consequences|journal=Population and Development Review|volume=28|issue=4|pages=599\u2013639|jstor=3092782|doi=10.1111/j.1728-4457.2002.00599.x}}</ref> Consumption in the United States increased in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ers.usda.gov/amber-waves/2018/june/per-capita-red-meat-and-poultry-disappearance-insights-into-its-steady-growth/|title=USDA ERS - Per Capita Red Meat and Poultry Disappearance: Insights Into Its Steady Growth|website=www.ers.usda.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-12-03}}</ref>\n\n== Nutrition ==<!-- This section is linked from [[Paleolithic diet]] -->\nRed meat contains large amounts of [[iron]], [[creatine]], minerals such as [[zinc]] and [[phosphorus]], and B-vitamins: ([[niacin]], [[Cobalamin|vitamin B<sub>12</sub>]], [[thiamine|thiamin]] and [[riboflavin]]).<ref>Kansas State University Agricultural Experiment Station and Cooperative Extension Service, ''Red Meats: Nutrient Contributions to the Diet'', September 20 BC, [http://www.oznet.ksu.edu/library/fntr2/mf974.pdf] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060912003940/http://www.oznet.ksu.edu/library/fntr2/mf974.pdf|date=September 12, 2006}}</ref>  Red meat is a source of [[alpha lipoic acid|lipoic acid]].\n\nRed meat contains small amounts of [[vitamin D]].<ref>[http://ro.uow.edu.au/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1053&context=hbspapers Nutritional composition of red meat] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110310231338/http://ro.uow.edu.au/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1053&context=hbspapers |date=2011-03-10 }}</ref>  The [[liver]] contains much higher quantities than other parts of the animal.\n\nIn 2011, the USDA launched MyPlate, which did not distinguish between kinds of meat, but did recommend eating at least 8 oz (227 grams) of fish each week.<ref name=HSPHshould>Harvard School of Public Health, 2012. [http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/nutritionsource/what-should-you-eat/pyramid-full-story/index.html Food Pyramids: What Should You Really Eat] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416231207/http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/nutritionsource/what-should-you-eat/pyramid-full-story/index.html |date=2009-04-16 }}</ref><ref>USDA [http://www.choosemyplate.gov/food-groups/protein-foods.html MyPlate Protein foods] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116120159/http://www.choosemyplate.gov/food-groups/protein-foods.html |date=2013-01-16 }} Page accessed February 27, 2015</ref> In 2011, the Harvard School of Public Health launched the Healthy Eating Plate in part because of the perceived inadequacies of the USDA's recommendations.<ref name=HSPHshould/> The Healthy Eating Plate encourages consumers to avoid processed meat and limit red meat consumption to twice a week because of links to heart disease, diabetes, and colon cancer. To replace these meats it recommends consuming fish, poultry, beans or nuts.<ref name=HSPHshould/>\n\n==Health effects==\n{{see also|Beef#Health concerns|Meat#Health}}\n\nThe health effects of red meat are unclear as of 2019.<ref name=John2019>{{cite journal |display-authors=3 |last1=Johnston |first1=Bradley C. |last2=Zeraatkar |first2=Dena |last3=Han |first3=Mi Ah |last4=Vernooij |first4=Robin W.M. |last5=Valli |first5=Claudia |last6=El Dib |first6=Regina |last7=Marshall |first7=Catherine |last8=Stover |first8=Patrick J. |last9=Fairweather-Taitt |first9=Susan |last10=W\u00f3jcik |first10=Grzegorz |last11=Bhatia |first11=Faiz |last12=de Souza |first12=Russell |last13=Brotons |first13=Carlos |last14=Meerpohl |first14=Joerg J. |last15=Patel |first15=Chirag J. |last16=Djulbegovic |first16=Benjamin |last17=Alonso-Coello |first17=Pablo |last18=Bala |first18=Malgorzata M. |last19=Guyatt |first19=Gordon H. |title=Unprocessed Red Meat and Processed Meat Consumption: Dietary Guideline Recommendations From the Nutritional Recommendations (NutriRECS) Consortium |journal=Annals of Internal Medicine |date=1 October 2019 |doi=10.7326/M19-1621 |pmid=31569235 |volume=171 |page=756|doi-access=free }}</ref> Understanding the health impact of red meat is difficult because it is not a uniform product, with effects varying based on fat content, processing and preparation. One analysis showed that processed red meat is linked to slightly higher mortality, mainly due to [[cardiovascular disease]]s and cancer.<ref name=\"BMC03713\">{{cite journal |author1=Sabine Rohrmann |author2=Kim Overvad |title=Meat consumption and mortality \u2013 results from the European Prospective Investigation into Cancer and Nutrition |journal=BMC Medicine |date=7 March 2013 |volume=11 |doi=10.1186/1741-7015-11-63 |author3=European Prospective Investigation into Cancer and Nutrition |author3link=European Prospective Investigation into Cancer and Nutrition |quote=The results of our analysis support a moderate positive association between processed meat consumption and mortality, in particular due to cardiovascular diseases, but also to cancer. |issue=1 |pages=63 |display-authors=etal |pmid=23497300 |pmc=3599112 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Processed meat===\n{{see also|Processed meat}}\nIn 2015, the [[International Agency for Research on Cancer]] of the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) classified ''processed meat'' (bacon, ham, hot dogs, sausages) as [[Carcinogen|carcinogenic]] to humans (Group 1), based on \"sufficient evidence in humans that the consumption of processed meat causes [[colorectal cancer]].\"<ref name=\"who\">{{cite web |title=Q&A on the carcinogenicity of the consumption of red meat and processed meat |url=https://www.who.int/features/qa/cancer-red-meat/en/ |publisher=World Health Organization |accessdate=7 August 2019 |date=1 October 2015}}</ref> \n\nMost processed meat contains at least some red meat.<ref name=IARC2015PR/> To enhance flavor or improve preservation meat is treated by salting, curing, fermentation, smoking, or other processes to create processed meat.<ref name=IARC2015PR/> Nitrates and nitrites found in processed meat (e.g. bacon, ham, salami, pepperoni, hot dogs, and some sausages) can be converted by the human body into nitrosamines that can be carcinogenic, causing mutation in the colorectal cell line, thereby causing tumorigenesis and eventually leading to cancer.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rapha\u00eblle|first1=Santarelli|title=Processed Meat and Colorectal Cancer: A Review of Epidemiologic and Experimental Evidence.|journal=Nutrition and Cancer|doi=10.1080/01635580701684872|pmid=18444144|pmc=2661797|volume=60|issue=2|pages=131\u2013144|df=|year=2008}}</ref> In its Press Release 240 (16 Oct. 2015) the International Agency for Research on Cancer, based on a review of 800 studies over 20 years, concluded that processed meat is definitely carcinogenic (Group 1) and found that for each additional 50g of processed meat consumed per day, the risk of  [[colorectal cancer]] increased by 18% (up to a maximum of approximately 140g);<ref name=\"chan2011\"/> it also found that there appeared to be an increase in [[gastric cancer]] but this was not as clear.<ref name=IARClancet/>\n\nA 2016 literature review found that for the each additional 50g per day of [[processed meat]] (e.g., bacon, ham, hot dogs, sausages) consumed, the risk increased 4% for total prostate cancer, 8% for cancer mortality, 9% for breast cancer, 18% for colorectal cancer, 19% for pancreatic cancer, 13% for stroke, 24% for cardiovascular mortality and 32% for diabetes.<ref name=Wolk2016rev/>\n\n===Red meat===\nIn 2015 the [[International Agency for Research on Cancer]] concluded that red meat is probably (Group 2A) [[carcinogenic]] to humans,<ref name=IARC2015PR>{{citation |author=International Agency for Research on Cancer |title=IARC Monographs evaluate consumption of red meat and processed meat |issue=Press Release N\u00b0 240 |date=26 October 2015 |url=https://www.iarc.fr/en/media-centre/pr/2015/pdfs/pr240_E.pdf |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151110184724/http://www.iarc.fr/en/media-centre/pr/2015/pdfs/pr240_E.pdf |archivedate=10 November 2015 }}</ref>.\n\nStudies that differentiate between processed and fresh red meat have failed to find a link between unprocessed red meat consumption and heart disease. A meta-analysis published in 2010 involving around one million people who ate meat found that only processed meat had an adverse risk in relation to [[coronary artery disease|coronary heart disease]] (CHD).<ref name=Micha2010>{{cite journal|last1=Micha|first1=R.|last2=Wallace|first2=S. K.|last3=Mozaffarian|first3=D.|title=Red and Processed Meat Consumption and Risk of Incident Coronary Heart Disease, Stroke, and Diabetes Mellitus: A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis|journal=Circulation|date=1 June 2010|volume=121|issue=21|pages=2271\u20132283|doi=10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.109.924977|pmid=20479151|pmc=2885952|df=}}</ref> The review suggested that the \"differences in salt and preservatives, rather than fats, might explain the higher risk of heart disease and diabetes seen with processed meats, but not with unprocessed red meats.\"<ref name=Micha2010/>\n\nSeveral studies have found a correlation between unprocessed red meat and the occurrence of CHD and certain types of stroke and have controlled for various confounding risk factors.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=TH|first=Leung|year=2012|title=Red Meat Consumption: The Good and the Bad|url=http://www.chp.gov.hk/files/pdf/ncd_watch_aug2012.pdf|journal=Non-Communicable Diseases Watch|volume=5|pages=1\u20137|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230201847/http://www.chp.gov.hk/files/pdf/ncd_watch_aug2012.pdf|archivedate=2015-12-30}}</ref> A study of 84,000 women, over a period of 26 years, finds that those with the highest intake of unprocessed red meat, have a 13% increased risk of CHD.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nUnprocessed red meat intake is tentatively associated with an increased risk of [[type II diabetes]], but the link is weaker and less certain than the link between processed red meat and diabetes.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Micha|first1=Renata|last2=Michas|first2=Georgios|last3=Mozaffarian|first3=Dariush|title=Unprocessed Red and Processed Meats and Risk of Coronary Artery Disease and Type 2 Diabetes \u2013 An Updated Review of the Evidence|journal=Current Atherosclerosis Reports|date=22 September 2012|volume=14|issue=6|pages=515\u2013524|doi=10.1007/s11883-012-0282-8|pmid=23001745|pmc=3483430}}</ref> Other findings have suggested that the association may be due to [[saturated fat]], [[trans fat]] and [[dietary cholesterol]], rather than red meat per se.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Hu | first1 = F. B. | last2 = Van Dam | first2 = S. | last3 = Liu | first3 = R. M. | title = Diet and risk of Type II diabetes: the role of types of fat and carbohydrate | journal = Diabetologia | volume = 44 | issue = 7 | pages = 805\u2013817 | year = 2001 | pmid = 11508264 | doi = 10.1007/s001250100547| doi-access = free }}</ref> \n\n==== Cancer ====\n{{Prose|section|date=March 2020}}\n* In 2015, the [[International Agency for Research on Cancer]] of the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) classified ''red meat'' as \"probably carcinogenic to humans (Group 2A), based on limited evidence that the consumption of red meat causes cancer in humans and strong mechanistic evidence supporting a carcinogenic effect.\"<ref name=\"WHO-20151026\">{{cite web|title=Press release: IARC monographs evaluate consumption of red meat and processed meat |url=http://www.iarc.fr/en/media-centre/pr/2015/pdfs/pr240_E.pdf |publisher=[[International Agency for Research on Cancer]], World Health Organization|accessdate=26 October  2015|date=15 October 2015 }}</ref> \n\n* A 2011 study reported that for each additional 100g (up to a maximum of approximately 140g)<ref name=\"chan2011\">{{cite journal |last=Chan |first=DS |last2=Lau |first2=R |last3=Aune |first3=D |last4=Vieira |first4=R |last5=Greenwood |first5=DC |last6=Kampman |first6=E |last7=Norat |first7=T |date=2011-06-06 |title=Red and processed meat and colorectal cancer incidence: meta-analysis of prospective studies. |journal=PLOS ONE |volume=6 |issue=6 |pages= e20456|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0020456 |pmid=21674008 |quote=In non-linear models, colorectal cancer risk appears to increase almost linearly with increasing intake of red and processed meats up to approximately 140 g/day. Above this level, the risk increase is less pronounced.. |pmc=3108955|bibcode=2011PLoSO...620456C }}</ref> of red meat consumed per day, the risk of  [[colorectal cancer]] increased by 17%; there also appeared to be increased risk of [[pancreatic cancer]] and [[prostate cancer]] but the association was not as clear.<ref name=IARClancet>{{cite journal|last1=Bouvard|first1=V|display-authors=etal|last2=International Agency for Research on Cancer Monograph Working Group.|title=Carcinogenicity of consumption of red and processed meat.|journal=The Lancet. Oncology|date=December 2015|volume=16|issue=16|pages=1599\u2013600|pmid=26514947|doi=10.1016/s1470-2045(15)00444-1|url=https://www.statsarecool.com/data/uploads/journal-articles/who_declares_reds_meat_carcinogeniclancet_oct_2015.pdf}}</ref>  Put in perspective, in the UK, 56 out of 1000 people who eat the lowest amount of red meat will develop colorectal cancer (5.6%) while 66 out of 1000 high-red meat eaters will develop colorectal cancer (6.6%) (1.17 x 5.6 = 6.6).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://scienceblog.cancerresearchuk.org/2015/10/26/processed-meat-and-cancer-what-you-need-to-know/|title=Processed meat and cancer \u2013 what you need to know|website=Cancer Research UK - Science blog|access-date=2016-12-29|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170109195400/http://scienceblog.cancerresearchuk.org/2015/10/26/processed-meat-and-cancer-what-you-need-to-know/|archivedate=2017-01-09}}</ref>\n\n* A 2012 meta-analysis found an increased risk of gastric cancer with higher consumption of red or processed meat.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Zhu|first1=H|display-authors=etal|title=Red and processed meat intake is associated with higher gastric cancer risk: a meta-analysis of epidemiological observational studies.|journal=PLOS ONE|date=2013|volume=8|issue=8|pages=e70955|pmid=23967140|pmc=3743884|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0070955|bibcode=2013PLoSO...870955Z}}</ref>  Red meat itself contains certain factors that, under certain conditions, produce carcinogens like N-nitroso compounds (NOCs).<ref>{{cite web|title=Inherited Bowel Cancer|url=http://www.geneticseducation.nhs.uk/genetic-conditions-54/677-inherited-bowel-cancer-new|website=geneticseducation.nhs.uk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225011653/http://www.geneticseducation.nhs.uk/genetic-conditions-54/677-inherited-bowel-cancer-new|archivedate=2014-12-25}}</ref>\n\n* A 2016 literature review reported that for 100g or more per day of red meat consumed, the risk increased 11% for each of stroke and for breast cancer, 15% for cardiovascular mortality, 17% for colorectal cancer, and 19% for advanced prostate cancer.<ref name=Wolk2016rev>{{cite journal |last1=Wolk |first1=A |title=Potential health hazards of eating red meat. |journal=Journal of Internal Medicine |volume = 281|issue=2 |pages=106\u2013122 |date=6 September 2016 |pmid=27597529 |doi=10.1111/joim.12543 |df= }}</ref>\n\n* A 2017 review indicated there are numerous potential carcinogens of colorectal tissue in red meat, particularly those in processed red meat products, such as [[N-nitroso]] compounds, [[polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon]]s, and [[heterocyclic amine]]s.<ref name=\"jeyakumar\">{{cite journal | last=Jeyakumar | first=Arunan | last2=Dissabandara | first2=Lakal | last3=Gopalan | first3=Vinod | title=A critical overview on the biological and molecular features of red and processed meat in colorectal carcinogenesis | journal=Journal of Gastroenterology | volume=52 | issue=4 | date=1 April 2017 | issn=0944-1174 | pmid=27913919 | doi=10.1007/s00535-016-1294-x | pages=407\u2013418}}</ref>\n\n====Cardiovascular disease and diabetes====\nA 2017 [[systematic review]] and [[meta-analysis]] of [[clinical research]] on [[stroke]] outcomes associated with meat consumption showed that total meat consumption, red meat consumption, and processed red meat consumption increased the risk of stroke by 18%, 11%, and 17%, respectively, while consuming white meat (chicken) reduced the risk of stroke by 13%.<ref name=\"Kim\">{{cite journal | last=Kim | first=Kyuwoong | last2=Hyeon | first2=Junghyeon | last3=Lee | first3=Sang Ah | last4=Kwon | first4=Sung Ok | last5=Lee | first5=Hyejin | last6=Keum | first6=NaNa | last7=Lee | first7=Jong\u2010Koo | last8=Park | first8=Sang Min | title=Role of total, red, processed, and white meat consumption in stroke incidence and mortality: A systematic review and meta\u2010analysis of prospective cohort studies | journal=Journal of the American Heart Association | volume=6 | issue=9 | date=2017-09-22 | issn=2047-9980 | doi=10.1161/jaha.117.005983 | page=e005983|pmid=28855166|pmc=5634267}}</ref> Factors associated with increased stroke risk from consuming red meat include [[saturated fat]]s that increase levels of [[blood cholesterol]], [[LDL cholesterol]], [[triglyceride]]s, and [[heme]] [[iron]], which may precipitate [[atherogenesis]] in cerebral arteries, leading to stroke.<ref name=Kim/>\n\nA 2017 review found that consuming a one-half serving of red meat daily was not associated with [[cardiovascular disease]] [[risk factor]]s, such as total cholesterol, LDL, and [[hypertension]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=O'Connor |first1=LE |last2=Kim |first2=JE |last3=Campbell |first3=WW |title=Total red meat intake of \u22650.5 servings/d does not negatively influence cardiovascular disease risk factors: a systemically searched meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials. |journal=American Journal of Clinical Nutrition |date=January 2017 |volume=105 |issue=1 |pages=57\u201369 |doi=10.3945/ajcn.116.142521 |pmid=27881394|pmc=5183733 }}</ref> One study estimated that \u201csubstitutions of one serving of nuts, low-fat dairy, and whole grains per day for one serving of red meat per day were associated with a 16\u201335% lower risk of type 2 diabetes\u201d.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Pan | first1 = A. | last2 = Sun | first2 = Q. | last3 = Bernstein | first3 = A. M. | last4 = Schulze | first4 = M. B. | last5 = Manson | first5 = J. E. | last6 = Willett | first6 = W. C. | last7 = Hu | first7 = F. B. | doi = 10.3945/ajcn.111.018978 | title = Red meat consumption and risk of type 2 diabetes: 3 cohorts of US adults and an updated meta-analysis | journal = American Journal of Clinical Nutrition | volume = 94 | issue = 4 | pages = 1088\u20131096 | year = 2011 | pmid =  21831992| pmc =3173026 }}</ref>\n\nRed meat consumption has been associated with higher [[fasting glucose]] and [[insulin]] concentrations, which are risk factors for [[type 2 diabetes]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fretts |first1=Amanda |title=Consumption of meat is associated with higher fasting glucose and insulin concentrations regardless of glucose and insulin genetic risk scores: a meta-analysis of 50,345 Caucasians |journal=American Journal of Clinical Nutrition |date=November 2015 |volume=102 |issue=5 |pages=1266\u201378 |pmid=26354543|pmc=4625584 |doi=10.3945/ajcn.114.101238 }}</ref> Daily consumption of 85 grams of red meat and 35 grams of processed red meat products by European and American consumers increased their risk of type 2 diabetes by 18-36%, while a diet of abstinence of red meat consuming whole grains, vegetables, fruits, and dairy was associated with an 81% reduced risk of diabetes.<ref name=\"Schwing\">{{cite journal | last=Schwingshackl | first=Lukas | last2=Hoffmann | first2=Georg | last3=Lampousi | first3=Anna-Maria | last4=Kn\u00fcppel | first4=Sven | last5=Iqbal | first5=Khalid | last6=Schwedhelm | first6=Carolina | last7=Bechthold | first7=Angela | last8=Schlesinger | first8=Sabrina | last9=Boeing | first9=Heiner | title=Food groups and risk of type 2 diabetes mellitus: a systematic review and meta-analysis of prospective studies | journal=European Journal of Epidemiology| volume=32 | issue=5 | date=2017-04-10 | issn=0393-2990 | doi=10.1007/s10654-017-0246-y | pages=363\u2013375|pmid=28397016|pmc=5506108}}</ref>\n\n====Cooking====\n[[File:Delmonico_steak.jpg|thumb|right|Meat with a dark exterior, common in high temperature cooking]]\nCooking any meat at a high temperature or smoking meat produces [[carcinogen]]ic [[polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon]] compounds (PAHs) and [[heterocyclic amines]] (HCAs).<ref>{{cite web|title=Chemicals in Meat Cooked at High Temperatures and Cancer Risk|url=http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/factsheet/Risk/cooked-meats|website=National Cancer Institute|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106080003/http://www.cancer.gov/cancertopics/factsheet/Risk/cooked-meats|archivedate=2011-11-06|year=2018}}</ref> The subgroups of heterocyclic amines compounds are amino-dimethylimidazo-quinoxaline (MelQx), amino-dimethylimidazo-quinoxaline (DiMelQx), and amino-methyl-phenylimidazo-pyridine (PhIP), which are mostly formed when meat is cooked at high temperatures.  [[Benzo(a)pyrene|Benzo[a]pyrene]] (B[a]P) is another compound found in meat cooked at extremely high temperatures. Likely because of these factors, marinating fresh lean red meat and thoroughly cooking it at a low temperature will reduce the production of carcinogenic compounds and thereby lower the risk of [[colorectal cancer]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Marinades Reduce Heterocyclic Amines from Primitive Food Preparation Techniques|url=http://naturalmedicinejournal.com/journal/2010-07/marinades-reduce-heterocyclic-amines-primitive-food-preparation-techniques|publisher=Schor J|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225012038/http://naturalmedicinejournal.com/journal/2010-07/marinades-reduce-heterocyclic-amines-primitive-food-preparation-techniques|archivedate=2014-12-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Seer Stat Fact Sheets: Colon and Rectum Cancer|url=http://seer.cancer.gov/statfacts/html/colorect.html|website=Seer.cancer.gov|publisher=National Cancer Institute|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140624140833/http://seer.cancer.gov/statfacts/html/colorect.html|archivedate=2014-06-24}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Food}}\n* [[White meat]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.iarc.fr/en/media-centre/pr/2015/pdfs/pr240_E.pdf International Association for Research on Cancer, press release 240, 26. October 2015]\n*[http://www.iarc.fr/en/media-centre/iarcnews/pdf/Monographs-Q&A.pdf IARC Monographs Q&A]\n*[http://www.iarc.fr/en/media-centre/iarcnews/pdf/Monographs-Q&A_Vol114.pdf IARC Monographs Q&A on the carcinogenicity of the consumption of red meat and processed meat.]\n\n{{sisterlinks}}\n\n{{Meat product navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Red Meat}}\n[[Category:Meat]]\n[[Category:IARC Group 2A carcinogens]]\n\n[[sv:K\u00f6tt#R\u00f6tt och vitt k\u00f6tt]]\n", "name_user": "Crywalt", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_meat"}
{"title_page": "Tormenta FC", "text_new": "{{short description|American soccer club in Statesboro, Georgia}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = South Georgia Tormenta FC\n| image = Tormenta FC logo.svg\n| image_size = 180px\n| caption = \n| fullname = South Georgia Tormenta Football Club\n| founded = {{start date and years ago|2015|||mf=yes}}\n| dissolved = \n| stadium = [[Eagle Field (Georgia Southern)|Eagle Field at Erk Russell Athletic Park]]<br>[[Statesboro, Georgia]]\n| capacity = 3,500\n| coordinates = \n| owntitle = Co-Owners\n| owner = {{ubl|Darin Van Tassell|Netra Van Tassell|Jeff Spencer}}\n| chrtitle = \n| chairman = \n| mgrtitle = Head Coach\n| manager = John Miglarese\n| league = [[USL League One]]\n| season = [[2019 USL League One season|2019]]\n| position = 6th Place<br>Playoffs: DNQ\n| website = http://www.tormentafc.com\n| kit_alt1 = \n| pattern_la1 = _tormenta19h\n| pattern_b1 = _tormenta19h\n| pattern_ra1 = _tormenta19h\n| pattern_sh1 = _tormenta19h\n| pattern_so1 = _tormenta19h\n| leftarm1 = 0F1D41\n| body1 = 0F1D41\n| rightarm1 = 0F1D41\n| shorts1 = 0F1D41\n| socks1 = 0F1D41\n| kit_alt2 = \n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2 = \n| pattern_ra2 = \n| pattern_sh2 = \n| pattern_so2 = \n| leftarm2 = \n| body2 = \n| rightarm2 = \n| shorts2 = \n| socks2 = \n| kit_alt3 = \n| pattern_la3 = \n| pattern_b3 = \n| pattern_ra3 = \n| pattern_sh3 = \n| pattern_so3 = \n| pattern_name3 = \n| leftarm3 = \n| body3 = \n| rightarm3 = \n| shorts3 = \n| socks3 = \n| current = 2020 Tormenta FC season\n}}\n\n'''South Georgia Tormenta FC''' is an American [[association football|soccer]] organization based in [[Statesboro, Georgia]], United States. Founded in 2015, the club fields a professional team in [[USL League One]], the third tier of the [[American Soccer Pyramid]], as well as the pre-professional [[USL League Two]]. The team colors are Midnight Navy, Sky Blue, Silver and Magenta. The team's crest shows an Ibis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uslpdl.com/home/888862.html|title=PDL Awards Franchise to Statesboro, Georgia|publisher=Premier Development League (PDL)|date=August 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uslpdl.com/home/898346.html|title=Tormenta FC Arrives in South Georgia|publisher=Premier Development League (PDL)|date=October 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nSouth Georgia Tormenta FC was founded in 2015 making it Statesboro's first pro team in any sport in 60 years, since the [[Statesboro Pilots]] of baseball's [[Georgia State League]] folded in 1955. Owned by Tormenta FC LLC, the operations of the franchise are steered by Darin Van Tassell and Netra Van Tassell. The word \"tormenta\" means \"storm\" in Spanish.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tormentafc.com/faqs|title=Frequently Asked Questions|website=Tormentafc.com|accessdate=February 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nOn May 21, 2016, Tormenta FC hosted its inaugural home match against the [[Carolina Dynamo]] in front of 3,105 fans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tormentafc.com/news_article/show/651560?referrer_id=2300356|title=History in the making for Tormenta|date=23 May 2016|website=Tormentafc.com}}</ref>\n\nTormenta FC won their first match in club history on June 16, 2016 against the [[Charlotte Eagles]] in a 2\u20130 decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tormentafc.com/news_article/show/661547?referrer_id=2006916|title=Tormenta FC Secures First Win|last=Colin|date=17 June 2016|publisher=}}</ref> The club then followed up that victory with a second consecutive win on June 18, 2016 by defeating the [[Carolina Dynamo]] 1\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tormentafc.com/news_article/show/662257?referrer_id=2006916|title=Tormenta FC moves up in Ranking with Two Consecutive Wins On The Road|date=20 June 2016|website=Tormentafc.com}}</ref> On June 23, 2016, Tormenta FC not only scored their first ever home goal, but the team managed to win their first home match as well; a 1\u20130 victory over [[Southern West Virginia King's Warriors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statesboroherald.com/section/3/article/74927/|title=Tormenta comes through in the clutch|website=Statesboroherald.com}}</ref>\n\nTormenta had a five-game win streak snapped in a 2\u20131 defeat against the King's Warriors on July 2, 2016. \n\nThe club finished 6th out of 8 in the South Atlantic Division.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uslleaguetwo.com/standings/show/2353458?subseason=278141|title=Standings - 2016 Regular Season - South Georgia Tormenta FC 2|website=www.uslleaguetwo.com|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\nOn January 25, 2018, South Georgia Tormenta FC was announced as the first founding member of [[USL League One]] for 2019. The team had an undefeated regular season in 2018, clinching the Deep South Division championship. Tormenta FC hosted the conference playoffs in Statesboro, Georgia.<ref>{{Cite Web|url=http://www.usld3.com/news_article/show/877210?referrer_id=3067499 |title=Tormenta FC joins USL Division III for 2019|date=January 25, 2018|accessdate=January 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 ===\nOn March 29, 2019, Tormenta FC hosted the inaugural match of [[USL League One]], winning 1\u20130 against the [[Greenville Triumph SC|Greenville Triumph]] and setting a new attendance record of 3,519.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tormentafc.com/news_article/show/1008446-post-game-notes-march-29-vs-greenville-triumph-sc|title=Post-Game Notes: March 29 vs Greenville Triumph SC|last=O'Donnell|first=Bernadette|date=2019-03-30|website=South Georgia Tormenta FC|language=en-us|access-date=2020-02-16}}</ref> After a successful start to the season that saw the team in second place, a second-half downturn with 2 wins in their last 16 matches brought them down to 6th place and out of a playoff spot.\n\n==Stadium==\nTormenta FC currently plays at [[Eagle Field (Georgia Southern)|Eagle Field]] at Erk Russell Park on the [[Georgia Southern University]] campus. Construction for a 5,300 seater [[soccer-specific stadium]] in Statesboro commenced on March 27, 2019, due for a 2021 completion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statesboroherald.com/local/tormenta-stadium-break-ground-march-27/|title=Tormenta Stadium to break ground March 27|website=Statesboroherald.com}}</ref><ref>https://www.wtoc.com/2019/10/24/tormenta-fc-owners-give-update-new-stadium-retail-shops/</ref>\n\n==Sponsorship==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#0F1D41; color:white; border:2px solid #FF00FF;;\" scope=\"col\"|Period\n! style=\"background:#0F1D41; color:white; border:2px solid #FF00FF;;\" scope=\"col\"|Kit manufacturer\n! style=\"background:#0F1D41; color:white; border:2px solid #FF00FF;;\" scope=\"col\"|Shirt sponsor\n|-\n| 2016\u20132018\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]]\n| Optim Orthopedics \n|-\n| 2019\u2013present\n| {{flagicon|GER}} [[Adidas]]\n| Optim Healthcare\n|-\n|}\n\n==Record==\n===Year-by-year===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Division\n!League\n!Regular Season\n!Playoffs\n!Open Cup\n|-\n|2016\n|4\n|[[2016 PDL season|USL PDL]]\n|5th, South Atlantic\n|''Did not qualify''\n|''Did not enter''\n|-\n|2017\n|4\n|[[2017 PDL season|USL PDL]]\n|4th, South Atlantic\n|''Did not qualify''\n|''Did not enter''\n|-\n|2018\n|4\n|[[2018 PDL season|USL PDL]]\n| style=\"background:#b3b7ff;\"|1st, Deep South\n|Conference Semifinals\n|[[2018 U.S. Open Cup|2nd Round]]\n|-\n|[[2019 South Georgia Tormenta FC season|2019]]\n|3\n|[[2019 USL League One season|USL1]]\n|6th\n|''Did not qualify''\n|[[2019 U.S. Open Cup|1st Round]]\n|}\n\n==Players and staff==\n===Current roster===\n{{updated|April 19, 2020|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tormentafc.com/2020roster|title=2020 USL League One Roster|website=tormentafc.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uslleagueone.com/south-georgia-tormenta-fc-roster|title=South Georgia Tormenta FC Roster &#124; uslleagueone.com|website=Uslleagueone.com}}</ref>}}\n<!----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n  -- Do NO