 |url=https://www.wjcl.com/article/historic-season-for-tormenta-fc-2-comes-to-an-end/28540744 |website=WJCL |accessdate=30 January 2020 |language=en |date=29 July 2019}}</ref> The 2 team also earned a spot in the [[2019 U.S. Open Cup]] from the first team's [[2018 PDL season|previous season results]] in the PDL and beat League One side [[Chattanooga Red Wolves SC]] in the first round before falling in the second to [[Nashville SC]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Popkin |first1=Jackson |title=A South Georgia Tormenta FC Guide to the 2019 U.S. Open Cup First Round |url=https://www.dirtysouthsoccer.com/2019/5/8/18534947/a-south-georgia-tormenta-fc-guide-to-the-2019-u-s-open-cup-first-round |website=Dirty South Soccer |accessdate=30 January 2020 |language=en |date=8 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Sullivan |first1=Tim |title=2019 US Open Cup Round 2: Nashville SC holds off pesky South Georgia Tormenta 2 |url=https://thecup.us/2019/05/15/2019-us-open-cup-round-2-nashville-sc-holds-off-pesky-south-georgia-tormenta-2/ |website=TheCup.us |accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Year-by-year===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Division\n!League\n!Regular Season\n!Playoffs\n!Open Cup\n|-\n|2019\n|4\n|[[2019 USL League Two season|USL2]]\n|style=\"background:#b3b7ff;\"|1st, Deep South\n|National Semifinals\n|[[2019 U.S. Open Cup|2nd Round]]\n|}\n\n====Staff====\n{{updated|September 17, 2018|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Tormenta_FC/status/1041688337671749632|title=Tormenta Nation, give a warm welcome to Ian Cameron! The Scottish native will be our PDL head coach this year as we not only try to win championships on the professional side but also the semi-professional side! Welcome to Statesboro coach! #ProSocc3r #USLD3 #PDL @USLPDL @USL_D3pic.twitter.com/TbgN9s7gD0|first=Tormenta|last=FC|website=Twitter.com|date=September 17, 2018}}</ref>}}\n* {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Ian Cameron (footballer)|Ian Cameron]] \u2013 ''Head Coach''\n*Tom Morris - ''Assistant Coach''\n\n==Honors==\n===Tormenta FC===\n====USL League Two====\n*'''Deep South Division Champion''': 2018\n\n===Tormenta FC 2===\n====USL League Two====\n*'''Deep South Division Champion''': 2019\n*'''Southern Conference Champion''': 2019\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{USL League One}}\n{{USL League Two}}\n{{Georgia Sports}}\n\n[[Category:Tormenta FC| ]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 2015]]\n[[Category:USL League Two teams]]\n[[Category:Soccer clubs in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:2015 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:USL League One teams]]\n", "name_user": "Gphhj", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCurrent roster", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tormenta_FC"}
{"title_page": "Georgian Terrace Hotel", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2020}}\n{{Infobox hotel\n| hotel_name = Georgian Terrace Hotel\n| image = Hotels_around_Fabulous_Fox_Theater_cropped.jpg\n| caption = Georgian Terrace Hotel in 2008\n| location = 659 Peachtree Street NE,<br />[[Atlanta]]\n| opening_date = 1911 (addition in 1991)\n| developer = Joseph F. Gatins, Jr\n| architect = Original hotel: [[William Lee Stoddart]]<br />Addition: Smallwood, Reynolds, Stewart, Stewart and Associates\n| operator = Chesapeake Hospitality\n| owner = Southerly Hotels\n| number_of_restaurants = 2\n| number_of_rooms = 326\n| floors = 10 stories in 1911<br />19-story wing added in 1991\n| website = [http://www.thegeorgianterrace.com Official site]\n{{Infobox NRHP | name =Georgian Terrace Hotel \n  | partof = Fox Theatre Historic District\n  | embed = yes\n  | nrhp_type = cp\n  | nocat = yes\n  | image =   | caption = \n  | location=   \n  | coordinates = \n  | locmapin = Atlanta, Georgia\n  | area =\n  | architect=[[William Lee Stoddart]]\n  | architecture= [[Moorish Revival]], [[Beaux-Arts style]], [[Neo-Renaissance|Renaissance Revival]]\n  | added = October 7, 1978<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref>\n  | governing_body = Private\n  | partof_refnum= 78003178\n| designated_other1_name = Atlanta Landmark Building\n| designated_other1_date = June 13, 1990\n| designated_other1_abbr = ALB\n| designated_other1_link = List of historic buildings and districts designated by the City of Atlanta\n| designated_other1_color= #aaccff\n}}\n}}\nThe '''Georgian Terrace Hotel''' in [[Midtown Atlanta]], part of the [[Fox Theatre Historic District]], was designed by architect [[William Lee Stoddart]] in a [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux-Arts]] style that was intended to evoke the architecture of Paris. Construction commenced on July 21, 1910, and ended on September 8, 1911, and the hotel opened on October 2, 1911.<ref name='CityofAtlanta'>{{cite web |url=http://www.atlantaga.gov/government/urbandesign_georgianterr.aspx |title=The Georgian Terrace Hotel |accessdate=2010-02-20 |year=2010 |work=City of Atlanta Online |publisher=City of [[Atlanta]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528035941/http://www.atlantaga.gov/government/urbandesign_georgianterr.aspx# |archive-date=2010-05-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The George C. Fuller Construction Company was contractor, and the developer was Joseph F. Gatins, Jr.<ref name='CityofAtlanta'/>\n\nA 19-story wing, designed by Smallwood, Reynolds, Stewart, Stewart and Associates, was added in 1991.<ref name='Craig'>{{cite book | last = Craig | first = Robert M. | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Atlanta Architecture: Art Deco to Modern Classic, 1929-1959 | publisher = Pelican Publishing Company, Inc. | year = 1995 | location = Gretna, Louisiana | page = 78 | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-0-88289-961-9 }}</ref><ref name='Emporis'>{{cite web|url=http://www.emporis.com/application/?nav=building&id=121218&lng=3 |title=Georgian Terrace Apartments |accessdate=2010-02-20 |work=Emporis.com }}</ref> A major renovation was completed in 2009.\n\nThe Georgian Terrace is a member of [[Historic Hotels of America]], the official program of the [[National Trust for Historic Preservation]].\n\n==Architecture==\nThe original 10-story Georgian Terrace Hotel was designed to conform to Atlanta's early [[tram|trolley]] rail lines that met at the corner of [[Peachtree Street]] and [[Ponce de Leon Avenue]]. It was one of the first hotels built outside of the city's downtown business district in a then residential neighborhood, which had been land originally owned by [[Richard Peters (Atlanta)|Richard Peters]].\n\nAt a cost of $500,000, the hotel was built of butter-colored brick, marble, and limestone in the Beaux-Arts style as a Southern interpretation of the Parisian hotel. The hotel features classical architectural details, such as [[turret]]ed corners, floor-to-ceiling [[Palladian architecture|Palladian-styled]] windows, and wide wrap-around columned [[terrace (architecture)|terraces]]. The hotel is largely unadorned until its [[cornice]] line, which is embellished by highly-decorative [[terracotta]].\n\nThe Peachtree Street fa\u00e7ade is composed of a two-story high window arcade set under a wide cornice supported on narrow [[pilaster]]s and has a centered [[portico]]. The Ponce de Leon Avenue fa\u00e7ade features a portico held up by four columns that rest on a [[Rustication (architecture)|rusticated]], arcaded base. This portico was used as the Ladies Carriage entrance and provided access to the main hotel; the caf\u00e9 terrace, which held exotic plants, tables, and chairs to resemble cafes in Europe; and a lower level of the hotel, which at one time housed the WAKE 1340AM radio station.\n\nOriginally, the hotel had a prominent, tile-buttressed, shed roof cornice that was supported by ornamented, paired brackets, but this element was removed in 1945.\n\nThe inside of the hotel was decorated with crystal and Italian-bronze [[chandelier]]s, white marble columns, ornate pilasters, paneled walls, elliptical staircases, and Italian-tiled floors. In addition to guest rooms, the hotel housed the Winter Garden, the Terrace Garden Lounging Room, which was almost entirely enclosed in glass, the Terrace Restaurant Grill Room, general management offices, an elevator, telephone booths, a curio booth, an \"oak-mission\" decorated [[Rathskeller]], barber shops, a manicure parlor, and an ornate ballroom that was the setting for the 1939 ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone with the Wind]]'' Gala.\n\nAll of the hotel's original furniture and interior furnishings were from M. Rich and Brothers Co., later [[Rich's (department store)|Rich's]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">''Atlanta Historic Resources Workbook'' by the Atlanta Urban Design Commission, September 1981</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">''AIA Guide to the Architecture of Atlanta'': University of Georgia Press, 1993</ref><ref name=\"Commercial District Tour Guide PC\">Atlanta Preservation Center's ''SoNo/Midtown Commercial District Tour Guide'': APC, 2009</ref><ref name=\"atlantaga.gov\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.atlantaga.gov/government/urbandesign_georgianterr.aspx/# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-02-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528035941/http://www.atlantaga.gov/government/urbandesign_georgianterr.aspx# |archive-date=2010-05-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceC\">''The Ponce Lobby'' by Richard Flinn, Director of Restoration for The Fox Theatre; 1981?, [Atlanta?], Ga.: n.p.</ref><ref>''Rich's of Atlanta: The Story of a Store since 1867'' by Henry Givens Baker, 1953, Foote and Davies</ref>\n\n==History==\nOn October 2, 1911, thousands of guests from Atlanta and other cities attended the opening night ceremonies of the Georgian Terrace Hotel, where they were entertained by a costumed-Spanish orchestra performing in the Grand Ballroom. Immediately, guests and the press dubbed the hotel as a \"distinct step forward in Southern hoteldom\" and a \"Parisian hotel on a noted boulevard in a metropolitan city\". Over subsequent decades, the hotel would be referred to as the \"Grand Old Lady of Peachtree\".<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/>\n\nSince its opening, the hotel has been the place for numerous historical events and housed several prominent guests, including [[Clark Gable]], [[Tallulah Bankhead]], [[Calvin Coolidge]], [[John J. Pershing]], [[Walt Disney]], and [[F. Scott Fitzgerald]].\n\nStarting in 1913, famous Italian tenor [[Enrico Caruso]] along with members of [[The Metropolitan Opera]] used the hotel as their Atlanta headquarters when they came yearly to the city to perform in spring concerts. Once the [[Fox Theatre (Atlanta, Georgia)|Fox Theatre]] opened across the street from the hotel in 1929, traffic on Peachtree Street would be stopped and a red carpet rolled from the door of the hotel to the theatre entrance, allowing the opera stars and other celebrities staying at the hotel to make a grand entrance into the theatre before their shows started.\n\n[[File:Front of Georgian Terrace.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Historic Front Entrance]]\nIn the 1920s, [[Arthur Murray]], who was then a student at [[Georgia Tech]], started teaching dance classes in the hotel's Grand Ballroom. This enterprise eventually spawned his franchised-branded dance lesson business. In 1926, Georgia's chief investigator for the Solicitor General, Bert Donaldson, was murdered at the hotel. It was thought that this planned \"hit\" was evidence of Atlanta's underworld connections to [[organized crime]].\n\nIn 1935, [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]] editor Harold Latham decided to stay at the hotel while scouting the Atlanta area for new writers and manuscripts. While in town, he met Peggy Mitchell Marsh, whom he was introduced to through a mutual acquaintance. This mutual acquaintance also had told Latham that Marsh had written a novel about Atlanta during the [[American Civil War]] and [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction]]. After several failed attempts to obtain the manuscript from Marsh, Latham finally succeeded in getting it from her in the lobby of the hotel as he was about to depart for [[New Orleans]]. Upon handing the manuscript to Latham, Marsh said, \"If you really want it you may take it, but it is incomplete and unrevised.\"<ref>''Road to Tara: The Life of Margaret Mitchell'' by [[Anne Edwards]], 1983, Ticknor & Fields</ref> That unfinished novel was completed and published in 1936 as ''[[Gone with the Wind (novel)|Gone with the Wind]]'', winning the [[Pulitzer Prize]] in 1937. While she insisted on using her married name socially, the book was published under her maiden name of [[Margaret Mitchell]].<ref>''Road to Tara: The Life of Margaret Mitchell'' by Anne Edwards, 1983, Ticknor & Fields</ref>\n\nOn December 15, 1939, the Georgian Terrace Hotel's Grand Ballroom was the site of the ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone with the Wind]]'' Gala, whose attendees included [[Clark Gable]], [[Carole Lombard]], [[Vivien Leigh]], [[Laurence Olivier]], [[Olivia de Havilland]], [[Claudette Colbert]], [[Victor Fleming]], [[Louis B. Mayer]], [[David O. Selznick]], Margaret Mitchell, and several other notable guests.\n\nThe premiere of Gone with the Wind was in Atlanta in 1939. All of the stars and the Director of the movie (with the exception of Vivien Leigh and her lover at the time, Lawrence Olivier) stayed at the Georgian Terrace. The pre-premiere party was held at the hotel.\n\nContrary to popular belief, the premier showing of ''Gone With the Wind'' was not held at the Fox Theatre, but rather at [[Loew's Grand Theatre]] in downtown Atlanta. After the movie was screened there, its stars were ushered to the Georgian Terrace via a motorcade through a parade route on Peachtree Street.\n\nDuring the premiere of ''[[Song of the South]]'', which did take place at the Fox Theatre, [[Walt Disney]] stayed at the hotel. He returned to his room before the film started; unexpected audience reactions of any kind upset him and he preferred not to watch it with the audience.\n\nThe Georgian Terrace Hotel saw quite a few changes in the 1940s. It had become a residential hotel in 1945 and had been modernized with air-conditioning, new plumbing, and some interior changes. In 1945, the prominent tile-buttressed, shed roof cornice was removed.\n\nDuring the 1970s, the Grand Ballroom was turned into the [[Alex Cooley's Electric Ballroom|Electric Ballroom]] by concert promoters Alex Cooley and Mark Golob. Musical performers providing concerts at the hotel included [[Billy Joel]], [[Fleetwood Mac]], [[Patti Smith]], and [[Bruce Springsteen]]. The 1974 film ''[[Cockfighter]]'', starring [[Warren Oates]], features some scenes that were shot at the Georgian Terrace.<ref>''Warren Oates: a wild life'' by Susan Compo, 2009, The University Press of Kentucky</ref>\n\nBy 1981, revenues were in steady decline and the hotel closed its doors for the first time in its 70-year history. By the middle of that decade, the hotel had been boarded up and condemned. In 1986, however, the hotel was listed as a part of the \"Fox Theatre District\" on the National Register of Historic Places, which successfully blocked plans for its demolition.\n\nThe 1990s saw a rebirth of the hotel. In 1991, the hotel was converted into a luxury apartment building, and a new 19-story wing complete with a roof-top pool was built to resemble the original 10-story Beaux-Arts-style hotel. In 1997, the apartments were vacated, and the property reopened as a luxury hotel.\n\nThe first decade of the 21st century has seen two major renovations done at the hotel, one in 2000 and one in 2009, which included the opening of Livingston's Restaurant and Bar and Mims Caf\u00e9, both named after early Atlanta Mayor [[Livingston Mims]], who had built his house in 1879 on the corner where the hotel now stands.\n\nIn April 2007, the hotel was used by [[Robert Rodriguez]] to film a [[Bacardi|Bacardi Global Brands]] commercial for the European market titled [http://www.youtubekeep.com/watch-video/el-toro-starring-george-clooney-60sec-generic-s/122656/ El Toro]. This commercial starred [[George Clooney]], Jamie King, and [[Leonor Varela]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nIn the fall of 2010, the Georgian Terrace's Grand Ballroom was used as a filming location for the [[Jason Bateman]] and [[Ryan Reynolds]] film ''[[The Change-Up]]''. In the film, the ballroom doubles as Plantation Oaks Country Club.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/><ref name=\"Commercial District Tour Guide PC\"/><ref name=\"atlantaga.gov\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blogs.ajc.com/the-buzz/2010/11/22/another-ryan-reynolds-jason-bateman-sighting/ |title=''Atlanta Journal-Constitution'', November 24, 2010 |access-date=November 24, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125150536/http://blogs.ajc.com/the-buzz/2010/11/22/another-ryan-reynolds-jason-bateman-sighting/ |archive-date=November 25, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thegeorgianterrace.com/explore/hotel.cfm/# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-02-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100327215721/http://www.thegeorgianterrace.com/explore/hotel.cfm# |archive-date=2010-03-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|33.7726|-84.3846|type:landmark_region:US-GA|display=title}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Georgian Terrace Hotel}}\n*[http://www.thegeorgianterrace.com] Official website\n* [http://georgiainfo.galileo.usg.edu/topics/historical_markers/county/fulton/the-georgian-terrace-hotel The Georgian Terrace Hotel] historical marker\n\n{{Atlanta landmarks}}\n\n[[Category:Hotel buildings completed in 1911]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper hotels in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:William Lee Stoddart buildings]]\n[[Category:1911 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Historic district contributing properties in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Historic Hotels Worldwide]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2020}}\n{{Infobox hotel\n| hotel_name = Georgian Terrace Hotel\n| image = Hotels_around_Fabulous_Fox_Theater_cropped.jpg\n| caption = Georgian Terrace Hotel in 2008\n| location = 659 Peachtree Street NE,<br />[[Atlanta]]\n| opening_date = 1911 (addition in 1991)\n| developer = Joseph F. Gatins, Jr\n| architect = Original hotel: [[William Lee Stoddart]]<br />Addition: Smallwood, Reynolds, Stewart, Stewart and Associates\n| operator = Chesapeake Hospitality\n| owner = Southerly Hotels\n| number_of_restaurants = 2\n| number_of_rooms = 326\n| floors = 10 stories in 1911<br />19-story wing added in 1991\n| website = [http://www.thegeorgianterrace.com Official site]\n{{Infobox NRHP | name =Georgian Terrace Hotel \n  | partof = Fox Theatre Historic District\n  | embed = yes\n  | nrhp_type = cp\n  | nocat = yes\n  | image =   | caption = \n  | location=   \n  | coordinates = \n  | locmapin = Atlanta, Georgia\n  | area =\n  | architect=[[William Lee Stoddart]]\n  | architecture= [[Moorish Revival]], [[Beaux-Arts style]], [[Neo-Renaissance|Renaissance Revival]]\n  | added = October 7, 1978<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref>\n  | governing_body = Private\n  | partof_refnum= 78003178\n| designated_other1_name = Atlanta Landmark Building\n| designated_other1_date = June 13, 1990\n| designated_other1_abbr = ALB\n| designated_other1_link = List of historic buildings and districts designated by the City of Atlanta\n| designated_other1_color= #aaccff\n}}\n}}\nThe '''Georgian Terrace Hotel''' in [[Midtown Atlanta]], part of the [[Fox Theatre Historic District]], was designed by architect [[William Lee Stoddart]] in a [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux-Arts]] style that was intended to evoke the architecture of Paris. Construction commenced on July 21, 1910, and ended on September 8, 1911, and the hotel opened on October 2, 1911.<ref name='CityofAtlanta'>{{cite web |url=http://www.atlantaga.gov/government/urbandesign_georgianterr.aspx |title=The Georgian Terrace Hotel |accessdate=2010-02-20 |year=2010 |work=City of Atlanta Online |publisher=City of [[Atlanta]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528035941/http://www.atlantaga.gov/government/urbandesign_georgianterr.aspx# |archive-date=2010-05-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The George C. Fuller Construction Company was contractor, and the developer was Joseph F. Gatins, Jr.<ref name='CityofAtlanta'/>\n\nA 19-story wing, designed by Smallwood, Reynolds, Stewart, Stewart and Associates, was added in 1991.<ref name='Craig'>{{cite book | last = Craig | first = Robert M. | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Atlanta Architecture: Art Deco to Modern Classic, 1929-1959 | publisher = Pelican Publishing Company, Inc. | year = 1995 | location = Gretna, Louisiana | page = 78 | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-0-88289-961-9 }}</ref><ref name='Emporis'>{{cite web|url=http://www.emporis.com/application/?nav=building&id=121218&lng=3 |title=Georgian Terrace Apartments |accessdate=2010-02-20 |work=Emporis.com }}</ref> A major renovation was completed in 2009.\n\nThe Georgian Terrace is a member of Historic Hotels of America, the official program of the [[National Trust for Historic Preservation]].\n\n==Architecture==\nThe original 10-story Georgian Terrace Hotel was designed to conform to Atlanta's early [[tram|trolley]] rail lines that met at the corner of [[Peachtree Street]] and [[Ponce de Leon Avenue]]. It was one of the first hotels built outside of the city's downtown business district in a then residential neighborhood, which had been land originally owned by [[Richard Peters (Atlanta)|Richard Peters]].\n\nAt a cost of $500,000, the hotel was built of butter-colored brick, marble, and limestone in the Beaux-Arts style as a Southern interpretation of the Parisian hotel. The hotel features classical architectural details, such as [[turret]]ed corners, floor-to-ceiling [[Palladian architecture|Palladian-styled]] windows, and wide wrap-around columned [[terrace (architecture)|terraces]]. The hotel is largely unadorned until its [[cornice]] line, which is embellished by highly-decorative [[terracotta]].\n\nThe Peachtree Street fa\u00e7ade is composed of a two-story high window arcade set under a wide cornice supported on narrow [[pilaster]]s and has a centered [[portico]]. The Ponce de Leon Avenue fa\u00e7ade features a portico held up by four columns that rest on a [[Rustication (architecture)|rusticated]], arcaded base. This portico was used as the Ladies Carriage entrance and provided access to the main hotel; the caf\u00e9 terrace, which held exotic plants, tables, and chairs to resemble cafes in Europe; and a lower level of the hotel, which at one time housed the WAKE 1340AM radio station.\n\nOriginally, the hotel had a prominent, tile-buttressed, shed roof cornice that was supported by ornamented, paired brackets, but this element was removed in 1945.\n\nThe inside of the hotel was decorated with crystal and Italian-bronze [[chandelier]]s, white marble columns, ornate pilasters, paneled walls, elliptical staircases, and Italian-tiled floors. In addition to guest rooms, the hotel housed the Winter Garden, the Terrace Garden Lounging Room, which was almost entirely enclosed in glass, the Terrace Restaurant Grill Room, general management offices, an elevator, telephone booths, a curio booth, an \"oak-mission\" decorated [[Rathskeller]], barber shops, a manicure parlor, and an ornate ballroom that was the setting for the 1939 ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone with the Wind]]'' Gala.\n\nAll of the hotel's original furniture and interior furnishings were from M. Rich and Brothers Co., later [[Rich's (department store)|Rich's]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">''Atlanta Historic Resources Workbook'' by the Atlanta Urban Design Commission, September 1981</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">''AIA Guide to the Architecture of Atlanta'': University of Georgia Press, 1993</ref><ref name=\"Commercial District Tour Guide PC\">Atlanta Preservation Center's ''SoNo/Midtown Commercial District Tour Guide'': APC, 2009</ref><ref name=\"atlantaga.gov\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.atlantaga.gov/government/urbandesign_georgianterr.aspx/# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-02-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528035941/http://www.atlantaga.gov/government/urbandesign_georgianterr.aspx# |archive-date=2010-05-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceC\">''The Ponce Lobby'' by Richard Flinn, Director of Restoration for The Fox Theatre; 1981?, [Atlanta?], Ga.: n.p.</ref><ref>''Rich's of Atlanta: The Story of a Store since 1867'' by Henry Givens Baker, 1953, Foote and Davies</ref>\n\n==History==\nOn October 2, 1911, thousands of guests from Atlanta and other cities attended the opening night ceremonies of the Georgian Terrace Hotel, where they were entertained by a costumed-Spanish orchestra performing in the Grand Ballroom. Immediately, guests and the press dubbed the hotel as a \"distinct step forward in Southern hoteldom\" and a \"Parisian hotel on a noted boulevard in a metropolitan city\". Over subsequent decades, the hotel would be referred to as the \"Grand Old Lady of Peachtree\".<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/>\n\nSince its opening, the hotel has been the place for numerous historical events and housed several prominent guests, including [[Clark Gable]], [[Tallulah Bankhead]], [[Calvin Coolidge]], [[John J. Pershing]], [[Walt Disney]], and [[F. Scott Fitzgerald]].\n\nStarting in 1913, famous Italian tenor [[Enrico Caruso]] along with members of [[The Metropolitan Opera]] used the hotel as their Atlanta headquarters when they came yearly to the city to perform in spring concerts. Once the [[Fox Theatre (Atlanta, Georgia)|Fox Theatre]] opened across the street from the hotel in 1929, traffic on Peachtree Street would be stopped and a red carpet rolled from the door of the hotel to the theatre entrance, allowing the opera stars and other celebrities staying at the hotel to make a grand entrance into the theatre before their shows started.\n\n[[File:Front of Georgian Terrace.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Historic Front Entrance]]\nIn the 1920s, [[Arthur Murray]], who was then a student at [[Georgia Tech]], started teaching dance classes in the hotel's Grand Ballroom. This enterprise eventually spawned his franchised-branded dance lesson business. In 1926, Georgia's chief investigator for the Solicitor General, Bert Donaldson, was murdered at the hotel. It was thought that this planned \"hit\" was evidence of Atlanta's underworld connections to [[organized crime]].\n\nIn 1935, [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]] editor Harold Latham decided to stay at the hotel while scouting the Atlanta area for new writers and manuscripts. While in town, he met Peggy Mitchell Marsh, whom he was introduced to through a mutual acquaintance. This mutual acquaintance also had told Latham that Marsh had written a novel about Atlanta during the [[American Civil War]] and [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction]]. After several failed attempts to obtain the manuscript from Marsh, Latham finally succeeded in getting it from her in the lobby of the hotel as he was about to depart for [[New Orleans]]. Upon handing the manuscript to Latham, Marsh said, \"If you really want it you may take it, but it is incomplete and unrevised.\"<ref>''Road to Tara: The Life of Margaret Mitchell'' by [[Anne Edwards]], 1983, Ticknor & Fields</ref> That unfinished novel was completed and published in 1936 as ''[[Gone with the Wind (novel)|Gone with the Wind]]'', winning the [[Pulitzer Prize]] in 1937. While she insisted on using her married name socially, the book was published under her maiden name of [[Margaret Mitchell]].<ref>''Road to Tara: The Life of Margaret Mitchell'' by Anne Edwards, 1983, Ticknor & Fields</ref>\n\nOn December 15, 1939, the Georgian Terrace Hotel's Grand Ballroom was the site of the ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone with the Wind]]'' Gala, whose attendees included [[Clark Gable]], [[Carole Lombard]], [[Vivien Leigh]], [[Laurence Olivier]], [[Olivia de Havilland]], [[Claudette Colbert]], [[Victor Fleming]], [[Louis B. Mayer]], [[David O. Selznick]], Margaret Mitchell, and several other notable guests.\n\nThe premiere of Gone with the Wind was in Atlanta in 1939. All of the stars and the Director of the movie (with the exception of Vivien Leigh and her lover at the time, Lawrence Olivier) stayed at the Georgian Terrace. The pre-premiere party was held at the hotel.\n\nContrary to popular belief, the premier showing of ''Gone With the Wind'' was not held at the Fox Theatre, but rather at [[Loew's Grand Theatre]] in downtown Atlanta. After the movie was screened there, its stars were ushered to the Georgian Terrace via a motorcade through a parade route on Peachtree Street.\n\nDuring the premiere of ''[[Song of the South]]'', which did take place at the Fox Theatre, [[Walt Disney]] stayed at the hotel. He returned to his room before the film started; unexpected audience reactions of any kind upset him and he preferred not to watch it with the audience.\n\nThe Georgian Terrace Hotel saw quite a few changes in the 1940s. It had become a residential hotel in 1945 and had been modernized with air-conditioning, new plumbing, and some interior changes. In 1945, the prominent tile-buttressed, shed roof cornice was removed.\n\nDuring the 1970s, the Grand Ballroom was turned into the [[Alex Cooley's Electric Ballroom|Electric Ballroom]] by concert promoters Alex Cooley and Mark Golob. Musical performers providing concerts at the hotel included [[Billy Joel]], [[Fleetwood Mac]], [[Patti Smith]], and [[Bruce Springsteen]]. The 1974 film ''[[Cockfighter]]'', starring [[Warren Oates]], features some scenes that were shot at the Georgian Terrace.<ref>''Warren Oates: a wild life'' by Susan Compo, 2009, The University Press of Kentucky</ref>\n\nBy 1981, revenues were in steady decline and the hotel closed its doors for the first time in its 70-year history. By the middle of that decade, the hotel had been boarded up and condemned. In 1986, however, the hotel was listed as a part of the \"Fox Theatre District\" on the National Register of Historic Places, which successfully blocked plans for its demolition.\n\nThe 1990s saw a rebirth of the hotel. In 1991, the hotel was converted into a luxury apartment building, and a new 19-story wing complete with a roof-top pool was built to resemble the original 10-story Beaux-Arts-style hotel. In 1997, the apartments were vacated, and the property reopened as a luxury hotel.\n\nThe first decade of the 21st century has seen two major renovations done at the hotel, one in 2000 and one in 2009, which included the opening of Livingston's Restaurant and Bar and Mims Caf\u00e9, both named after early Atlanta Mayor [[Livingston Mims]], who had built his house in 1879 on the corner where the hotel now stands.\n\nIn April 2007, the hotel was used by [[Robert Rodriguez]] to film a [[Bacardi|Bacardi Global Brands]] commercial for the European market titled [http://www.youtubekeep.com/watch-video/el-toro-starring-george-clooney-60sec-generic-s/122656/ El Toro]. This commercial starred [[George Clooney]], Jamie King, and [[Leonor Varela]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nIn the fall of 2010, the Georgian Terrace's Grand Ballroom was used as a filming location for the [[Jason Bateman]] and [[Ryan Reynolds]] film ''[[The Change-Up]]''. In the film, the ballroom doubles as Plantation Oaks Country Club.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/><ref name=\"Commercial District Tour Guide PC\"/><ref name=\"atlantaga.gov\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blogs.ajc.com/the-buzz/2010/11/22/another-ryan-reynolds-jason-bateman-sighting/ |title=''Atlanta Journal-Constitution'', November 24, 2010 |access-date=November 24, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125150536/http://blogs.ajc.com/the-buzz/2010/11/22/another-ryan-reynolds-jason-bateman-sighting/ |archive-date=November 25, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thegeorgianterrace.com/explore/hotel.cfm/# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-02-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100327215721/http://www.thegeorgianterrace.com/explore/hotel.cfm# |archive-date=2010-03-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|33.7726|-84.3846|type:landmark_region:US-GA|display=title}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Georgian Terrace Hotel}}\n*[http://www.thegeorgianterrace.com] Official website\n* [http://georgiainfo.galileo.usg.edu/topics/historical_markers/county/fulton/the-georgian-terrace-hotel The Georgian Terrace Hotel] historical marker\n\n{{Atlanta landmarks}}\n\n[[Category:Hotel buildings completed in 1911]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper hotels in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:William Lee Stoddart buildings]]\n[[Category:1911 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Historic district contributing properties in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Historic Hotels Worldwide]]\n", "name_user": "Bubba73", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georgian_Terrace_Hotel"}
{"title_page": "Ursula (The Little Mermaid)", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Ursula (''The Little Mermaid'')}}  \n{{Infobox character\n| color              = #4f316a\n| name               = Ursula\n| series             = [[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]\n| image              = Ursula(TheLittleMermaid)character.png \n\n\n| caption            = \n| first              = ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'' (1989)\n| last               = \n| creator            = [[Ron Clements]]<br>[[John Musker]]\n| lbl1               = Based on\n| data1              = The Sea Witch from the [[Hans Christian Andersen]]'s [[The Little Mermaid|fairy tale]]\n| portrayer          = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Sherie Rene Scott]]<br>(''[[The Little Mermaid (musical)|Broadway musical]]'')\n*[[Queen Latifah]]<br>(''[[The Little Mermaid Live!]]'')}}\n| voice              = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Pat Carroll (actress)|Pat Carroll]] {{small|(as Ursula)}}<br>[[Jodi Benson]] {{small|(as Vanessa)}}<br>(''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'')\n*[[Whoopi Goldberg]]<br>(''[[Descendants 2]]'')}}\n| alias              = [[Vanessa]] {{small|(human alter-ego)}}\n| species            = [[Cecaelia]]\n| gender             = Female\n| occupation         = [[Magician (fantasy)|Sorceress]], [[Bargaining|faustian bargainer]]\n| affiliation        = [[List of Disney villains|Disney Villains]]\n| title              = The Sea Witch\n| relatives          = Unnamed father (dead) <br>Unnamed mother (dead) <br>[[Morgana (The Little Mermaid)|Morgana]] {{small|(younger sister)}}<br>Uma {{small|(daughter)}}\n| nationality        = Atlantican}}\n'''Ursula''' is a [[fiction]]al [[Character (arts)|character]] and the main [[Antagonist|antagonist]] of [[Walt Disney Pictures]]' 28th animated feature film ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'' (1989). Voiced by American actress [[Pat Carroll (actress)|Pat Carroll]], Ursula is a villainous [[sea witch]] who offers a [[mermaid]] princess named [[Ariel (Disney character)|Ariel]] in exchange to trade her voice for a pair of human legs, at first appearing to be providing the character with an opportunity to become human by temporarily transforming her into one so that she may earn the love of [[List of Disney's The Little Mermaid characters|Prince Eric]] within three days. However, Ursula is, in fact, determined to sabotage Ariel's chances so that she can ultimately replace [[King Triton (The Little Mermaid)|King Triton]] as ruler over Atlantica.\n\nCreated by directors and screenwriters [[Ron Clements]] and [[John Musker]], Ursula is based on the sea witch character who appears in the fairy tale \"[[The Little Mermaid]]\" by [[Hans Christian Andersen]]. However, her minor role was greatly expanded into that of a much more prominent villain for the film. Disney had struggled to cast Ursula for a year, during which the role was well sought after by several coveted television actresses at the time. Clements and Musker disagreed with lyricist [[Howard Ashman]] about who should voice the character. While the directors had written the role with [[Bea Arthur]] in mind, Ashman intended to offer it to [[soap opera]] star [[Joan Collins]]; both actresses rejected the part. When Ashman cast his second choice, Broadway actress [[Elaine Stritch]], as Ursula, both stage veterans disagreed about the manner in which Ursula's song \"[[Poor Unfortunate Souls]]\" would be performed, and [[Pat Carroll (actress)|Pat Carroll]] was finally hired to replace Stritch after Ashman fired her. Deepening her own voice for the role, Carroll based her performance on a combination of [[William Shakespeare|Shakespearean]] actresses and [[Car salesman|car salespeople]].\n\nAnimated by [[Ruben A. Aquino]], Ursula's original design was inspired by several different [[Marine biology|sea creatures]], including [[manta ray]]s and [[Scorpaeniformes|scorpion fish]], before Clements finally decided to base the character on an [[octopus]]; her number of [[tentacle]]s was reduced from eight to six for financial reasons. Ursula's appearance was also inspired by American actor and drag queen [[Divine (performer)|Divine]]. When ''The Little Mermaid'' was first released in 1989, Ursula was immediately embraced as one of Disney's best villains, and continues to be ranked highly among the studio's greatest by the media. Praised for being humorous and frightening, the character has garnered positive reviews from film critics, some of whom dubbed her Disney's strongest villain in decades. Meanwhile, Carroll's performance has garnered similar acclaim to the point that the role has eclipsed her previous body of work, ultimately becoming virtually synonymous with the character. \u2018This one longing to be thinner this one wants to get the girl do I help them yes indeed \n    Poor Unfortunate Souls \nSorry I was bored in quarantine\n\n==Development==\n\n===Conception and writing===\nAt the behest of Disney executives [[Michael Eisner]] and [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]], director and screenwriter [[Ron Clements]] was among several filmmakers instructed to research new story ideas that could potentially be adapted into the studio's next major animated film release.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.beliefnet.com/columnists/moviemom/2013/09/interview-ron-clements-john-musker-little-mermaid-disney.html|title=Interview: Ron Clements and John Musker of \"The Little Mermaid\"|last=Minow|first=Nell|date=|website=Beliefnet|publisher=Beliefnet, Inc|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Clements first discovered [[Hans Christian Andersen]]'s classic fairy tale \"[[The Little Mermaid]]\" at a local bookstore, and began deliberating why Disney had never attempted to adapt the story before.<ref name=\":2\" /> Clements eventually learned that [[Walt Disney]] himself had actually attempted to adapt the fairy tale into a feature-length animated film as early as the 1930s,<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moviefone.com/2014/11/14/the-little-mermaid-facts/|title='The Little Mermaid' Facts: 25 Things You Didn't Know About the Disney Masterpiece|last=Susman|first=Gary|date=November 14, 2014|website=Moviefone|publisher=Aol Inc|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> but the project was ultimately shelved due in part to its sad ending.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2015/03/15/10-things-you-probably-didnt-know-about-the-little-mermaid-5104832/|title=10 things you probably didn\u2019t know about The Little Mermaid|last=Duncan|first=Amy|date=March 15, 2010|website=Metro|publisher=|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> Clements suggested \"The Little Mermaid\" to Katzenberg, who finally [[Green-light|green-lit]] it after having first rejected it.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nHardly present in Andersen's original story,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emgn.com/entertainment/15-exciting-facts-about-the-little-mermaid-you-never-knew/|title=15 Exciting Facts About The Little Mermaid You Never Knew!|last=|first=|date=|website=EMGN|publisher=|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> the [[sea witch]] is not a prominent character and lacks a [[proper name]].<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://ohmy.disney.com/movies/2014/08/16/15-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-little-mermaid/|title=15 THINGS YOU DIDN\u2019T KNOW ABOUT THE LITTLE MERMAID|last=Brandon|first=Emily|date=2014|website=Oh My Disney|publisher=Disney|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Among Clements' ideas to alter the story, the filmmaker decided to \"make the witch more of a villain\", describing Ursula as \"a fun character to develop\" into such.<ref name=\":2\" /> In Andersen's tale, the sea witch is not a villain as much as she is \"a disreputable mermaid.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.disneyvillains.net/Ursula.php|title=Ursula \u2013 The Little Mermaid (1989)|last=|first=|date=|website=Disney Villains|publisher=Disney Villains|access-date=April 20, 2016}}</ref> JR Thorpe of ''[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]'' agreed that, in Andersen's story, \"The sea witch isn't the enemy\". Instead, \"[[Human nature|human ... nature]] is.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/65813-9-ways-the-original-little-mermaid-by-hans-christian-andersen-is-actually-seriously-disturbing|title=9 Ways The Original 'Little Mermaid' By Hans Christian Andersen Is Actually Seriously Disturbing|last=Thorpe|first=JR|date=February 25, 2015|website=Bustle|publisher=|access-date=April 22, 2016}}</ref> While the original sea witch is willing to help the little mermaid despite the fact that she openly disagrees with her motives, Ursula is only interested in helping Ariel in the hopes of ultimately overthrowing her father.<ref name=\":21\" /> Emma James of ''[[Teen Ink]]'' observed that in addition to giving the character the name \"Ursula\", the studio \"changed her role as a catalyst in the tale, and morphed her actions into those of an antagonist.\"<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.teenink.com/nonfiction/academic/article/586214/The-Evolution-of-the-Little-Mermaid/|title=The Evolution of the Little Mermaid|last=James|first=Emma|date=|website=Teen Ink|publisher=Emerson Media|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> Unlike the sea witch, Ursula deliberately intervenes in an attempt to keep the mermaid from success.<ref name=\":41\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vjdQBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA69&dq=ursula+matriarchy+disney&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj9ifCdzoPNAhVNNFIKHbTfDZUQ6AEIMDAE#v=onepage&q=ursula%20matriarchy%20disney&f=false|title=Emerson Goes to the Movies: Individualism in Walt Disney Company's Post-1989 Animated Films|last=Fruzi\u0144ska|first=Justyna|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|year=2014|isbn=9781443869157|location=United Kingdom|pages=69}}</ref>\n\nLyricist, producer and writer [[Howard Ashman]] had originally envisioned Ursula's relationship with [[King Triton (The Little Mermaid)|King Triton]] as a [[soap opera]], and thus drew inspiration from soap opera actress [[Joan Collins]].<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/67862/10-disney-characters-who-were-almost-voiced-lister|title=10 Disney Characters Who Were Almost Voiced By an A-Lister|last=Malach|first=Maggie|date=August 28, 2015|website=Mental Floss|publisher=Mental Floss, Inc|access-date=April 2, 2016}}</ref> Ursula was originally conceived as Triton's sister,<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://ca.movies.yahoo.com/blogs/wide-screen/5-disney-villains-who-deserve-their-own-movies-181045442.html|title=5 Disney Villains Who Deserve Their Own Movies|last=Perkins|first=Will|date=May 27, 2014|website=Yahoo! Movies|publisher=|access-date=April 28, 2016}}</ref> which would have naturally made the character Ariel's aunt,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/inarelationshipwithpizza/17things-you-probably-didnt-know-about-the-littl-7shb|title=17 Things You Probably Didn\u2019t Know About Disney\u2019s \"The Little Mermaid\"|last=|first=|date=December 4, 2012|website=BuzzFeed|publisher=BuzzFeed, Inc|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> but the idea was ultimately abandoned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.j-14.com/posts/10-totally-mind-blowing-facts-about-the-little-mermaid-17164/photos/the-little-mermaid-9-9728#photo-anchor|title=10 Totally Mind-Blowing Facts About 'The Little Mermaid'|last=Van de Wall|first=Virginia|date=October 1, 2013|website=J-14|publisher=|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> However, their [[blood relationship]] is still vaguely alluded to when the character mentions a time during which she actually lived in Triton's palace.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/59003/11-things-you-might-not-know-about-little-mermaid|title=11 Things You Might Not Know About 'The Little Mermaid'|last=Oneill|first=Therese|date=October 28, 2015|website=Mental Floss|publisher=Mental Floss, Inc|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Clements and Musker had originally intended for Ursula to remain her original size at the end of the film.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/top/2529/8/The-Little-Mermaid-1989-50-things-you-might-not-know-about-your-favorite-Disney-films-1989-1997.html|title=50 things you might not know about your favorite Disney films, 1989-1997 edition|last=Hicken|first=Jackie|date=June 17, 2014|website=Desert News|publisher=|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> However, Katzenberg had just recently seen the film ''[[Die Hard]]'' (1988), which inspired him to request a \"bigger\" ending for ''The Little Mermaid'', and thus he instructed the writers to have Ursula grow much larger in size during her [[Climax (narrative)|climactic]] fight with Ariel and Eric.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n===Voice and music===\nUrsula is voiced by American actress and comedian [[Pat Carroll (actress)|Pat Carroll]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wic.org/bio/pcarroll.htm|title=Pat Carroll|last=|first=|date=|website=Women's International Center|publisher=|access-date=April 2, 2016}}</ref> Carroll was not the filmmakers' first choice for the role; Clements, Musker and Ashman had long debated who should voice the villainness,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2007/06/15/why-for-pat-carroll-wasn-t-actually-disney-s-first-choice-to-voice-ursula-in-the-little-mermaid.aspx|title=Why (For) Pat Carroll wasn't actually Disney's first choice to voice Ursula in \"The Little Mermaid\"|last=Hill|first=Jim|date=June 14, 2007|website=Jim Hill Media|publisher=|access-date=March 4, 2016}}</ref> the casting of whom was long and tedious, spanning an entire year.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=http://howardashman.com/blog/john-musker-question-countdown-number-7/|title=John Musker Question Countdown \u2013 Number 7|last=|first=|date=|website=Howard Ashman|publisher=Shoptalk Ltd|access-date=April 2, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/jim-hill/which-1980s-tv-favorites_b_6465252.html|title=Which 1980s TV Favorites Almost Voiced Ursula the Sea Witch for Disney\u2019s The Little Mermaid|last=hill|first=Jim|date=March 15, 2015|website=The Huffington Post|publisher=TheHuffingtonPost.com, Inc|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> In his book ''Makin' Toons: Inside the Most Popular Animated TV Shows and Movies'', author Allan Neuwirth documented that the filmmakers searched \"for just the right performer who could put across the deep-voiced, world-weary, [[deadpan]] villainness they had in mind\u2013but never quite snaring their catch\".<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xEctAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT253&dq=pat+carroll+ursula+the+little+mermaid&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiH7Yyt_-7LAhVDuoMKHQISB2sQ6AEIHDAA#v=onepage&q=pat%20carroll%20ursula%20the%20little%20mermaid&f=false|title=Makin' Toons: Inside the Most Popular Animated TV Shows and Movies|last=Neuwirth|first=Allan|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing, Inc|year=2013|isbn=9781621531975|location=United States|pages=|quote=|via=Google Books}}</ref> While Ashman was interested in actress [[Joan Collins]] because he was a fan of her performance as [[Alexis Colby]] in the [[soap opera]] ''[[Dynasty (1981 TV series)|Dynasty]]'',<ref name=\":1\" /> Clements and Musker favored actress [[Bea Arthur]], for whom they had actually written the role,<ref name=\":2\" /> describing Ursula as \"having a Bea Arthur-type [[Bass (voice type)|basso]] voice\" in early drafts of their screenplay.<ref name=\":0\"/> Clements and Musker expected Arthur to accept the role because she had already been working for Disney's [[Touchstone Television]] on the sitcom ''[[The Golden Girls]]''.<ref name=\":1\" /> However, Arthur's agent resented the directors-writers for insinuating that her client voice a witch,<ref name=\":1\" /> refusing to even present the script to the actress.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nWith Arthur eliminated, Clements and Musker were forced to audition several other popular television actresses of the decade, including [[Nancy Marchand]], [[Charlotte Rae]] and [[Roseanne Barr]],<ref name=\":0\" /> the last of whom had originally auditioned for the supporting role of chambermaid Carlotta.<ref name=\":11\"/> Amused by her [[nasal voice]], Howard invited the comedian to read for Ursula, but concluded that her approach was ultimately not suitable for the character.<ref name=\":12\"/> Jazz singer [[Nancy Wilson (jazz singer)|Nancy Wilson]] also auditioned.<ref name=\":1\" /> Meanwhile, Ashman himself had been similarly unsuccessful in recruiting Collins because ''Dynasty'' producer [[Aaron Spelling]] feared that the actress' reputation would be jeopardized should she voice an animated character.<ref name=\":1\" /> Thus, Ashman pursued [[Musical theatre|Broadway]] veteran [[Elaine Stritch]], of whom he had been a long-time fan.<ref name=\":0\" /> The audition process for Ursula required each hopeful to both recite a scene from the film and perform a Broadway-style song of their choice.<ref name=\":12\"/> The finalists became Clements and Musker's Rae versus Ashman's Stritch,<ref name=\":1\" /> the latter of whom ultimately won the role over Rae with her preferred rendition of Ursula's song \"[[Poor Unfortunate Souls]]\".<ref name=\":0\" /> Musker described Stritch's approach to Ursula as \"an eccentric, loopy reading\".<ref name=\":1\" /> However, Stritch and Ashman soon began to experience creative differences over \"Poor Unfortunate Souls\" because the actress refused to follow the lyricist's \"very specific directions\".<ref name=\":0\" /> After refusing to perform the song at Ashman's preferred tempo (combined with her [[alcoholism]]),<ref name=\":1\" /> the songwriter fired Stritch from the project,<ref name=\":12\"/> thus forcing Clements and Musker to find a replacement with yet another round of auditions.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nCarroll first learned of ''The Little Mermaid''<nowiki/> from her agent, and immediately agreed to audition for Ursula because she had always wanted to voice a [[Disney characters|Disney character]].<ref name=\":10\" /> However, the actress felt that her chances were slim to none upon realizing that her competition largely consisted of famous film and television actresses.<ref name=\":0\" /> Musker described Carroll's audition approach as a hybrid of actors [[Maurice Evans (actor)|Maurice Evans]] and [[Tallulah Bankhead]].<ref name=\":12\" /> Although confident in both her acting and singing auditions,<ref name=\":10\" /> Carroll did not hear back from her agent about the role until a year afterward, by which time she had already forgotten she had ever auditioned.<ref name=\":0\" /> Upon being cast, Carroll was entirely committed to the role, giving it complete precedence over all other jobs and projects at the time.<ref name=\":10\" /> Carroll's first task was to record \"Poor Unfortunate Souls\", her approach to which was remarkably different than Stritch's, first asking Howard to demonstrate exactly how he would like her to perform the song before attempting it.<ref name=\":0\" /> Carroll completely credits Ashman with her delivery,<ref name=\":4\" /> explaining, \"I got the whole attitude from him ... and his shoulders would twitch a certain way, and his eyes would go a certain way ... I got more about that character from Howard singing that song than from anything else.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Carroll also borrowed Ursula's habit of saying \"innit\" instead of \"isn't it\" from Ashman.<ref name=\":0\" /> Despite their strong working relationship, Carroll described working with Ashman and composer [[Alan Menken]] as a \"brutal\" experience because of the songwriters' \"military\" approach; she would often return home from recording sessions with blown vocal chords.<ref name=\":0\" /> Carroll recalled her daughter, filmmaker [[Tara Karsian]], reassuring her that \"you're in something that fifty years from now may be shown ... What you're working on now will be seen by our children, and our grandchildren, and our great-grandchildren\" after complaining to her about one of her recording sessions.<ref name=\":0\" /> Describing her own performance as [[William Shakespeare|Shakespearean]], Carroll perceived Ursula as an \"ex-Shakespearean actress who now sold cars\", which inspired her dry, theatrical interpretation.<ref name=\":0\" /> Carroll also deepened her own voice for the role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fast-rewind.com/making_littlemermaid.htm|title=Making Of...The Little Mermaid Behind The Scenes|website=The 80s Movies Rewind|publisher=Fast-Rewind.com|access-date=April 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107050713/http://www.fast-rewind.com/making_littlemermaid.htm|archive-date=November 7, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> When Carroll watched the completed film for the first time, she was frightened by her own performance, comparing it to actress [[Margaret Hamilton (actress)|Margaret Hamilton]]'s performance as the [[Wicked Witch of the West]] in the film ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' (1939).<ref name=\":10\" /> Actress [[Jodi Benson]], who voices Ariel, briefly provides the voice of \"Vanessa\", Ursula's beautiful human [[Alter ego|alter-ego]], in lieu of Carroll.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/jim-hill/this-little-mermaid-has-l_b_4323101.html|title=This \u2018Little Mermaid\u2019 Has Legs: Disney Legend Jodi Benson Looks Back on 25 Years of Voicing the Character of Ariel|last=Hill|first=Jim|date=November 22, 2013|website=The Huffington Post|publisher=TheHuffingtonPost.com, Inc|access-date=April 2, 2016}}</ref> With the writing and recording of \"Poor Unfortunate Souls\", Ursula became the first Disney villainness to receive her own song.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://ca.movies.yahoo.com/blogs/wide-screen/ranking-the-12-most-famous-disney-villains-from-worst-to-best-185848655.html|title=Ranking the 12 most famous Disney villains from worst to best|last=Perkins|first=Will|date=May 29, 2014|website=Yahoo! Movies|publisher=|access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, it was announced that [[Melissa McCarthy]] is in talks to play Ursula in the upcoming live-action remake of ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'', set to be directed by [[Rob Marshall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/melissa-mccarthy-little-mermaid-ursula-1203217481/|title=Melissa McCarthy in Talks to Play Ursula in Live-Action 'Little Mermaid' (EXCLUSIVE)|first=Justin|last=Kroll|date=28 June 2019|work=Variety|accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Design===\n\nDuring production of ''The Little Mermaid''<nowiki/>, Ursula's design evolved and transformed dramatically. Animator [[Glen Keane]]'s earliest sketches of Ursula were drawn to resemble Rae, specifically based on the actress' audition for the role.<ref name=\":12\" /> The short-lived casting of Stritch as Ursula and her subsequent performance eventually inspired the animators to design the character as \"a tall, thin regal-looking sea witch\" based on [[manta ray]]s and [[Scorpaeniformes|scorpion fish]], complete with a long cape.<ref name=\":0\" /> At one point, Ursula had also been drawn with spikes to resemble a [[Spikefish|spinefish]].<ref name=\":4\" /> Ursula's appearance was largely inspired by American actor and [[drag queen]] [[Divine (actor)|Divine]],<ref name=\":40\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pdCrF4JxKDIC&pg=PA182&dq=ursula+feminism+the+little+mermaid&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiEiLHm0oPNAhVBDlIKHQuyAdYQ6AEIHDAA#v=onepage&q=ursula%20feminism%20the%20little%20mermaid&f=false|title=From Mouse to Mermaid: The Politics of Film, Gender, and Culture|last=Bell|first=Elizabeth|last2=Haas|first2=Lynda|last3=Sells|first3=Laura|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=1995|isbn=9780253209788|location=United States|pages=182}}</ref> who was best known for his frequent appearances in several films directed by filmmaker [[John Waters]].<ref name=\":6\" /> Similarities were first drawn between the character and the actor after animator [[Rob Minkoff]] sketched \"a vampy overweight matron\", to which Ashman responded, \"She looks like a [[Miami Beach, Florida|Miami Beach]] matron ... playing [[Mahjong|Mah Jong]] by the pool.\u201d<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/article/read-how-divine-inspired-ursula-sea-witch-230938|title=Read This: How Divine inspired Ursula The Sea Witch|last=Dart|first=Chris|date=January 19, 2016|website=A. V. Club|publisher=Onion Inc|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> The character shares Divine's signature [[eye makeup]], jewelry and body type while originally sporting a [[Mohawk hairstyle|Mohawk]],<ref name=\":5\" /> the last of which was borrowed from the actor's ''[[Pink Flamingos|Pink Flamingo]]''[[Pink Flamingos|s]] (1972) character Babs Johnson.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=http://moviepilot.com/posts/2766413|title=(WATCH) Things you probably didn't know about \"The Little Mermaid\"|last=Portolan|first=Daniel|date=March 9, 2015|website=Moviepilot|publisher=|access-date=April 20, 2016}}</ref> However, Minkoff had been drawing the character with a shark's tail at the time.<ref name=\":5\" /> Clements eventually decided to place Ursula's head on top of the body of an octopus instead, which ultimately resulted in her current design.<ref name=\":2\" /> The animators then studied the way in which octopuses move, explaining, \"There was a very kind of seductive and yet scary aspect\", which they incorporated into the character's own gait.<ref name=\":2\" /> The ''Pink Flamingos''-inspired Mohawk was ultimately discarded because Disney felt that the hairstyle was \"too over-the-top\" for the film.<ref name=\":14\" /> Additionally, Ursula's face was also inspired by that of [[Madame Medusa]] from Disney's ''[[The Rescuers]]'' (1977)''.''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/movies/bp/17-things-didn-t-know-little-mermaid-201752088.html|title=17 Things You Didn\u2019t Know About \u2018The Little Mermaid\u2019|last=Min|first=Lilian|date=September 20, 2013|website=Yahoo!|publisher=|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> According to ''The Gospel according to Disney: Faith, Trust, and Pixie Dust'' author Mark I. Pinsky, Ursula became \"the most [[Grotesque body|grotesque]] characterization Disney ... have created for a female villain\" at that time.<ref name=\":44\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N551BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA140&dq=ursula+norma+desmond&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiHubjqw4fNAhXF6YMKHVVJCXYQ6AEIMTAD#v=onepage&q=ursula%20norma%20desmond&f=false|title=The Gospel according to Disney: Faith, Trust, and Pixie Dust|last=Pinsky|first=Mark I.|publisher=Westminster John Knox Press|year=2004|isbn=9781611644272|location=United Kingdom|pages=140}}</ref>\n\nHaving animated previous Disney villains, Keane was originally approached to be the supervising animator of Ursula, but declined in favor of animating Ariel because he longed to do something different.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aimeemajor.com/anim/aagleninterview.html|title=Glen Keane Interview August 22, 1990|last=|first=|date=August 22, 1990|website=AimeeMajor.com|publisher=|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> Thus, Keane was replaced by [[Ruben A. Aquino]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dvdizzy.com/littlemermaid-platinumeditionb.html|title=The Little Mermaid: Platinum Edition DVD Review|last=|first=|date=October 3, 2006|website=DVDizzy.com|publisher=DVDizzy.com|access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> The character was originally drawn with a full set of eight tentacles similar to a real-life octopus, which were eventually reduced to a more manageable six because the original amount would have been too difficult and costly to animate.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{cite web|url=http://thefw.com/things-you-didnt-know-about-disneys-the-little-mermaid/|title=10 Things You Didn\u2019t Know About Disney\u2019s \u2018The Little Mermaid\u2019|last=Franks-Allen|first=Sara|date=|website=The FW|publisher=SCREENCRUSH NETWORK|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> According to Carroll,<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://deaditeden.com/2015/11/18/happy-26th-birthday-to-the-little-mermaid-here-are-a-few-facts-you-didnt-know/|title=Happy 26th birthday to The Little Mermaid! Here are a few facts you didn\u2019t know|date=November 18, 2015|website=Deadite Den|access-date=April 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508133235/https://deaditeden.com/2015/11/18/happy-26th-birthday-to-the-little-mermaid-here-are-a-few-facts-you-didnt-know/|archive-date=May 8, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> this modification actually makes the character more similar to a [[squid]] than an octopus;<ref name=\":9\" /> whether or not Ursula is an octopus continues to be debated among both critics and devout fans, some of whom believe that the character's pair of arms actually account for the remaining two tentacles.<ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":15\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.people.com/article/the-little-mermaid-25th-anniversary|title=Celebrate 25 Years of The Little Mermaid with 25 Things Even Superfans May Not Know|last=Mackie|first=Drew|date=November 14, 2014|website=People|publisher=Time Inc|access-date=April 22, 2016}}</ref> Clements admitted that the character's six tentacles made animating her a challenge nonetheless.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jetsettingmom.com/creating-disney-classic-interview-jon-musker-ron-clements-writers-directors-little-mermaid/|title=Creating a Disney Classic \u2013 Interview with John Musker & Ron Clements, writers & directors of The Little Mermaid!|last=|first=|date=September 11, 2013|website=Jet-Setting Mom|publisher=JETSETTING MOM|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> Ursula was intentionally designed to instill fear in ''The Little Mermaid''<nowiki/>'s viewers.<ref name=\":37\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.techtimes.com/articles/20379/20141117/the-little-mermaid-ursula-disney-villains.htm|title=Why Ursula From 'The Little Mermaid' is the Scariest Disney Villain|last=Rosenfeld|first=Laura|date=November 17, 2014|website=Tech Times|publisher=TechTimes Inc|access-date=May 26, 2016}}</ref> Animators studied [[The Terrible Dogfish|Monstro]] from Disney's ''[[Pinocchio (1940 film)|Pinocchio]]'' (1940) in order to animate the character's enlarged self emerging from the sea.<ref name=\":4\" /> Ursula's appearance was also based on that of the character [[Sunset Boulevard (film)|Norma Desmond]], who appears in the film ''[[Sunset Boulevard (film)|Sunset Boulevard]]'' (1950).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wx8JsmNxjcUC&pg=PA286&dq=ursula+norma+desmond&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiHubjqw4fNAhXF6YMKHVVJCXYQ6AEIUjAJ#v=onepage&q=ursula%20norma%20desmond&f=false|title=Film Theory Goes to the Movies: Cultural Analysis of Contemporary Film|last=Collins|first=Jim|last2=Collins|first2=Ava Preacher|last3=Radner|first3=Hilary|publisher=Routledge|year=2012|isbn=9781135216450|location=United Kingdom|pages=286}}</ref> Divine never lived to see his own likeness appear in ''The Little Mermaid''; the actor died in 1988, one year before the film's release.<ref name=\":5\" /> However, his cohorts agree that Divine would have greatly enjoyed Ursula.<ref name=\":5\" /> Documentarian [[Jeffrey Schwarz|Jeffrey Schwartz]] joked that the actor would have wanted to play Ursula himself had he known about the character, having once told Waters \"When I was young, all I wanted to be was a Disney villain\".<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==Characterization and themes==\n[[About.com]]'s David Nusair observed that \"There\u2019s no limit to how low Ursula will stoop to achieve her goals\";<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=http://movies.about.com/od/animatedmovies/tp/disney-villains.htm|title=Top 10 Disney Villains|last=Nusair|first=David|date=|website=About.com|publisher=About.com|access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> the character often relies on a combination of [[Witchcraft|sorcery]] and deception to achieve them.<ref name=\":26\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.tvovermind.com/movies/ranking-top-10-animated-disney-villains|title=Ranking the Top 10 Animated Disney Villains|last=|first=|date=March 30, 2016|website=TVOvermind|publisher=TVOvermind|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> \"A bargainer of the worst kind\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://moviepilot.com/posts/1464097|title=Top Ten: Disney Animated Villains!|last=Eguizabal|first=William|date=June 1, 2014|website=Moviepilot|publisher=|access-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref> Ursula only agrees to help the less fortunate when she's confident that she can gain something from them in return.<ref name=\":27\">{{Cite web|url=http://theodysseyonline.com/ksu/10-best-worst-disney-villains/344551|title=The 10 Best (Worst) Disney Villains|last=Nouryeh|first=Elizabeth|date=March 7, 2016|website=The Odyssey|publisher=Olympia Media Group|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> Identifying Ursula as Ariel's binary due to the character's experience and authority, ''Collision of Realities: Establishing Research on the Fantastic in Europe'' author Lars Schmeink described Ursula as a \"more complex and mature character\" than Ariel, embodying everything that the mermaid can potentially become.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t1znBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA140&dq=ursula+the+little+mermaid+feminist&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjylJir8aXMAhXG5xoKHUIlAtoQ6AEILTAD#v=onepage&q=ursula%20the%20little%20mermaid%20feminist&f=false|title=Collision of Realities: Establishing Research on the Fantastic in Europe|last=Schmeink|first=Lars|last2=B\u00f6ger|first2=Astrid|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|year=2012|isbn=9783110276718|location=Germany|pages=140}}</ref> To Ariel, Ursula represents \"the matronly image\" who \"instigate[s] the young princess' epic journey\" as she longs to achieve the witch's \"[[Sage (philosophy)|sage]]-like knowledge and power\".<ref name=\":20\" /> Ursula teaches Ariel about [[womanhood]], a theme ''From Mouse to Mermaid: The Politics of Film, Gender, and Culture'' author Elizabeth Belle noticed is absent in Anderson's story.<ref name=\":40\" /> According to Bell, \"Ursula can retrieve Ariel from her destined alliance with patriarchy\", observing that the witch actually \"teaches Ariel that performance and voice and manifestations\" are \"liberations of gender\".<ref name=\":40\" /> ''[[Teen Ink]]''<nowiki/>'s Emma James believes that Ursula's death ultimately prevents Ariel from experiencing and learning from the consequences of her actions, concluding, \"Ariel never really owns up to all the mishap she caused.\"<ref name=\":25\" /> Observing that Ursula actually warns Ariel about the consequences should she fail to earn a kiss from Eric, Laura Stampler of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' described the character as a \"savvy contract negotiator\".<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/3586569/sexist-little-mermaid/|title=The Little Mermaid: Not as Sexist as You Thought It Was|last=Stampler|first=Laura|last2=Dockterman|first2=Eliana|date=November 17, 2014|website=Time|publisher=Time Inc|access-date=April 22, 2016}}</ref> Writing for [[Collider (website)|Collider]], Dave Trumbore identified Ursula as the film's \"Crossroads Demon\".<ref name=\":35\">{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/best-disney-villains/#ursula|title=Disney\u2019s 9 Most Wicked Animated Villains|last=Foutch|first=Haleigh|date=April 24, 2016|website=Collider.com|publisher=COMPLEX MEDIA INC|access-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref> According to Gary Thompson of the ''[[Philadelphia Daily News]]'', Ursula is similar to businesswoman [[Leona Helmsley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/1989-11-17/entertainment/26137106_1_young-mermaid-evil-sea-witch-samuel-e-wright|title=Back To The Drawing Boards Disney Regains Form With 'Mermaid' Tale|last=Thompson|first=Gary|date=November 17, 1989|website=Philly.com|publisher=|access-date=April 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n''Makin' Toons: Inside the Most Popular Animated TV Shows and Movies'' author Allan Neuwirth observed that Ursula obeys Disney's \"long-standing tradition of depicting classic scoundrels ... none so unsettling as their female villains.\"<ref name=\":10\" /> Neuwirth believes that the public's fear of Disney's female villains \"stems from our expectations of nurturing, comfort and honesty from our mothers\",<ref name=\":10\" /> while Disney's villainnesses, including Ursula, tend to \"lust after ... youth and beauty.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dFR9aLIA3g8C&pg=PA34&dq=ursula+matriarchy+disney&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj9ifCdzoPNAhVNNFIKHbTfDZUQ6AEIKzAD#v=onepage&q=ursula%20matriarchy%20disney&f=false|title=Mommy Angst: Motherhood in American Popular Culture: Motherhood in American Popular Culture|last=Bishop|first=Mardia J.|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2009|isbn=9780313375316|location=United States|pages=33}}</ref> Ursula even goes as far as transforming herself into a beautiful young woman in order to trick Ariel's love interest into marrying her instead.<ref name=\":43\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Q5UVgMLxWcC&pg=PA67&dq=ursula+feminism+the+little+mermaid&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiqyJOorIfNAhVGyoMKHZXeBlYQ6AEIOTAF#v=onepage&q=ursula%20feminism%20the%20little%20mermaid&f=false|title=Bloody Mary in the Mirror: Essays in Psychoanalytic Folkloristics|last=Dundes|first=Alan|publisher=Univ. Press of Mississippi|year=2008|isbn=9781604731873|location=United States|pages=55\u201375}}</ref> Janet Wasko believes that Ursula's role as a powerful but antagonistic woman in ''The Little Mermaid'' alludes to the idea of [[patriarchy]] being preferable to [[matriarchy]].<ref name=\":42\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GQfk_5oMrCcC&pg=PT128&dq=ursula+matriarchy+disney&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj9ifCdzoPNAhVNNFIKHbTfDZUQ6AEIIjAB#v=onepage&q=ursula%20matriarchy%20disney&f=false|title=Understanding Disney: The Manufacture of Fantasy|last=Wasko|first=Janet|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2013|isbn=9780745669045|location=United States|pages=}}</ref> Sophie Hall of [[Beamly]] identified Ursula as a woman struggling to \"run the kingdom in a man\u2019s world, having been kicked out for no specific reason.\"<ref name=\":28\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.beamly.com/tv-film/8-disney-villains-better-heroes|title=8 Disney villains who are better than the heroes|last=Hall|first=Sophie|date=July 9, 2015|website=Beamly|publisher=|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> In her book ''Emerson Goes to the Movies: Individualism in Walt Disney Company's Post-1989 Animated Films'', author Justyna Fruzi\u0144ska claimed that \"the masculine rule of Triton is presented as positive and opposed to the negative, feminine rule of Ursula\".<ref name=\":41\" /> ''Understanding Disney: The Manufacture of Fantasy'' author Janet Wasko accused the film's treatment of Ursula of \"eliminat[ing] many of the female characters and undermin[ing] [the] feminine power\" present in Andersen's fairy tale.<ref name=\":42\" /> However, Wasko also argued that Ursula could possibly be considered a [[mother figure]] for Ariel;<ref name=\":42\" /><ref name=\":43\" /> the tunnel of Ursula's cave resembles a [[vagina]], while Ursula's mannerisms evoke those of a mother as she refers to Ariel as \"my dear sweet child\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lvKUm7D2vckC&pg=PA158&dq=ursula+feminism+the+little+mermaid&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiqyJOorIfNAhVGyoMKHZXeBlYQ6AEINDAE#v=onepage&q=ursula%20feminism%20the%20little%20mermaid&f=false|title=Shakespeare Survey: Volume 56, Shakespeare and Comedy: An Annual Survey of Shakespeare Studies and Production|last=Holland|first=Peter|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2003|isbn=9780521827270|location=England|pages=158}}</ref> Gwynne Watkins of [[Yahoo!]] accused Ursula of \"assur[ing] Ariel that human men prefer their women to be silent\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/movies/its-time-to-see-the-little-mermaid-as-a-feminist-102969568407.html|title=It's Time to See 'The Little Mermaid' as a Feminist Film|last=Watkins|first=Gwynne|date=November 18, 2014|website=Yahoo!|publisher=|access-date=April 23, 2014}}</ref> Meanwhile, in response to feminist critiques of the character, author Amy M. Davis observed in her book ''Handsome Heroes and Vile Villains: Masculinity in Disney's Feature Films'' that Ursula is actually responsible for giving Eric the \"power to make Ariel permanently human\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0OQoCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA169&dq=ursula+the+little+mermaid+feminist&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjylJir8aXMAhXG5xoKHUIlAtoQ6AEINzAF#v=onepage&q=ursula%20the%20little%20mermaid%20feminist&f=false|title=Handsome Heroes and Vile Villains: Masculinity in Disney's Feature Films|last=Davis|first=Amy M|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2014|isbn=9780861969074|location=2014|pages=170}}</ref> However, author Alan Dundes in his book ''Bloody Mary in the Mirror: Essays in Psychoanalytic Folkloristics'' in conjunction with co-author Lauren Dundes observed that Ursula becomes masculine and deep-voiced once she acquires Triton's trident, implying that even \"the only powerful woman in the story fulfills her desire for supreme power by becoming masculine\".<ref name=\":43\" /> Dundes and Dundes also observed that Ursula reverts to being feminine once she is impaled.<ref name=\":43\" />\n\nIn her book ''Tales, Then and Now: More Folktales as Literary Fictions for Young Adults'', author Anna E. Altmann compared Ursula to [[Satan]] because both Ariel and Triton \"sign a contract ... with her\";<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TK0fOeuFiA0C&pg=PA194&dq=ursula+the+little+mermaid+feminist&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjylJir8aXMAhXG5xoKHUIlAtoQ6AEIHDAA#v=onepage&q=ursula%20the%20little%20mermaid%20feminist&f=false|title=Tales, Then and Now: More Folktales as Literary Fictions for Young Adults|last=Altmann|first=Anna E|publisher=Libraries Unlimited|year=2001|isbn=9781563088315|location=United States|pages=194}}</ref> James Plath of Movie Metropolis described Ursula's contract as \"a Mephistophelean bargain.\"<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=http://moviemet.com/review/little-mermaid-3d-blu-ray-review |title=THE LITTLE MERMAID - 3D Blu-ray review |last=Plath |first=James |date=September 28, 2013 |website=Movie Metropolis |publisher=Movie Metropolis |access-date=April 25, 2016 |quote=Ursula\u2014one of the stronger Disney villains in the past several decades\u2014gets her to sign on the dotted line of a Mephistophelean bargain. |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140208010138/http://moviemet.com/review/little-mermaid-3d-blu-ray-review |archivedate=February 8, 2014 }}</ref> Much like Satan, Ursula was banished from Triton's palace, similar to the way in which [[Lucifer]] was exiled from heaven.<ref name=\":44\" /> Felix Vasquez of Cinema Crazed believes that Ursula \"is evil just for the sake of being evil\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cinema-crazed.com/blog/2013/09/30/the-little-mermaid-1989/|title=The Little Mermaid (1989)|last=Vasquez|first=Felix|date=September 30, 2013|website=Cinema Crazed|publisher=Cinema Crazed|access-date=April 18, 2016}}</ref> Writing for the [[Disney.com|Disney Archives]], Dave Smith observed that Ursula \"has the gross unsubtlety of Ratigan from '[[The Great Mouse Detective]]' but substantially more brio.\"<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=http://disney.go.com/vault/archives/villains/ursula/ursula.html |title=Ursula |last=Smith |first=Dave |website=Disney Archives |publisher=Disney |access-date=April 19, 2016 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100331195110/http://disney.go.com/vault/archives/villains/ursula/ursula.html |archivedate=March 31, 2010 }}</ref> Describing Ursula as \"Bejeweled and lip-pouting like an overweight, over-rich, over-pampered, over-the-top society hostess gone mad,\" Smith perceived the character as \"all flair, flamboyance, and theatricality mixed with a touch of con-artistry\", citing [[Anger|wrath]] as her only genuine emotion.<ref name=\":13\" /> Additionally, Ursula tends to act as though she is performing for an audience.<ref name=\":13\" /> Jay Boyar of the ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'' compared the character's appearance to that of evangelist [[Tammy Faye Messner|Tammy Faye]].<ref name=\":19\" /> At times, Ursula tends to demonstrate stereotypically masculine physical traits.<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.threemoviebuffs.com/review/little-mermaid|title=The Little Mermaid|last=|first=|date=January 21, 2015|website=Three Movie Buffs|publisher=Three Movie Buffs|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> Describing the character as \"A campy sea witch with an insatiable thirst for power\", ''[[Rolling Stone]]''<nowiki/>'s David Ehrlich believes that Ursula resembles a child of Divine and [[Donald Trump]].<ref name=\":24\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/lists/12-scariest-moments-in-kids-films-20151019/the-little-mermaid-1989-ursula-supersized-20151019|title=12 Scariest Moments in Kids' Films|last=Ehrlich|first=David|date=October 19, 2015|website=Rolling Stone|publisher=Rolling Stone|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> Some critics identify the character with body positivity. According to Michaela Glover of ''The Odyssey'', ''\"''Ursula portrays a bold business woman, not being afraid to show off her curves and use them, which defies the typical standards of beauty by also being a full figured woman.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theodysseyonline.com/spelman/its-good-to-be-bad/260365|title=Why Disney Female Villains Are Iconic Feminists|last=Glover|first=Michaela|date=December 27, 2015|website=The Odyssey|publisher=Olympia Media Group|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Appearances==\n\n===Film===\nUrsula debuted in ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'' (1989) as a sea witch who is scheming to take advantage of the ambitions of King Triton's youngest daughter Princess Ariel in order to usurp the throne and turning merpeople into polyps for her garden. When Ariel saves and falls in love with a human named Prince Eric much to her father's chagrin, Ursula temporarily grants Ariel's wish to live as a human for three days in return for her voice. If she successfully earns a kiss from Eric by the end of the third day, Ariel will remain human permanently; if she fails, she will turn back into a mermaid and belong to Ursula forever. However, Ursula is determined to sabotage Ariel's and Eric's budding romance at any cost; when she realizes that Ariel and Eric are falling in love, Ursula transforms herself into a beautiful young woman named \"Vanessa\" and hypnotizes Eric, tricking him into agreeing to marry her instead. Ariel manages to thwart Ursula and Eric's wedding. Eric realizes that it was Ariel who saved him when her voice returns to her and is about to kiss her, but as the sun sets Ariel transforms back into a mermaid and is captured by Ursula. Triton confronts Ursula and agrees to give up himself and his magical trident in return for Ariel's freedom. Ursula then uses the trident to expand into monstrous proportions and attempts to kill Ariel and Eric, but Eric manages to impale Ursula with the splintered bowsprit of a wrecked ship, and she dies. With Ursula defeated, her power's cease, the merpeople turn back to normal, Triton's power is restored, and Ariel marries Eric once she is permanently transformed into a human.\n\n===Television series===\n{{main|The Little Mermaid (TV series)}}\nUrsula appears as the antagonist in four episodes of ''[[The Little Mermaid (TV series)|The Little Mermaid]]'' prequel television series: \"Against the Tide\", \"Tail of Two Crabs\", \"Heroes\" and \"Ariel's Treasures\". In all four episodes, she executes various plans to antagonize King Triton and take over Atlantica, but all fail.  \n\n===''The Little Mermaid II: Return to the Sea''===\n{{Main|The Little Mermaid II: Return to the Sea}}\n\nUrsula does not appear in the direct-to-video film ''[[The Little Mermaid II: Return to the Sea]]'' because she is killed in the first film, but she is mentioned many times, mostly by her younger sister [[Morgana (The Little Mermaid)|Morgana]], also voiced by Pat Carroll. In the family portrait during the cut song \"Gonna Get My Wish\", Ursula was also depicted with light green skin similar to Morgana and their mother.\n\n==In other media==\nUrsula appears in Disney park attractions such as the ''[[Fantasmic!]]'' show debuted in 1992 at Disneyland Park, as one of the [[Disney Villains]] summoned to destroy [[Mickey Mouse]]. A massive Ursula [[Audio-Animatronics|Audio-Animatronic]] appears in [[The Little Mermaid ~ Ariel's Undersea Adventure]], a dark ride at [[Disney California Adventure]], and [[Magic Kingdom]]. Ursula is a central character in the annual [[Halloween]]-themed [[fireworks]] show [[HalloWishes]] at the [[Walt Disney World]] [[Magic Kingdom]] ''[[Mickey's Not-So-Scary Halloween Party]]'' \"hard ticket\" event. Ursula also appears at the tail end of the ''Little Mermaid'' unit in [[Walt Disney's Parade of Dreams]] at [[Disneyland]].\n\nIn the ''[[Kingdom Hearts (video game)|Kingdom Hearts]]'' video game, Ursula appears as one of [[Maleficent (Disney)|Maleficent]]'s co-conspirators, using the power of the [[Heartless (Kingdom Hearts)|Heartless]] to attack Atlantica and gain power. In this version of events, the official walkthrough states that Ursula was King Triton's fortuneteller before she was banished. Ursula is eventually defeated by [[Sora (Kingdom Hearts)|Sora]], Ariel, [[Donald Duck]] and [[Goofy]]. In ''[[Kingdom Hearts: Chain of Memories]]'', she appears as a [[facsimile]] created from Sora's memories. In ''[[Kingdom Hearts II]]'', Ursula mysteriously returns through the powers of darkness and appears to Ariel, and recreates her film role. As the film's storyline is retold in the game, Ursula does not recognize Sora and company, and Ariel makes no mention of her defeat in the original ''Kingdom Hearts''. In fact, when Ursula arrives to make the deal with Ariel, the latter reacts as though she has seen Ursula for the first time. Sora, however, does note that Ursula \"got what she deserved\" in the first game. At the story's climax, she is defeated when Eric hurls the trident straight through Ursula's chest, destroying her seemingly once and for all. However, she reappears in the ''[[Kingdom Hearts 3D: Dream Drop Distance]]'', confronting Sora and Riku out at sea in her giant form from the end of the movie. The game gives conflicting hints on whether or not this Ursula is the \"real one,\" and serves a very small role, providing the tutorial to the game's battle system and delivering a line that foreshadows the plot of the game's main antagonist, Xehanort.\n\nShe has appeared for the concept art from [[Epic Mickey]] in 2010. When Ursula tries to kidnap Gremlin Gus, Mickey comes to the rescue and saved him from trying to let go of her clutches.\n\nUrsula appeared occasionally in the animated television series ''[[Disney's House of Mouse]]'' (2001) as one of Mickey's guests at the night club. In the feature film ''[[Mickey's House of Villains]]'' she participated in the musical number \"It's Our House Now\" alongside other Disney villains, and is one of Jafar's henchmen.<ref>{{cite AV media|people =Jamie Mitchell|title =Mickey's House of Villains|medium =Television production|publisher =Walt Disney Television Animation|location =USA|date = 2002}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, [[Rebel Wilson]] performed the role of Ursula at a stripped-down concert version of ''The Little Mermaid'' at the [[Hollywood Bowl]], which featured the songs from the film and four songs from the Broadway musical.<ref>{{ cite web | first=Jenelle | last=Riley | date=2016-06-04 | title=L.A. Theater Review: \u2018The Little Mermaid in Concert\u2019 at the Hollywood Bowl | url=https://variety.com/2016/legit/reviews/little-mermaid-in-concert-at-the-hollywood-bowl-1201788875/ | publisher=Variety.com | accessdate=2016-06-22 }}</ref> Wilson was praised for her performance, which was described by The Huffington Post as \"pitch perfect\".<ref>{{ cite web | first=Hayley | last=Cuccinello | title=Rebel Wilson Is The Ursula We Always Wanted In \u2018The Little Mermaid Live\u2019 | date=2016-06-06 | url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/rebel-wilson-is-the-ursula-we-always-wanted-in-the-little-mermaid-live_us_57556b31e4b0c3752dce06b9 | accessdate=2016-06-22 }}</ref> [[Queen Latifah]] portrayed Ursula in the 2019 television special, ''[[The Little Mermaid Live!]]'' which used a similar format of the live concerts at the Hollywood Bowl, by combining a screening of the film with live accompaniment by guest musicians and celebrities.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/little-mermaid-live-starring-aulii-cravalho-set-at-abc-1229130 |title=Little Mermaid' Live Starring Auli'i Cravalho Set at ABC |last=Bentley |first=Jean |date=August 5, 2019 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016044739/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/little-mermaid-live-starring-aulii-cravalho-set-at-abc-1229130 |archive-date=October 16, 2019 |access-date=October 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Books===\nUrsula has appeared in various Disney Press novels and tie-ins for the franchise. A comic book series \"Disney's The Little Mermaid\" was released in 1992, revolving around the adventures of Ariel living under the sea as a mermaid. Ursula appears in a few issues, notably \"Serpent Teen\", which depicts how Ursula obtained the sea serpent carcass that makes her home.<ref>{{cite comic|writer=Peter David|penciller=Bill Fugate|inker=Dave Hunt|title=Serpent Teen|volume=1|issue=1|date=1992|publisher=Walt Disney Magazine Publishing Group}}</ref> ''My Side of the Story: Ursula'' (2004) retells the plot of the film from Ursula's point of view, and depicts Ursula having romantic feelings for Triton.<ref>{{cite book|last=Skinner|first=Daphne|title=My Side of the Story: Ursula|publisher=Disney Press|date=2004|location=New York|isbn=0-7868-3503-6|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/mysideofstory00skin}}</ref> ''The Villain Files'' (2005) depicts Ursula's youth living in Triton's castle while Ariel was a baby.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pringle|first=Betsy Henry|title=Disney Villains: The Top Secret Files|publisher=Disney Press|date=2005|location=New York|isbn=0-7868-3603-2}}</ref>\n\nUrsula is a main character in the 2016 [[young adult fiction|young adult]] novel ''Poor Unfortunate Soul: A Tale of the Sea Witch'' by [[Serena Valentino]].<ref>{{ cite web | title=Poor Unfortunate Soul: A Tale of the Sea Witch | url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/1484724054 | publisher=amazon.com | accessdate=2016-04-10 }}</ref><ref>{{ cite web | title=Serena Valentino (official website): Poor Unfortunate Soul | url=http://www.serenavalentino.com/projects/ursula/ | accessdate=2016-04-10 }}</ref> The novel is the third entry of the \"Villains\" series, a shared universe that [[Crossover (fiction)|crosses over]] various theatrical Disney films including ''[[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]'', ''[[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937 film)|Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs]]'' and ''[[Sleeping Beauty (1959 film)|Sleeping Beauty]]''. In this novel, Ursula is King Triton's younger sister who was betrayed by him as a child for choosing a tentacled form instead of a mermaid's tail, and grew up as a human in the town of Ipswich with an adoptive human father. Ursula returned to the sea when her adopted father was killed by the townsfolk for protecting her, befriending Athena, Queen of Atlantica, but was denied her inheritance by Triton and banished to the shadows. Ursula conspires with three other witches to steal Triton's soul and become ruler of all the seas, but is ultimately defeated.<ref>{{ cite book | first=Serena | last=Valentino | date=2016 | title=Poor Unfortunate Soul | publisher=Disney Press | ISBN=9781484724057 }}</ref>\n\n===Broadway musical===\n{{main|The Little Mermaid (musical)}}\nIn the [[The Little Mermaid (musical)|musical version]] of the original film, [[Sherie Rene Scott]] originated the live role, which she played until January 25, 2009. Other actresses who played the role are [[Heidi Blickenstaff]]  and [[Faith Prince]].\n\nIn this version, Ursula is King Triton's sister, a concept for the original film that was eventually dropped.<ref>(2006) ''Treasures Untold: The Making of Disney's 'The Little Mermaid'' [Documentary featurette]. Bonus material from ''The Little Mermaid: Platinum Edition'' DVD. Walt Disney Home Entertainment.</ref> When Ursula and Triton's father died, the pair were given equal share of the sea plus two magical items: Triton received the trident while Ursula received the magic Nautilus shell. Though the two were meant to rule the seas together, Ursula's greed and use of dark magic to usurp Triton led to her being banished. The desire for revenge and power is her motivation for the show. The musical's plot is similar to the film, with the exceptions that Ursula doesn't transform into Vanessa, and Ursula is ultimately defeated by Ariel, when the mermaid destroys the Nautilus shell that contains Ursula's power. In the revamped version of the musical developed by Glenn Casale in 2012, Ursula and Triton's backstory was changed, making them the seventh and eighth of eight siblings respectively. Ursula killed their older siblings one by one until she became a queen, and she forgot about Triton until he became old enough to depose her and become king. Ursula's motivation for revenge otherwise remains similar to the original book of the musical, with the addition that she was the one who killed Ariel's mother.\n\nIn addition to her song from the film, [[Alan Menken]] and [[Glenn Slater]] wrote new songs for Ursula: \"I Want the Good Times Back\", which introduces Ursula and her backstory, \"I Want the Good Times Back (reprise)\", where Ursula orders Flotsam and Jetsam to sabotage Ariel's attempt to get Eric to kiss her, and a reprise of \"Poor Unfortunate Souls\", where Ursula forces Triton to sign a deal and claims the trident. In the workshop stage, Ursula had a different introductory song: \"Wasting Away\", and its reprise featured Ursula preparing to transform into Vanessa.<ref name=\"book\">{{cite book|last=Lassell|first=Michael|title =The Little Mermaid: A Broadway Musical - From the Deep Blue Sea to the Great White Way|publisher =Disney Editions New York|year =2009|isbn =978-1-4231-1272-3}}</ref> [[Emily Skinner (actress, born 1970)|Emily Skinner]] provided vocals for Ursula in the workshop.<ref name=\"book\" /> In the 2012 revamped version of the musical, \"I Want the Good Times Back\" is replaced with a new song, \"Daddy's Little Angel\".<ref name=\"casale\">{{ cite web | last=Hill | first=Jim | title=How Glenn Casale Helped The Little Mermaid Find Her Feet After This Disney Stage Show Stumbled on Broadway | date=2014-07-23 | url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/jim-hill/how-glenn-casale-helped-t_b_5612802.html | publisher=Huffington Post | accessdate=2016-08-05 }}</ref>\n\n===''Once Upon a Time''===\n{{Infobox character\n|color      = #d6d6ff\n|series     = Once Upon a Time\n|name       = Ursula the Sea Witch\n|image      = Ursula once upon a time.png\n|first      = \"[[Heroes and Villains (Once Upon a Time)|Heroes and Villains]]\" (4.11)\n|last       = \"[[Best Laid Plans (Once Upon a Time)|Best Laid Plans]]\" (4.16)\n|creator    = [[Edward Kitsis]] & [[Adam Horowitz]]\n|portrayer  = [[Merrin Dungey]]<br>[[Tiffany Boone]] (young)\n|alias      = Sea Witch\n|species    = Cecaelia\n|title      = Queen of Darkness\n|family     = [[Poseidon]] (father, arguably deceased/dead)<ref name=\"actor\">{{cite web|title=Ernie Hudson To Play Poseidon On \u2018''Once Upon a Time''\u2019|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/ernie-hudson-cast-poseidon-once-upon-a-time-abc-1201330792/|accessdate=February 3, 2015|date=December 19, 2014|website=deadline.com|publisher=Deadline|last=Brooks|first=Larry}}</ref><br />Mother without name (deceased/dead)\n|extra-hdr  = Centric episodes\n|data31     = {{plainlist|\n*\"[[Darkness on the Edge of Town (Once Upon a Time)|Darkness on the Edge of Town]]\"\n*\"[[Poor Unfortunate Soul]]\"\n}}\n\n}}\nTwo live-action versions of Ursula appear in the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] television series ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]]''.\n\n;The Sea Goddess\nUrsula the Sea Goddess appears in Season 3, where she is voiced by [[Yvette Nicole Brown]]. In the episode \"[[Ariel (Once Upon a Time)|Ariel]]\", Ursula is described as a sea goddess whom no one has seen for a thousand years. According to Ariel, Ursula gave merfolk the ability to gain legs once a year, when the tide is highest. Ariel uses this ability to visit Prince Eric at his castle, where he is having a ball honoring Ursula. Later, the [[Evil Queen (Disney)|Evil Queen]] ([[Lana Parrilla]]) disguises herself as Ursula in order to make a deal with Ariel and trick her into capturing Snow White. This physical disguise includes short white hair and tentacles, similar to Ursula's animated appearance. Although the Queen considers Ursula to be \"a long-dead octopus\", she is shocked when the real Ursula possesses a statue and warns the queen not to impersonate her again.\n\n;The Sea Witch\nUrsula the Sea Witch is an antagonist who appears in the second half of Season 4, where she is portrayed as an adult by [[Merrin Dungey]], and as a teenager by [[Tiffany Boone]].\n\nThe episode \"[[Poor Unfortunate Soul (Once Upon a Time)|Poor Unfortunate Soul]]\" contains further flashbacks to Ursula's youth, when she was a teenage [[mermaid]] living under the sea with her father King [[Poseidon]] ([[Ernie Hudson]]). Ursula was gifted with a beautiful voice, which Poseidon wanted her to use to lure pirates to their death, in order to avenge the murder of Ursula's mother at the hands of an unnamed pirate. Ursula refused and instead befriended a pirate, Captain Hook ([[Colin O'Donoghue]]), who supported her desire for freedom. Ursula and Hook's friendship fell apart when Hook sealed Ursula's singing voice inside an enchanted shell, in order to punish Poseidon for destroying a weapon Hook wanted for himself. Ursula, angered and disappointed with both merfolk and humans, used Poseidon's trident to transform her tail into tentacles, emulating the ancient sea goddess that she was named after.\n\nThe episodes \"[[Heroes and Villains (Once Upon a Time)|Heroes and Villains]]\" and \"[[Darkness on the Edge of Town (Once Upon a Time)|Darkness on the Edge of Town]]\" contain flashbacks to the Enchanted Forest past, where Ursula teamed up with fellow witches [[Maleficent#Once Upon a Time|Maleficent]] ([[Kristin Bauer van Straten]]) and [[Cruella de Vil#Once Upon a Time|Cruella De Vil]] ([[Victoria Smurfit]]). The three of them worked together to try to defeat the heroes and find their happy endings, but failed. In the episode \"[[Best Laid Plans (Once Upon a Time)|Best Laid Plans]]\", while trying to rescue Maleficent's baby from Snow and Charming, Ursula and Cruella fell into a portal that lead into the non-magical world. Three decades later, in modern day New York, Ursula is working as a cleaner in an aquarium when she is recruited by Rumplestiltskin, who also reunites her with Cruella. Ursula, Cruella and Rumplestiltskin then trick their way into entering the magical town of Storybrooke. In the episode \"[[Unforgiven (Once Upon a Time)|Unforgiven]]\", they resurrect Maleficent to join their group.\n\nIn the episode \"[[Best Laid Plans (Once Upon a Time)|Best Laid Plans]]\" flashback it was shown that she and Cruella were sent from Enchanted Forrest before Dark Curse to World Without Magic because of [[Snow White]] ([[Ginnifer Goodwin]]) and [[Prince Charming]] ([[Josh Dallas]]). \n\nIn the episode's \"Poor Unfortunate Soul\" present time, a remorseful Hook makes a deal with Ursula to get her singing voice back. They are only successful when Ariel intercedes, bringing Poseidon to Storybrooke so that he and Ursula can reconcile, and the enchantment is broken. Having achieved her happy ending, Ursula then tells Hook the full plan Rumplestiltskin has for the heroes, and afterward returns to the sea with her father.\n\n===''Descendants 2''===\n{{Main|Descendants 2}}\n\nUrsula makes an appearance in the movie, voiced by [[Whoopi Goldberg]]. In the film, her daughter Uma is the main antagonist. During one scene, Ursula whips her tentacle out from the kitchen of her Fish and Chips shop and yells at Uma to stop singing and come to wash the dishes.\n\nTwenty years prior to the movie, Ursula had been banished on the Isle of the Lost with other villains. It's also revealed that Ursula and Maleficent had a rivalry over who gets to be the ruler of the island. Now, she has a daughter named Uma, who is feisty and manipulative just like her mom and she works at her mother's fish and chips shop. Uma and her archenemy, Mal, who is Maleficent's daughter, have a heated rivalry on the island. On ''Rise of the Isle of the Lost'', Uma befriends with Harry, son of [[Captain Hook]], who's also Uma's first mate at her pirate crew and Gil, son of [[Gaston]], who's also in Uma's pirate crew. Uma, Harry, and Gil are on a quest to find King Triton's trident to get out of the island for good until Mal retrieve it and Uma swears that she will get her revenge on Mal.\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\nUrsula has earned a positive reception from entertainment critics. When ''The Little Mermaid'' was first released in 1989, film critics and audiences alike immediately embraced Ursula as one of Disney's best villains,<ref name=\":0\" /> as well as one of the studio's strongest and most powerful villains in several years.<ref name=\":22\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familyhometheater.com/2013/10/01/the-little-mermaid-1989-3d-blu-ray-combo/|title=THE LITTLE MERMAID (1989) (3D Blu-ray combo)|last=|first=|date=October 1, 2013|website=Family Home Theater|publisher=|access-date=April 18, 2016|quote=Ursula\u2014one of the stronger Disney villains in the past several decades\u2014gets her to sign on the dotted line of a Mephistophelean bargain.}}</ref> Film critic [[Roger Ebert]] dubbed Ursula Disney's \"most satisfying villainess since\" ''[[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937 film)|Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs]]''<nowiki/>' [[Evil Queen (Disney)|Evil Queen]], who debuted in 1937.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-little-mermaid-1989|title=THE LITTLE MERMAID|last=Ebert|first=Roger|date=November 17, 1989|website=Roger Ebert|publisher=Ebert Digital LLC|access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> Critics agree that Ursula played an important role in the overall success of ''The Little Mermaid''<nowiki/>.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dustinputman.com/bluray/89_littlemermaid.htm|title=The Little Mermaid  (1989)|last=Putman|first=Dustin|date=October 1, 2013|website=TheBluFile|publisher=Dustin Putman|access-date=April 18, 2016}}</ref> Samantha Rullo of ''[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]'' reviewed Ursula as a \"way more interesting\" character than Ariel herself, while praising her for \"rocking the best hair and makeup of any Disney villain.\"<ref name=\":31\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/26194-6-disney-villains-with-more-movie-potential-than-maleficent|title=6 Disney Villains With More Movie Potential Than 'Maleficent'|last=Rullo|first=Samantha|date=May 29, 2014|website=Bustle|publisher=|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref> Also writing for ''Bustle'', Caitlyn Callegari appreciated Ursula for \"tell[ing] it like it is.\"<ref name=\":33\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/25743-angelina-jolies-maleficient-premiere-is-upon-us-gear-up-with-our-top-10-favorite-villains|title=Angelina Jolie's 'Maleficient' Premiere Is Upon Us: Gear Up With Our Top 10 Favorite Villains|last=Callegari|first=Caitlyn|date=May 28, 2014|website=Bustle|publisher=|access-date=April 28, 2016}}</ref> <nowiki/>Jay Boyar of the ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'' hailed Ursula as \"A total success\" despite sharing some similarities with previous Disney villains.<ref name=\":19\">{{cite web|url = http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1999-08-08/entertainment/9908050509_1_mermaid-shop-of-horrors-ariel|title = Dive Into Disneys Delightful 'Mermaid'|date = August 8, 1999|accessdate = September 14, 2014|website = Orlando Sentinel|publisher =|last = Boyar|first = Jay}}</ref> [[Janet Maslin]] of ''[[The New York Times]] ''described Ursula as \"a fabulously [[Camp (style)|campy]] creation embodying the film's well-developed sense of mischief.\"<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=950DE2DE1331F936A25752C1A96F948260&partner=Rotten%2520Tomatoes|title = The Little Mermaid (1989) Review/Film; Andersen's 'Mermaid,' by Way of Disney|date = November 15, 1989|accessdate = September 14, 2014|website = The New York Times|publisher = The New York Times Company|last = Maslin|first = Janet}}</ref> Describing the character as an \"inventive high-camp villainess,\" the ''[[New York Daily News]]''<nowiki/>' Kathleen Carroll cited Ursula as a prime example of the film's \"outstanding\" animation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/mermaid-sea-1989-review-article-1.2429392|title=\u2018The Little Mermaid\u2019 is a must sea: 1989 review|last=Carroll|first=Kathleen|date=November 15, 1989|website=New York Daily News|publisher=NYDailyNews.com|access-date=April 6, 2016}}</ref> Hailing the character as \"a visual feast,\" ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' considered Ursula to be among \"the film\u2019s more inspired inventions\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/1988/film/reviews/the-little-mermaid-1200427784/|title=Review: \u2018The Little Mermaid\u2019|last=|first=|date=December 31, 1988|website=Variety|publisher=Variety Media, LLC|access-date=April 20, 2016}}</ref><nowiki/>\n\n{{rquote|right|Actress Pat Carroll and the Ursula animators pump astonishing gobs of rotten-flirty menace and perversity into Witch Ursula, who looks a bit like the late actor Divine pasted over with an evil [[Jack Nicholson]] leer and squeezed into a cleavage-popping black evening gown, tailing off startlingly into eight squiggling black octopus tentacles. With her pet moray eels, she is a genuine nightmare, an obese lavender voluptuary peeling off lines like \"Life's full of hard choices . . . I'n't it?\" with blowzy relish or erupting from the ocean like [[Moby Dick (whale)|Moby Dick]] on [[bonbons]].|The ''Los Angeles Times''' Michael Wilmington}}\nWilliam Thomas of ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' described Ursula as \"truly quake-inducing\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/little-mermaid/review/|title=The Little Mermaid Review|last=Thomas|first=William|date=January 1, 2000|website=Empire|publisher=|access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> while ''Time''<nowiki/>'s Eliana Dockterman enjoyed the fact that, unlike previous Disney villains, \"Ursula doesn\u2019t even pretend to be good ... Right off the bat, she owns her evil witchiness\".<ref name=\":16\" /> Kilmeny Fane-Saunders, writing for ''[[Radio Times]]'', warned parents that Ursula could possibly frighten young children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/film/nbmmk/the-little-mermaid|title=The Little Mermaid|last=Fane-Saunders|first=Kilmeny|date=1989|website=Radio Times|publisher=Immediate Media Company|access-date=April 6, 2016}}</ref> However, ''[[The Huffington Post]]''<nowiki/>'s Hilary Sheinbau believes that \"there are many of these people who walk ... talk and strive among us\", concluding, \"it\u2019s important for kids to know that not everyone is going to look out for their best interests, however tempting some offers may be.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/hilary-sheinbaum/the-little-mermaid_b_1694342.html|title=Why My Kids Will Not Be Watching The Little Mermaid|last=Sheinbaum|first=Hilary|date=September 22, 2012|website=The Huffington Post|publisher=TheHuffingtonPost.com, In|access-date=April 22, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]''<nowiki/>'s Duncan Lindsay agreed that Ursula teaches children \"that binding contracts are a necessary part of every deal. We can thank her for all of our business sense as we are always sure to triple check that paperwork when ... securing deals.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2015/06/20/12-valuable-lessons-disney-villains-taught-all-children-5255431/|title=12 valuable lessons Disney villains taught all children|last=Lindsay|first=Duncan|date=June 20, 2015|website=Metro|publisher=|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> Dave Smith of the [[Disney.com|Disney Archives]] wrote, \"When anger does bring out her true emotion, the effects are staggering. Her look of stark hatred, even while her face is still human, must certainly have brought nightmares to young children. And when she finally changes into a giant, towering up through the waves and over puny mortals, the embodiment of fury is quite breathtaking.\" Smith concluded, \"Earlier we may have chuckled at her villainy; at this moment, there is no laughter ... only genuine fear.\"<ref name=\":13\" /> Meanwhile, [[Smosh|SMOSH]]'s Francesco Marciuliano praised the character as \"one of the most gleefully evil characters Disney has ever created.\"<ref name=\":34\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.smosh.com/smosh-pit/articles/6-more-disney-villains-should-get-their-own-movies|title=6 Disney Villains That Should Get Their Own Movies|last=Marciuliano|first=Francesco|date=2014|website=SMOSH|publisher=Defy Media, LLC|access-date=May 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCarroll's vocal performance as Ursula has been met with similar praise.<ref name=\":0\" /> Michael Wilmington of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' predicted that the actress \"will make [the film] a hit\".<ref>{{cite web|url = https://articles.latimes.com/1989-11-15/entertainment/ca-1802_1_big-leap|title = MOVIE REVIEW : 'Little Mermaid' Makes Big Splash|date = November 15, 1989|accessdate = September 14, 2014|website = Los Angeles Times|publisher = Los Angeles Times|last = Wilmington|first = Michael}}</ref> <nowiki/>Roger Hurlburt of the ''[[Sun-Sentinel]] ''enthused, \"If [[Academy Awards]] were given for vocal talents, then Pat Carroll ... certainly is deserving.\" Hurlburt went on to extol Carroll as \"a tour de force ... making such previous Disney villainesses -- [[Cruella de Vil]]le ([[sic]]) (''[[One Hundred and One Dalmatians|101 Dalmatians]]'') and the Evil Queen (''Snow White'') -- pale in comparison\",<ref>{{cite web|url = http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1989-11-17/features/8902100289_1_mermaid-animation-whippet|title = `Mermaid` Is Magic|date = November 17, 1989|accessdate = September 19, 2014|website = Sun-Sentinel|publisher = Roger|last = Hurlburt|first =}}</ref> while the ''[[Deseret News]]''<nowiki/>' Chris Hicks described her performance as \"delightful\".<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.deseretnews.com/article/700001061/Little-Mermaid-The.html|title = Film review: Little Mermaid, The|date = November 14, 1997|accessdate = September 14, 2014|website = Deseret News|publisher =|last = Hicks|first = Chris}}</ref> To-date, Carroll's interpretation of Ursula remains so respected that it has ultimately eclipsed her previous [[body of work]] as an actress, of which she is \"most proud\" nonetheless, not minding that she is associated with the role almost exclusively.<ref name=\":0\" /> Carroll explained that she continues to sign [[autograph]]s \"Dear Sweetlips: I hug you with my tentacles. Oceans of love, Ursula.' And then, underneath, in parentheses, I put 'Pat Carroll,' very small\" because her fans are more likely to identify with her character than her.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Accolades and legacy===\nRevered as a fan favorite,<ref name=\":35\" /> Ursula has established herself as one of Disney's most iconic characters;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxofficescoop.com/top-ten-animated-disney-villains/|title=Top Ten Animated Disney Villains|last=|first=|date=January 14, 2014|website=Box Office Scoop|publisher=BoxOfficeScoop.com|access-date=April 26, 2016|quote=Ursula is a truly iconic character in the Disney franchise.}}</ref><ref name=\":39\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/10/16/showbiz/movies/disney-villains-gallery/|title=Disney's scariest villains|last=Burdette|first=Kacy|last2=France|first2=Lisa Respers|date=October 16, 2013|website=CNN|publisher=Cable News Network|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref> she is widely regarded as one of the studio's \"classic\" villains.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":29\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/28/disney-villains_n_4661417.html|title=A Definitive Ranking Of 25 Classic Disney Villains|last=Duca|first=Lauren|date=January 28, 2014|website=The Huffington Post|publisher=TheHuffingtonPost.com, Inc|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.popoptiq.com/20-greatest-classic-disney-villians/|title=20 Greatest Classic Disney Villains|last=Reese|first=Kyle|date=June 11, 2009|website=PopOptiq|publisher=PopOptiQ|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":30\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/new/11-Classic-Disney-Villains-Ranked-By-How-They-Survive-Jail-70202-p9.html|title=11 Classic Disney Villains, Ranked By How Well They\u2019d Survive In Jail|last=Romano|first=Nick|date=|website=Cinemablend|publisher=Gateway Media News & Entertainment|access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> Author Corey Sandler described Ursula as a popular \"anti-favorite\" in his book ''Econoguide Disneyland Resort, Universal Studios Hollywood: And Other Major Southern California Attractions Including Disney's California Adventure''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5rx5dKbVU78C&pg=PT95&dq=ursula+anti-favorites+disney&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiP3bmIqKnMAhVKt4MKHZaGCkMQ6AEIHDAA#v=onepage&q=ursula%20anti-favorites%20disney&f=false|title=Econoguide Disneyland Resort, Universal Studios Hollywood: And Other Major Southern California Attractions Including Disney's California Adventure|last=Sandler|first=Corey|publisher=Globe Pequot|year=2007|isbn=9780762741670|location=United States|pages=}}</ref> The character's impact as a villainness has ultimately eclipsed those of her predecessors.<ref name=\":13\" /> According to Laura Rosenfeld of Tech Times, Ursula has had the most profound influence out of all animated characters in the [[Disney canon]].<ref name=\":37\" /> The character is considered to be one of the greatest Disney villains of all-time,<ref name=\":23\" /><ref name=\":33\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/travel/attractions/the-daily-disney/os-best-disney-villains-pictures-photogallery.html|title=Pictures: Best Disney villains|last=|first=|date=|website=Orlando Sentinel|publisher=|access-date=May 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/travel/attractions/the-daily-disney/os-greatest-disney-villains-story.html|title=The 30 greatest Disney villains of all time|last=Mauney|first=Matt|date=May 30, 2014|website=Orlando Sentinel|publisher=|access-date=May 26, 2016}}</ref> and continues to be ranked highly on [[Countdown|countdown lists]] compiled by various publications. Ursula topped [[E!]]'s Disney villains ranking; author John Boone concluded that \"There will never be a Disney villain more wickedly wonderful than\" Ursula.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/ca/news/542233/all-of-the-disney-villains-ranked|title=All of the Disney Villains, Ranked|last=Boone|first=John|last2=Mullins|first2=Jenna|date=May 15, 2014|website=E!|publisher=Entertainment Television, LLC|access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> [[Yahoo! Movies]] ranked Ursula third, praising her \"for being the first female Disney baddie to get her own song.\"<ref name=\":18\" /> On ''The Huffington Post''<nowiki/>'s \"Definitive Ranking Of 25 Classic Disney Villains\", Ursula was also ranked third.<ref name=\":29\" /> [[About.com]] placed the character at number four in the website's \"Top 10 Disney Villains\" article.<ref name=\":17\" /> [[Babble.com]] ranked the character the fifth greatest Disney villain \"From Bad to Worst\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.babble.com/mom/the-top-15-disney-villains-ranked-from-bad-to-worst/|title=THE TOP 15 DISNEY VILLAINS RANKED FROM BAD TO WORST|last=Castiglia|first=Carolyn|date=2013|website=Babble.com|publisher=Disney|access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> [[Moviefone]] ranked Ursula seventh on the website's list of the thirty greatest Disney villains of all-time.<ref name=\":36\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.moviefone.com/2014/05/25/disney-villains/#slide=2641807|title=Disney Villains: Ranking the Top 30 of All Time|last=Susman|first=Gary|date=May 25, 2014|website=Moviefone|publisher=Aol Inc|access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> [[TVOvermind]] also ranked Ursula seventh in its article \"Ranking the Top 10 Animated Disney Villains\".<ref name=\":26\" /> Recognizing Ursula among \"8 Disney villains who are better than the heroes\", [[Beamly]]'s Sophie Hall believes that the character \"had more charisma than Ariel\".<ref name=\":28\" /> By extension, Ursula is also often considered to be among the greatest animated villains of all-time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.themarysue.com/seven-best-animated-female-fillans/|title=Bad and Drawn That Way: The Seven Best Animated Female Villains|last=Goodwin|first=Sara|date=September 17, 2015|website=The Mary Sue|publisher=The Mary Sue|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref> [[Sky Movies]] included the character on the website's list \"Despicable Them: Top Animated Villains\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sky.com/tv/channel/skymovies/gallery/top-animated-villains|title=Despicable Them: Top Animated Villains|last=|first=|date=|website=Sky Movies|publisher=Sky UK|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref> The ''[[Toronto Sun]]'' ranked Ursula the third \"top animated [villain] of all time\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2013/07/04/our-top-animated-villains-of-all-time|title=Our top animated villains of all time|last=Braun|first=Liz|date=July 4, 2013|website=Toronto Sun|publisher=Postmedia Network|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nUrsula is also considered to be one of Disney's most terrifying villains.<ref name=\":37\" /><ref name=\":35\" /><ref name=\":36\" /><ref name=\":39\" /> [[Disney.com|Oh My Disney]] ranked Ursula's line \"Triton\u2019s daughter will be mine and then I\u2019ll make him writhe. I\u2019ll see him wriggle like a worm on a hook!\" the fifth \"Most Sinister Disney Villain Quote\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ohmy.disney.com/movies/2015/01/27/the-definitive-ranking-of-the-most-sinister-disney-villain-quotes/|title=THE DEFINITIVE RANKING OF THE MOST SINISTER DISNEY VILLAIN QUOTES|last=|first=|date=2015|website=Oh My Disney|publisher=Disney|access-date=April 24, 2016}}</ref> Meanwhile, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' included the [[Climax (narrative)|climactic]] sequence in which Ursula grows into a giant on the magazine's list of the \"12 Scariest Moments in Kids' Films\", comparing the sequence to the iconic [[shower scene]] in the horror film ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' (1960),<ref name=\":24\" /> while [[BuzzFeed]] ranked the character's death fifth on the website's \"Definitive Ranking Of The Most Horrific Disney Villain Deaths\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/jamesgrebey/jeez-these-movies-are-supposed-to-be-for-children#.gm4zJ4MoK|title=A Definitive Ranking Of The Most Horrific Disney Villain Deaths|last=Grebey|first=James|last2=Nedd|first2=Alexis|date=July 25, 2014|website=BuzzFeed|publisher=BuzzFeed, Inc|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref> In the wake of the release of ''[[Maleficent (film)|Maleficent]]'' (2014), a [[Live action|live-action]] remake of Disney's ''Sleeping Beauty'' (1959) told from the perspective of the film's villain, several publications voted for Ursula among Disney villains who deserve to star in their own films,<ref name=\":34\" /> including [[Yahoo! Movies]], [[MTV]], ''[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]'' and the ''[[New York Post]].''<ref name=\":32\" /><ref name=\":31\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1835420/7-disney-villains-who-deserve-live-action-movies/|title=7 DISNEY VILLAINS WHO WOULD MAKE THEIR OWN PRETTY WICKED MOVIES|last=Myers|first=Janelle|date=May 31, 2014|website=MTV|publisher=Viacom International Inc|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2014/05/27/5-disney-villains-who-should-get-their-own-movies/|title=5 Disney villains who should get their own movies|last=Miller|first=George E|date=May 27, 2014|website=New York Post|publisher=|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref> David Crow of [[Den of Geek]] selected actor [[John Travolta]] as his first choice for the role of Ursula because of his drag performance as Edna Turnblad in the film ''[[Hairspray (2007 film)|Hairspray]]'' (2007), a role actually originated by Divine, the actor upon whose appearance Ursula's design was based.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.us/movies/disney-villains/231142/6-disney-villains-who-deserve-their-own-movie|title=6 Disney Villains Who Deserve Their Own Movie|last=Crow|first=David|date=January 21, 2014|website=Den of Geek|publisher=|access-date=April 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nUrsula's body type has been positively embraced by the public; the character has since been recognized as a symbol of body positivity.<ref name=\":38\">{{Cite web|url=http://hellogiggles.com/life-lessons-learned-disney-villains/2/|title=6 Life Lessons I Learned From Disney Villains|last=|first=|date=July 22, 2014|website=HelloGiggles|publisher=|access-date=May 29, 2016}}</ref> [[HelloGiggles]] believes that \"Ursula has the most positive body image\" out of all of Disney's villainnesses: \"She may not be a size zero, like the other villains and heroines, but she\u2019s equally as confident. She is sexy, she is glamorous and she shows of her curves with no apology.\"<ref name=\":38\" /> From 2007 onwards, Disney launched an advertising campaign called ''Disney Dreams Portraits'' featuring celebrities dressed up as various Disney characters and photographer [[Annie Leibovitz]]; [[Queen Latifah]] was photographed as Ursula for this campaign in 2011.<ref>{{ cite web | first=Ann | last=Oldenburg | date=March 3, 2011 | title=Queen Latifah, Olivia Wilde become Disney characters | url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2011/03/queen-latifah-olivia-wilde-become-disney-characters/1#.V_2_siQw3D4 | publisher=USAToday.com | accessdate=October 12, 2016 }}</ref> In 2012 Disney released a Disney Villain line of dolls and make-up, and its revamped imagery was criticized for \"slimming down\" of Ursula to make her \"marketable\" and ignoring body diversity.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gray|first=Emma|date=2012-06-29|title=Disney Villains: Ursula Gets Slimmed Down For The New 'Designer Collection'|publisher=Huffington Post|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/emma-gray/disney-villains-little-mermaid-ursula-slimmed-down-designer-collection_b_1638895.html|accessdate=2009-12-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Leach|first=Michelle|date=2012-07-04|title= The Little Mermaid's Ursula gets controversial makeover|publisher=She Knows Entertainment|url=http://www.sheknows.com/entertainment/articles/965185/the-little-mermaids-ursula-gets-controversial-makeoverl|accessdate=2009-12-23}}</ref> For Halloween of 2013, [[Amber Riley]] portrayed Ursula in a celebrity parody/tribute of \"[[Cell Block Tango]]\" from ''[[Chicago (musical)|Chicago]]'' titled \"Spell Block Tango\", directed by [[Todrick Hall]], which was praised for its highlighting Disney villains.<ref>{{cite web|last=Emmanuele|first=Juana|title=5 Reasons We Love the Disney Animation/'Chicago' Masup Video 'Spell Block Tango'| publisher=Hollywood.com| date=2013-10-28|url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/celebrities/55039054/spell-block-tango-todrick-hall-chicago-disney|accessdate=2013-11-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Eby|first=Margaret|title=Disney villains sing 'Chicago' parody 'Spell Block Tango'|publisher=New York Daily News|date=2013-10-30|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music-arts/disney-villains-sing-chicago-parody-spell-block-tango-article-1.1502061|accessdate=2013-11-05}}</ref> [[Lady Gaga]] wore an Ursula-inspired dress during [[ArtRave: The Artpop Ball]]. In the 2015 season of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]'', [[Rumer Willis]] dressed up as Ursula to perform a samba set to \"[[Poor Unfortunate Souls]]\".<ref>{{cite web | first=Hal | last=Boedeker | title=Disney Night scores for 'Dancing,' ABC | date=2015-04-14 | url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/tv/tv-guy/os-disney-night-dancing-abc-20150414-post.html | publisher=OrlandoSentinel | accessdate=2015-04-15 }}</ref> As arguably \"the most famous example of a direct tie to the [[LGBT community]],\" Ursula has also become something of a [[gay icon]], due in part to sharing Divine's appearance and personality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/14-disney-characters-you-had-no-idea-were-gay051013/#gs.Iq6YR3k|title=The 16 Disney characters you had no idea were gay|last=Morgan|first=Joe|date=October 5, 2013|website=Gay Star News|publisher=Gay Star News|access-date=May 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{The Little Mermaid}}\n\n[[Category:The Little Mermaid (franchise) characters]]\n[[Category:Kingdom Hearts characters]]\n[[Category:Female characters in animation]]\n[[Category:Female film villains]]\n[[Category:Female characters in television]]\n[[Category:Film characters introduced in 1989]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who use magic]]\n[[Category:Fictional kidnappers]]\n[[Category:Fictional octopuses]]\n[[Category:Fictional shapeshifters]]\n[[Category:Fictional witches]]\n[[Category:Disney animated villains]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:Ursula (''The Little Mermaid'')}}  \n{{Infobox character\n| color              = #4f316a\n| name               = Ursula\n| series             = [[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]\n| image              = Ursula(TheLittleMermaid)character.png\n| caption            = \n| first              = ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'' (1989)\n| last               = \n| creator            = [[Ron Clements]]<br>[[John Musker]]\n| lbl1               = Based on\n| data1              = The Sea Witch from the [[Hans Christian Andersen]]'s [[The Little Mermaid|fairy tale]]\n| portrayer          = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Sherie Rene Scott]]<br>(''[[The Little Mermaid (musical)|Broadway musical]]'')\n*[[Queen Latifah]]<br>(''[[The Little Mermaid Live!]]'')}}\n| voice              = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Pat Carroll (actress)|Pat Carroll]] {{small|(as Ursula)}}<br>[[Jodi Benson]] {{small|(as Vanessa)}}<br>(''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'')\n*[[Whoopi Goldberg]]<br>(''[[Descendants 2]]'')}}\n| alias              = [[Vanessa]] {{small|(human alter-ego)}}\n| species            = [[Cecaelia]]\n| gender             = Female\n| occupation         = [[Magician (fantasy)|Sorceress]], [[Bargaining|faustian bargainer]]\n| affiliation        = [[List of Disney villains|Disney Villains]]\n| title              = The Sea Witch\n| relatives          = Unnamed father (dead) <br>Unnamed mother (dead) <br>[[Morgana (The Little Mermaid)|Morgana]] {{small|(younger sister)}}<br>Uma {{small|(daughter)}}\n| nationality        = Atlantican}}\n'''Ursula''' is a [[fiction]]al [[Character (arts)|character]] and the main [[Antagonist|antagonist]] of [[Walt Disney Pictures]]' 28th animated feature film ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'' (1989). Voiced by American actress [[Pat Carroll (actress)|Pat Carroll]], Ursula is a villainous [[sea witch]] who offers a [[mermaid]] princess named [[Ariel (Disney character)|Ariel]] in exchange to trade her voice for a pair of human legs, at first appearing to be providing the character with an opportunity to become human by temporarily transforming her into one so that she may earn the love of [[List of Disney's The Little Mermaid characters|Prince Eric]] within three days. However, Ursula is, in fact, determined to sabotage Ariel's chances so that she can ultimately replace [[King Triton (The Little Mermaid)|King Triton]] as ruler over Atlantica.\n\nCreated by directors and screenwriters [[Ron Clements]] and [[John Musker]], Ursula is based on the sea witch character who appears in the fairy tale \"[[The Little Mermaid]]\" by [[Hans Christian Andersen]]. However, her minor role was greatly expanded into that of a much more prominent villain for the film. Disney had struggled to cast Ursula for a year, during which the role was well sought after by several coveted television actresses at the time. Clements and Musker disagreed with lyricist [[Howard Ashman]] about who should voice the character. While the directors had written the role with [[Bea Arthur]] in mind, Ashman intended to offer it to [[soap opera]] star [[Joan Collins]]; both actresses rejected the part. When Ashman cast his second choice, Broadway actress [[Elaine Stritch]], as Ursula, both stage veterans disagreed about the manner in which Ursula's song \"[[Poor Unfortunate Souls]]\" would be performed, and [[Pat Carroll (actress)|Pat Carroll]] was finally hired to replace Stritch after Ashman fired her. Deepening her own voice for the role, Carroll based her performance on a combination of [[William Shakespeare|Shakespearean]] actresses and [[Car salesman|car salespeople]].\n\nAnimated by [[Ruben A. Aquino]], Ursula's original design was inspired by several different [[Marine biology|sea creatures]], including [[manta ray]]s and [[Scorpaeniformes|scorpion fish]], before Clements finally decided to base the character on an [[octopus]]; her number of [[tentacle]]s was reduced from eight to six for financial reasons. Ursula's appearance was also inspired by American actor and drag queen [[Divine (performer)|Divine]]. When ''The Little Mermaid'' was first released in 1989, Ursula was immediately embraced as one of Disney's best villains, and continues to be ranked highly among the studio's greatest by the media. Praised for being humorous and frightening, the character has garnered positive reviews from film critics, some of whom dubbed her Disney's strongest villain in decades. Meanwhile, Carroll's performance has garnered similar acclaim to the point that the role has eclipsed her previous body of work, ultimately becoming virtually synonymous with the character.\n\n==Development==\n\n===Conception and writing===\nAt the behest of Disney executives [[Michael Eisner]] and [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]], director and screenwriter [[Ron Clements]] was among several filmmakers instructed to research new story ideas that could potentially be adapted into the studio's next major animated film release.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.beliefnet.com/columnists/moviemom/2013/09/interview-ron-clements-john-musker-little-mermaid-disney.html|title=Interview: Ron Clements and John Musker of \"The Little Mermaid\"|last=Minow|first=Nell|date=|website=Beliefnet|publisher=Beliefnet, Inc|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Clements first discovered [[Hans Christian Andersen]]'s classic fairy tale \"[[The Little Mermaid]]\" at a local bookstore, and began deliberating why Disney had never attempted to adapt the story before.<ref name=\":2\" /> Clements eventually learned that [[Walt Disney]] himself had actually attempted to adapt the fairy tale into a feature-length animated film as early as the 1930s,<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moviefone.com/2014/11/14/the-little-mermaid-facts/|title='The Little Mermaid' Facts: 25 Things You Didn't Know About the Disney Masterpiece|last=Susman|first=Gary|date=November 14, 2014|website=Moviefone|publisher=Aol Inc|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> but the project was ultimately shelved due in part to its sad ending.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2015/03/15/10-things-you-probably-didnt-know-about-the-little-mermaid-5104832/|title=10 things you probably didn\u2019t know about The Little Mermaid|last=Duncan|first=Amy|date=March 15, 2010|website=Metro|publisher=|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> Clements suggested \"The Little Mermaid\" to Katzenberg, who finally [[Green-light|green-lit]] it after having first rejected it.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nHardly present in Andersen's original story,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emgn.com/entertainment/15-exciting-facts-about-the-little-mermaid-you-never-knew/|title=15 Exciting Facts About The Little Mermaid You Never Knew!|last=|first=|date=|website=EMGN|publisher=|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> the [[sea witch]] is not a prominent character and lacks a [[proper name]].<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://ohmy.disney.com/movies/2014/08/16/15-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-little-mermaid/|title=15 THINGS YOU DIDN\u2019T KNOW ABOUT THE LITTLE MERMAID|last=Brandon|first=Emily|date=2014|website=Oh My Disney|publisher=Disney|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Among Clements' ideas to alter the story, the filmmaker decided to \"make the witch more of a villain\", describing Ursula as \"a fun character to develop\" into such.<ref name=\":2\" /> In Andersen's tale, the sea witch is not a villain as much as she is \"a disreputable mermaid.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.disneyvillains.net/Ursula.php|title=Ursula \u2013 The Little Mermaid (1989)|last=|first=|date=|website=Disney Villains|publisher=Disney Villains|access-date=April 20, 2016}}</ref> JR Thorpe of ''[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]'' agreed that, in Andersen's story, \"The sea witch isn't the enemy\". Instead, \"[[Human nature|human ... nature]] is.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/65813-9-ways-the-original-little-mermaid-by-hans-christian-andersen-is-actually-seriously-disturbing|title=9 Ways The Original 'Little Mermaid' By Hans Christian Andersen Is Actually Seriously Disturbing|last=Thorpe|first=JR|date=February 25, 2015|website=Bustle|publisher=|access-date=April 22, 2016}}</ref> While the original sea witch is willing to help the little mermaid despite the fact that she openly disagrees with her motives, Ursula is only interested in helping Ariel in the hopes of ultimately overthrowing her father.<ref name=\":21\" /> Emma James of ''[[Teen Ink]]'' observed that in addition to giving the character the name \"Ursula\", the studio \"changed her role as a catalyst in the tale, and morphed her actions into those of an antagonist.\"<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.teenink.com/nonfiction/academic/article/586214/The-Evolution-of-the-Little-Mermaid/|title=The Evolution of the Little Mermaid|last=James|first=Emma|date=|website=Teen Ink|publisher=Emerson Media|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> Unlike the sea witch, Ursula deliberately intervenes in an attempt to keep the mermaid from success.<ref name=\":41\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vjdQBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA69&dq=ursula+matriarchy+disney&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj9ifCdzoPNAhVNNFIKHbTfDZUQ6AEIMDAE#v=onepage&q=ursula%20matriarchy%20disney&f=false|title=Emerson Goes to the Movies: Individualism in Walt Disney Company's Post-1989 Animated Films|last=Fruzi\u0144ska|first=Justyna|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|year=2014|isbn=9781443869157|location=United Kingdom|pages=69}}</ref>\n\nLyricist, producer and writer [[Howard Ashman]] had originally envisioned Ursula's relationship with [[King Triton (The Little Mermaid)|King Triton]] as a [[soap opera]], and thus drew inspiration from soap opera actress [[Joan Collins]].<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/67862/10-disney-characters-who-were-almost-voiced-lister|title=10 Disney Characters Who Were Almost Voiced By an A-Lister|last=Malach|first=Maggie|date=August 28, 2015|website=Mental Floss|publisher=Mental Floss, Inc|access-date=April 2, 2016}}</ref> Ursula was originally conceived as Triton's sister,<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://ca.movies.yahoo.com/blogs/wide-screen/5-disney-villains-who-deserve-their-own-movies-181045442.html|title=5 Disney Villains Who Deserve Their Own Movies|last=Perkins|first=Will|date=May 27, 2014|website=Yahoo! Movies|publisher=|access-date=April 28, 2016}}</ref> which would have naturally made the character Ariel's aunt,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/inarelationshipwithpizza/17things-you-probably-didnt-know-about-the-littl-7shb|title=17 Things You Probably Didn\u2019t Know About Disney\u2019s \"The Little Mermaid\"|last=|first=|date=December 4, 2012|website=BuzzFeed|publisher=BuzzFeed, Inc|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> but the idea was ultimately abandoned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.j-14.com/posts/10-totally-mind-blowing-facts-about-the-little-mermaid-17164/photos/the-little-mermaid-9-9728#photo-anchor|title=10 Totally Mind-Blowing Facts About 'The Little Mermaid'|last=Van de Wall|first=Virginia|date=October 1, 2013|website=J-14|publisher=|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> However, their [[blood relationship]] is still vaguely alluded to when the character mentions a time during which she actually lived in Triton's palace.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/59003/11-things-you-might-not-know-about-little-mermaid|title=11 Things You Might Not Know About 'The Little Mermaid'|last=Oneill|first=Therese|date=October 28, 2015|website=Mental Floss|publisher=Mental Floss, Inc|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> Clements and Musker had originally intended for Ursula to remain her original size at the end of the film.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/top/2529/8/The-Little-Mermaid-1989-50-things-you-might-not-know-about-your-favorite-Disney-films-1989-1997.html|title=50 things you might not know about your favorite Disney films, 1989-1997 edition|last=Hicken|first=Jackie|date=June 17, 2014|website=Desert News|publisher=|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> However, Katzenberg had just recently seen the film ''[[Die Hard]]'' (1988), which inspired him to request a \"bigger\" ending for ''The Little Mermaid'', and thus he instructed the writers to have Ursula grow much larger in size during her [[Climax (narrative)|climactic]] fight with Ariel and Eric.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n===Voice and music===\nUrsula is voiced by American actress and comedian [[Pat Carroll (actress)|Pat Carroll]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wic.org/bio/pcarroll.htm|title=Pat Carroll|last=|first=|date=|website=Women's International Center|publisher=|access-date=April 2, 2016}}</ref> Carroll was not the filmmakers' first choice for the role; Clements, Musker and Ashman had long debated who should voice the villainness,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2007/06/15/why-for-pat-carroll-wasn-t-actually-disney-s-first-choice-to-voice-ursula-in-the-little-mermaid.aspx|title=Why (For) Pat Carroll wasn't actually Disney's first choice to voice Ursula in \"The Little Mermaid\"|last=Hill|first=Jim|date=June 14, 2007|website=Jim Hill Media|publisher=|access-date=March 4, 2016}}</ref> the casting of whom was long and tedious, spanning an entire year.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=http://howardashman.com/blog/john-musker-question-countdown-number-7/|title=John Musker Question Countdown \u2013 Number 7|last=|first=|date=|website=Howard Ashman|publisher=Shoptalk Ltd|access-date=April 2, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/jim-hill/which-1980s-tv-favorites_b_6465252.html|title=Which 1980s TV Favorites Almost Voiced Ursula the Sea Witch for Disney\u2019s The Little Mermaid|last=hill|first=Jim|date=March 15, 2015|website=The Huffington Post|publisher=TheHuffingtonPost.com, Inc|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> In his book ''Makin' Toons: Inside the Most Popular Animated TV Shows and Movies'', author Allan Neuwirth documented that the filmmakers searched \"for just the right performer who could put across the deep-voiced, world-weary, [[deadpan]] villainness they had in mind\u2013but never quite snaring their catch\".<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xEctAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT253&dq=pat+carroll+ursula+the+little+mermaid&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiH7Yyt_-7LAhVDuoMKHQISB2sQ6AEIHDAA#v=onepage&q=pat%20carroll%20ursula%20the%20little%20mermaid&f=false|title=Makin' Toons: Inside the Most Popular Animated TV Shows and Movies|last=Neuwirth|first=Allan|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing, Inc|year=2013|isbn=9781621531975|location=United States|pages=|quote=|via=Google Books}}</ref> While Ashman was interested in actress [[Joan Collins]] because he was a fan of her performance as [[Alexis Colby]] in the [[soap opera]] ''[[Dynasty (1981 TV series)|Dynasty]]'',<ref name=\":1\" /> Clements and Musker favored actress [[Bea Arthur]], for whom they had actually written the role,<ref name=\":2\" /> describing Ursula as \"having a Bea Arthur-type [[Bass (voice type)|basso]] voice\" in early drafts of their screenplay.<ref name=\":0\"/> Clements and Musker expected Arthur to accept the role because she had already been working for Disney's [[Touchstone Television]] on the sitcom ''[[The Golden Girls]]''.<ref name=\":1\" /> However, Arthur's agent resented the directors-writers for insinuating that her client voice a witch,<ref name=\":1\" /> refusing to even present the script to the actress.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nWith Arthur eliminated, Clements and Musker were forced to audition several other popular television actresses of the decade, including [[Nancy Marchand]], [[Charlotte Rae]] and [[Roseanne Barr]],<ref name=\":0\" /> the last of whom had originally auditioned for the supporting role of chambermaid Carlotta.<ref name=\":11\"/> Amused by her [[nasal voice]], Howard invited the comedian to read for Ursula, but concluded that her approach was ultimately not suitable for the character.<ref name=\":12\"/> Jazz singer [[Nancy Wilson (jazz singer)|Nancy Wilson]] also auditioned.<ref name=\":1\" /> Meanwhile, Ashman himself had been similarly unsuccessful in recruiting Collins because ''Dynasty'' producer [[Aaron Spelling]] feared that the actress' reputation would be jeopardized should she voice an animated character.<ref name=\":1\" /> Thus, Ashman pursued [[Musical theatre|Broadway]] veteran [[Elaine Stritch]], of whom he had been a long-time fan.<ref name=\":0\" /> The audition process for Ursula required each hopeful to both recite a scene from the film and perform a Broadway-style song of their choice.<ref name=\":12\"/> The finalists became Clements and Musker's Rae versus Ashman's Stritch,<ref name=\":1\" /> the latter of whom ultimately won the role over Rae with her preferred rendition of Ursula's song \"[[Poor Unfortunate Souls]]\".<ref name=\":0\" /> Musker described Stritch's approach to Ursula as \"an eccentric, loopy reading\".<ref name=\":1\" /> However, Stritch and Ashman soon began to experience creative differences over \"Poor Unfortunate Souls\" because the actress refused to follow the lyricist's \"very specific directions\".<ref name=\":0\" /> After refusing to perform the song at Ashman's preferred tempo (combined with her [[alcoholism]]),<ref name=\":1\" /> the songwriter fired Stritch from the project,<ref name=\":12\"/> thus forcing Clements and Musker to find a replacement with yet another round of auditions.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nCarroll first learned of ''The Little Mermaid''<nowiki/> from her agent, and immediately agreed to audition for Ursula because she had always wanted to voice a [[Disney characters|Disney character]].<ref name=\":10\" /> However, the actress felt that her chances were slim to none upon realizing that her competition largely consisted of famous film and television actresses.<ref name=\":0\" /> Musker described Carroll's audition approach as a hybrid of actors [[Maurice Evans (actor)|Maurice Evans]] and [[Tallulah Bankhead]].<ref name=\":12\" /> Although confident in both her acting and singing auditions,<ref name=\":10\" /> Carroll did not hear back from her agent about the role until a year afterward, by which time she had already forgotten she had ever auditioned.<ref name=\":0\" /> Upon being cast, Carroll was entirely committed to the role, giving it complete precedence over all other jobs and projects at the time.<ref name=\":10\" /> Carroll's first task was to record \"Poor Unfortunate Souls\", her approach to which was remarkably different than Stritch's, first asking Howard to demonstrate exactly how he would like her to perform the song before attempting it.<ref name=\":0\" /> Carroll completely credits Ashman with her delivery,<ref name=\":4\" /> explaining, \"I got the whole attitude from him ... and his shoulders would twitch a certain way, and his eyes would go a certain way ... I got more about that character from Howard singing that song than from anything else.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Carroll also borrowed Ursula's habit of saying \"innit\" instead of \"isn't it\" from Ashman.<ref name=\":0\" /> Despite their strong working relationship, Carroll described working with Ashman and composer [[Alan Menken]] as a \"brutal\" experience because of the songwriters' \"military\" approach; she would often return home from recording sessions with blown vocal chords.<ref name=\":0\" /> Carroll recalled her daughter, filmmaker [[Tara Karsian]], reassuring her that \"you're in something that fifty years from now may be shown ... What you're working on now will be seen by our children, and our grandchildren, and our great-grandchildren\" after complaining to her about one of her recording sessions.<ref name=\":0\" /> Describing her own performance as [[William Shakespeare|Shakespearean]], Carroll perceived Ursula as an \"ex-Shakespearean actress who now sold cars\", which inspired her dry, theatrical interpretation.<ref name=\":0\" /> Carroll also deepened her own voice for the role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fast-rewind.com/making_littlemermaid.htm|title=Making Of...The Little Mermaid Behind The Scenes|website=The 80s Movies Rewind|publisher=Fast-Rewind.com|access-date=April 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107050713/http://www.fast-rewind.com/making_littlemermaid.htm|archive-date=November 7, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> When Carroll watched the completed film for the first time, she was frightened by her own performance, comparing it to actress [[Margaret Hamilton (actress)|Margaret Hamilton]]'s performance as the [[Wicked Witch of the West]] in the film ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' (1939).<ref name=\":10\" /> Actress [[Jodi Benson]], who voices Ariel, briefly provides the voice of \"Vanessa\", Ursula's beautiful human [[Alter ego|alter-ego]], in lieu of Carroll.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/jim-hill/this-little-mermaid-has-l_b_4323101.html|title=This \u2018Little Mermaid\u2019 Has Legs: Disney Legend Jodi Benson Looks Back on 25 Years of Voicing the Character of Ariel|last=Hill|first=Jim|date=November 22, 2013|website=The Huffington Post|publisher=TheHuffingtonPost.com, Inc|access-date=April 2, 2016}}</ref> With the writing and recording of \"Poor Unfortunate Souls\", Ursula became the first Disney villainness to receive her own song.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://ca.movies.yahoo.com/blogs/wide-screen/ranking-the-12-most-famous-disney-villains-from-worst-to-best-185848655.html|title=Ranking the 12 most famous Disney villains from worst to best|last=Perkins|first=Will|date=May 29, 2014|website=Yahoo! Movies|publisher=|access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, it was announced that [[Melissa McCarthy]] is in talks to play Ursula in the upcoming live-action remake of ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'', set to be directed by [[Rob Marshall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/melissa-mccarthy-little-mermaid-ursula-1203217481/|title=Melissa McCarthy in Talks to Play Ursula in Live-Action 'Little Mermaid' (EXCLUSIVE)|first=Justin|last=Kroll|date=28 June 2019|work=Variety|accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Design===\n\nDuring production of ''The Little Mermaid''<nowiki/>, Ursula's design evolved and transformed dramatically. Animator [[Glen Keane]]'s earliest sketches of Ursula were drawn to resemble Rae, specifically based on the actress' audition for the role.<ref name=\":12\" /> The short-lived casting of Stritch as Ursula and her subsequent performance eventually inspired the animators to design the character as \"a tall, thin regal-looking sea witch\" based on [[manta ray]]s and [[Scorpaeniformes|scorpion fish]], complete with a long cape.<ref name=\":0\" /> At one point, Ursula had also been drawn with spikes to resemble a [[Spikefish|spinefish]].<ref name=\":4\" /> Ursula's appearance was largely inspired by American actor and [[drag queen]] [[Divine (actor)|Divine]],<ref name=\":40\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pdCrF4JxKDIC&pg=PA182&dq=ursula+feminism+the+little+mermaid&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiEiLHm0oPNAhVBDlIKHQuyAdYQ6AEIHDAA#v=onepage&q=ursula%20feminism%20the%20little%20mermaid&f=false|title=From Mouse to Mermaid: The Politics of Film, Gender, and Culture|last=Bell|first=Elizabeth|last2=Haas|first2=Lynda|last3=Sells|first3=Laura|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=1995|isbn=9780253209788|location=United States|pages=182}}</ref> who was best known for his frequent appearances in several films directed by filmmaker [[John Waters]].<ref name=\":6\" /> Similarities were first drawn between the character and the actor after animator [[Rob Minkoff]] sketched \"a vampy overweight matron\", to which Ashman responded, \"She looks like a [[Miami Beach, Florida|Miami Beach]] matron ... playing [[Mahjong|Mah Jong]] by the pool.\u201d<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/article/read-how-divine-inspired-ursula-sea-witch-230938|title=Read This: How Divine inspired Ursula The Sea Witch|last=Dart|first=Chris|date=January 19, 2016|website=A. V. Club|publisher=Onion Inc|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> The character shares Divine's signature [[eye makeup]], jewelry and body type while originally sporting a [[Mohawk hairstyle|Mohawk]],<ref name=\":5\" /> the last of which was borrowed from the actor's ''[[Pink Flamingos|Pink Flamingo]]''[[Pink Flamingos|s]] (1972) character Babs Johnson.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=http://moviepilot.com/posts/2766413|title=(WATCH) Things you probably didn't know about \"The Little Mermaid\"|last=Portolan|first=Daniel|date=March 9, 2015|website=Moviepilot|publisher=|access-date=April 20, 2016}}</ref> However, Minkoff had been drawing the character with a shark's tail at the time.<ref name=\":5\" /> Clements eventually decided to place Ursula's head on top of the body of an octopus instead, which ultimately resulted in her current design.<ref name=\":2\" /> The animators then studied the way in which octopuses move, explaining, \"There was a very kind of seductive and yet scary aspect\", which they incorporated into the character's own gait.<ref name=\":2\" /> The ''Pink Flamingos''-inspired Mohawk was ultimately discarded because Disney felt that the hairstyle was \"too over-the-top\" for the film.<ref name=\":14\" /> Additionally, Ursula's face was also inspired by that of [[Madame Medusa]] from Disney's ''[[The Rescuers]]'' (1977)''.''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/movies/bp/17-things-didn-t-know-little-mermaid-201752088.html|title=17 Things You Didn\u2019t Know About \u2018The Little Mermaid\u2019|last=Min|first=Lilian|date=September 20, 2013|website=Yahoo!|publisher=|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> According to ''The Gospel according to Disney: Faith, Trust, and Pixie Dust'' author Mark I. Pinsky, Ursula became \"the most [[Grotesque body|grotesque]] characterization Disney ... have created for a female villain\" at that time.<ref name=\":44\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N551BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA140&dq=ursula+norma+desmond&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiHubjqw4fNAhXF6YMKHVVJCXYQ6AEIMTAD#v=onepage&q=ursula%20norma%20desmond&f=false|title=The Gospel according to Disney: Faith, Trust, and Pixie Dust|last=Pinsky|first=Mark I.|publisher=Westminster John Knox Press|year=2004|isbn=9781611644272|location=United Kingdom|pages=140}}</ref>\n\nHaving animated previous Disney villains, Keane was originally approached to be the supervising animator of Ursula, but declined in favor of animating Ariel because he longed to do something different.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aimeemajor.com/anim/aagleninterview.html|title=Glen Keane Interview August 22, 1990|last=|first=|date=August 22, 1990|website=AimeeMajor.com|publisher=|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> Thus, Keane was replaced by [[Ruben A. Aquino]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dvdizzy.com/littlemermaid-platinumeditionb.html|title=The Little Mermaid: Platinum Edition DVD Review|last=|first=|date=October 3, 2006|website=DVDizzy.com|publisher=DVDizzy.com|access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> The character was originally drawn with a full set of eight tentacles similar to a real-life octopus, which were eventually reduced to a more manageable six because the original amount would have been too difficult and costly to animate.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{cite web|url=http://thefw.com/things-you-didnt-know-about-disneys-the-little-mermaid/|title=10 Things You Didn\u2019t Know About Disney\u2019s \u2018The Little Mermaid\u2019|last=Franks-Allen|first=Sara|date=|website=The FW|publisher=SCREENCRUSH NETWORK|access-date=April 1, 2016}}</ref> According to Carroll,<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://deaditeden.com/2015/11/18/happy-26th-birthday-to-the-little-mermaid-here-are-a-few-facts-you-didnt-know/|title=Happy 26th birthday to The Little Mermaid! Here are a few facts you didn\u2019t know|date=November 18, 2015|website=Deadite Den|access-date=April 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508133235/https://deaditeden.com/2015/11/18/happy-26th-birthday-to-the-little-mermaid-here-are-a-few-facts-you-didnt-know/|archive-date=May 8, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> this modification actually makes the character more similar to a [[squid]] than an octopus;<ref name=\":9\" /> whether or not Ursula is an octopus continues to be debated among both critics and devout fans, some of whom believe that the character's pair of arms actually account for the remaining two tentacles.<ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":15\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.people.com/article/the-little-mermaid-25th-anniversary|title=Celebrate 25 Years of The Little Mermaid with 25 Things Even Superfans May Not Know|last=Mackie|first=Drew|date=November 14, 2014|website=People|publisher=Time Inc|access-date=April 22, 2016}}</ref> Clements admitted that the character's six tentacles made animating her a challenge nonetheless.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jetsettingmom.com/creating-disney-classic-interview-jon-musker-ron-clements-writers-directors-little-mermaid/|title=Creating a Disney Classic \u2013 Interview with John Musker & Ron Clements, writers & directors of The Little Mermaid!|last=|first=|date=September 11, 2013|website=Jet-Setting Mom|publisher=JETSETTING MOM|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> Ursula was intentionally designed to instill fear in ''The Little Mermaid''<nowiki/>'s viewers.<ref name=\":37\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.techtimes.com/articles/20379/20141117/the-little-mermaid-ursula-disney-villains.htm|title=Why Ursula From 'The Little Mermaid' is the Scariest Disney Villain|last=Rosenfeld|first=Laura|date=November 17, 2014|website=Tech Times|publisher=TechTimes Inc|access-date=May 26, 2016}}</ref> Animators studied [[The Terrible Dogfish|Monstro]] from Disney's ''[[Pinocchio (1940 film)|Pinocchio]]'' (1940) in order to animate the character's enlarged self emerging from the sea.<ref name=\":4\" /> Ursula's appearance was also based on that of the character [[Sunset Boulevard (film)|Norma Desmond]], who appears in the film ''[[Sunset Boulevard (film)|Sunset Boulevard]]'' (1950).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wx8JsmNxjcUC&pg=PA286&dq=ursula+norma+desmond&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiHubjqw4fNAhXF6YMKHVVJCXYQ6AEIUjAJ#v=onepage&q=ursula%20norma%20desmond&f=false|title=Film Theory Goes to the Movies: Cultural Analysis of Contemporary Film|last=Collins|first=Jim|last2=Collins|first2=Ava Preacher|last3=Radner|first3=Hilary|publisher=Routledge|year=2012|isbn=9781135216450|location=United Kingdom|pages=286}}</ref> Divine never lived to see his own likeness appear in ''The Little Mermaid''; the actor died in 1988, one year before the film's release.<ref name=\":5\" /> However, his cohorts agree that Divine would have greatly enjoyed Ursula.<ref name=\":5\" /> Documentarian [[Jeffrey Schwarz|Jeffrey Schwartz]] joked that the actor would have wanted to play Ursula himself had he known about the character, having once told Waters \"When I was young, all I wanted to be was a Disney villain\".<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==Characterization and themes==\n[[About.com]]'s David Nusair observed that \"There\u2019s no limit to how low Ursula will stoop to achieve her goals\";<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=http://movies.about.com/od/animatedmovies/tp/disney-villains.htm|title=Top 10 Disney Villains|last=Nusair|first=David|date=|website=About.com|publisher=About.com|access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> the character often relies on a combination of [[Witchcraft|sorcery]] and deception to achieve them.<ref name=\":26\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.tvovermind.com/movies/ranking-top-10-animated-disney-villains|title=Ranking the Top 10 Animated Disney Villains|last=|first=|date=March 30, 2016|website=TVOvermind|publisher=TVOvermind|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> \"A bargainer of the worst kind\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://moviepilot.com/posts/1464097|title=Top Ten: Disney Animated Villains!|last=Eguizabal|first=William|date=June 1, 2014|website=Moviepilot|publisher=|access-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref> Ursula only agrees to help the less fortunate when she's confident that she can gain something from them in return.<ref name=\":27\">{{Cite web|url=http://theodysseyonline.com/ksu/10-best-worst-disney-villains/344551|title=The 10 Best (Worst) Disney Villains|last=Nouryeh|first=Elizabeth|date=March 7, 2016|website=The Odyssey|publisher=Olympia Media Group|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> Identifying Ursula as Ariel's binary due to the character's experience and authority, ''Collision of Realities: Establishing Research on the Fantastic in Europe'' author Lars Schmeink described Ursula as a \"more complex and mature character\" than Ariel, embodying everything that the mermaid can potentially become.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t1znBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA140&dq=ursula+the+little+mermaid+feminist&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjylJir8aXMAhXG5xoKHUIlAtoQ6AEILTAD#v=onepage&q=ursula%20the%20little%20mermaid%20feminist&f=false|title=Collision of Realities: Establishing Research on the Fantastic in Europe|last=Schmeink|first=Lars|last2=B\u00f6ger|first2=Astrid|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|year=2012|isbn=9783110276718|location=Germany|pages=140}}</ref> To Ariel, Ursula represents \"the matronly image\" who \"instigate[s] the young princess' epic journey\" as she longs to achieve the witch's \"[[Sage (philosophy)|sage]]-like knowledge and power\".<ref name=\":20\" /> Ursula teaches Ariel about [[womanhood]], a theme ''From Mouse to Mermaid: The Politics of Film, Gender, and Culture'' author Elizabeth Belle noticed is absent in Anderson's story.<ref name=\":40\" /> According to Bell, \"Ursula can retrieve Ariel from her destined alliance with patriarchy\", observing that the witch actually \"teaches Ariel that performance and voice and manifestations\" are \"liberations of gender\".<ref name=\":40\" /> ''[[Teen Ink]]''<nowiki/>'s Emma James believes that Ursula's death ultimately prevents Ariel from experiencing and learning from the consequences of her actions, concluding, \"Ariel never really owns up to all the mishap she caused.\"<ref name=\":25\" /> Observing that Ursula actually warns Ariel about the consequences should she fail to earn a kiss from Eric, Laura Stampler of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' described the character as a \"savvy contract negotiator\".<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/3586569/sexist-little-mermaid/|title=The Little Mermaid: Not as Sexist as You Thought It Was|last=Stampler|first=Laura|last2=Dockterman|first2=Eliana|date=November 17, 2014|website=Time|publisher=Time Inc|access-date=April 22, 2016}}</ref> Writing for [[Collider (website)|Collider]], Dave Trumbore identified Ursula as the film's \"Crossroads Demon\".<ref name=\":35\">{{Cite web|url=https://collider.com/best-disney-villains/#ursula|title=Disney\u2019s 9 Most Wicked Animated Villains|last=Foutch|first=Haleigh|date=April 24, 2016|website=Collider.com|publisher=COMPLEX MEDIA INC|access-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref> According to Gary Thompson of the ''[[Philadelphia Daily News]]'', Ursula is similar to businesswoman [[Leona Helmsley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/1989-11-17/entertainment/26137106_1_young-mermaid-evil-sea-witch-samuel-e-wright|title=Back To The Drawing Boards Disney Regains Form With 'Mermaid' Tale|last=Thompson|first=Gary|date=November 17, 1989|website=Philly.com|publisher=|access-date=April 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n''Makin' Toons: Inside the Most Popular Animated TV Shows and Movies'' author Allan Neuwirth observed that Ursula obeys Disney's \"long-standing tradition of depicting classic scoundrels ... none so unsettling as their female villains.\"<ref name=\":10\" /> Neuwirth believes that the public's fear of Disney's female villains \"stems from our expectations of nurturing, comfort and honesty from our mothers\",<ref name=\":10\" /> while Disney's villainnesses, including Ursula, tend to \"lust after ... youth and beauty.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dFR9aLIA3g8C&pg=PA34&dq=ursula+matriarchy+disney&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj9ifCdzoPNAhVNNFIKHbTfDZUQ6AEIKzAD#v=onepage&q=ursula%20matriarchy%20disney&f=false|title=Mommy Angst: Motherhood in American Popular Culture: Motherhood in American Popular Culture|last=Bishop|first=Mardia J.|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2009|isbn=9780313375316|location=United States|pages=33}}</ref> Ursula even goes as far as transforming herself into a beautiful young woman in order to trick Ariel's love interest into marrying her instead.<ref name=\":43\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Q5UVgMLxWcC&pg=PA67&dq=ursula+feminism+the+little+mermaid&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiqyJOorIfNAhVGyoMKHZXeBlYQ6AEIOTAF#v=onepage&q=ursula%20feminism%20the%20little%20mermaid&f=false|title=Bloody Mary in the Mirror: Essays in Psychoanalytic Folkloristics|last=Dundes|first=Alan|publisher=Univ. Press of Mississippi|year=2008|isbn=9781604731873|location=United States|pages=55\u201375}}</ref> Janet Wasko believes that Ursula's role as a powerful but antagonistic woman in ''The Little Mermaid'' alludes to the idea of [[patriarchy]] being preferable to [[matriarchy]].<ref name=\":42\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GQfk_5oMrCcC&pg=PT128&dq=ursula+matriarchy+disney&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj9ifCdzoPNAhVNNFIKHbTfDZUQ6AEIIjAB#v=onepage&q=ursula%20matriarchy%20disney&f=false|title=Understanding Disney: The Manufacture of Fantasy|last=Wasko|first=Janet|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2013|isbn=9780745669045|location=United States|pages=}}</ref> Sophie Hall of [[Beamly]] identified Ursula as a woman struggling to \"run the kingdom in a man\u2019s world, having been kicked out for no specific reason.\"<ref name=\":28\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.beamly.com/tv-film/8-disney-villains-better-heroes|title=8 Disney villains who are better than the heroes|last=Hall|first=Sophie|date=July 9, 2015|website=Beamly|publisher=|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> In her book ''Emerson Goes to the Movies: Individualism in Walt Disney Company's Post-1989 Animated Films'', author Justyna Fruzi\u0144ska claimed that \"the masculine rule of Triton is presented as positive and opposed to the negative, feminine rule of Ursula\".<ref name=\":41\" /> ''Understanding Disney: The Manufacture of Fantasy'' author Janet Wasko accused the film's treatment of Ursula of \"eliminat[ing] many of the female characters and undermin[ing] [the] feminine power\" present in Andersen's fairy tale.<ref name=\":42\" /> However, Wasko also argued that Ursula could possibly be considered a [[mother figure]] for Ariel;<ref name=\":42\" /><ref name=\":43\" /> the tunnel of Ursula's cave resembles a [[vagina]], while Ursula's mannerisms evoke those of a mother as she refers to Ariel as \"my dear sweet child\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lvKUm7D2vckC&pg=PA158&dq=ursula+feminism+the+little+mermaid&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiqyJOorIfNAhVGyoMKHZXeBlYQ6AEINDAE#v=onepage&q=ursula%20feminism%20the%20little%20mermaid&f=false|title=Shakespeare Survey: Volume 56, Shakespeare and Comedy: An Annual Survey of Shakespeare Studies and Production|last=Holland|first=Peter|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2003|isbn=9780521827270|location=England|pages=158}}</ref> Gwynne Watkins of [[Yahoo!]] accused Ursula of \"assur[ing] Ariel that human men prefer their women to be silent\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/movies/its-time-to-see-the-little-mermaid-as-a-feminist-102969568407.html|title=It's Time to See 'The Little Mermaid' as a Feminist Film|last=Watkins|first=Gwynne|date=November 18, 2014|website=Yahoo!|publisher=|access-date=April 23, 2014}}</ref> Meanwhile, in response to feminist critiques of the character, author Amy M. Davis observed in her book ''Handsome Heroes and Vile Villains: Masculinity in Disney's Feature Films'' that Ursula is actually responsible for giving Eric the \"power to make Ariel permanently human\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0OQoCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA169&dq=ursula+the+little+mermaid+feminist&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjylJir8aXMAhXG5xoKHUIlAtoQ6AEINzAF#v=onepage&q=ursula%20the%20little%20mermaid%20feminist&f=false|title=Handsome Heroes and Vile Villains: Masculinity in Disney's Feature Films|last=Davis|first=Amy M|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2014|isbn=9780861969074|location=2014|pages=170}}</ref> However, author Alan Dundes in his book ''Bloody Mary in the Mirror: Essays in Psychoanalytic Folkloristics'' in conjunction with co-author Lauren Dundes observed that Ursula becomes masculine and deep-voiced once she acquires Triton's trident, implying that even \"the only powerful woman in the story fulfills her desire for supreme power by becoming masculine\".<ref name=\":43\" /> Dundes and Dundes also observed that Ursula reverts to being feminine once she is impaled.<ref name=\":43\" />\n\nIn her book ''Tales, Then and Now: More Folktales as Literary Fictions for Young Adults'', author Anna E. Altmann compared Ursula to [[Satan]] because both Ariel and Triton \"sign a contract ... with her\";<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TK0fOeuFiA0C&pg=PA194&dq=ursula+the+little+mermaid+feminist&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjylJir8aXMAhXG5xoKHUIlAtoQ6AEIHDAA#v=onepage&q=ursula%20the%20little%20mermaid%20feminist&f=false|title=Tales, Then and Now: More Folktales as Literary Fictions for Young Adults|last=Altmann|first=Anna E|publisher=Libraries Unlimited|year=2001|isbn=9781563088315|location=United States|pages=194}}</ref> James Plath of Movie Metropolis described Ursula's contract as \"a Mephistophelean bargain.\"<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=http://moviemet.com/review/little-mermaid-3d-blu-ray-review |title=THE LITTLE MERMAID - 3D Blu-ray review |last=Plath |first=James |date=September 28, 2013 |website=Movie Metropolis |publisher=Movie Metropolis |access-date=April 25, 2016 |quote=Ursula\u2014one of the stronger Disney villains in the past several decades\u2014gets her to sign on the dotted line of a Mephistophelean bargain. |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140208010138/http://moviemet.com/review/little-mermaid-3d-blu-ray-review |archivedate=February 8, 2014 }}</ref> Much like Satan, Ursula was banished from Triton's palace, similar to the way in which [[Lucifer]] was exiled from heaven.<ref name=\":44\" /> Felix Vasquez of Cinema Crazed believes that Ursula \"is evil just for the sake of being evil\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cinema-crazed.com/blog/2013/09/30/the-little-mermaid-1989/|title=The Little Mermaid (1989)|last=Vasquez|first=Felix|date=September 30, 2013|website=Cinema Crazed|publisher=Cinema Crazed|access-date=April 18, 2016}}</ref> Writing for the [[Disney.com|Disney Archives]], Dave Smith observed that Ursula \"has the gross unsubtlety of Ratigan from '[[The Great Mouse Detective]]' but substantially more brio.\"<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=http://disney.go.com/vault/archives/villains/ursula/ursula.html |title=Ursula |last=Smith |first=Dave |website=Disney Archives |publisher=Disney |access-date=April 19, 2016 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100331195110/http://disney.go.com/vault/archives/villains/ursula/ursula.html |archivedate=March 31, 2010 }}</ref> Describing Ursula as \"Bejeweled and lip-pouting like an overweight, over-rich, over-pampered, over-the-top society hostess gone mad,\" Smith perceived the character as \"all flair, flamboyance, and theatricality mixed with a touch of con-artistry\", citing [[Anger|wrath]] as her only genuine emotion.<ref name=\":13\" /> Additionally, Ursula tends to act as though she is performing for an audience.<ref name=\":13\" /> Jay Boyar of the ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'' compared the character's appearance to that of evangelist [[Tammy Faye Messner|Tammy Faye]].<ref name=\":19\" /> At times, Ursula tends to demonstrate stereotypically masculine physical traits.<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.threemoviebuffs.com/review/little-mermaid|title=The Little Mermaid|last=|first=|date=January 21, 2015|website=Three Movie Buffs|publisher=Three Movie Buffs|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> Describing the character as \"A campy sea witch with an insatiable thirst for power\", ''[[Rolling Stone]]''<nowiki/>'s David Ehrlich believes that Ursula resembles a child of Divine and [[Donald Trump]].<ref name=\":24\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/lists/12-scariest-moments-in-kids-films-20151019/the-little-mermaid-1989-ursula-supersized-20151019|title=12 Scariest Moments in Kids' Films|last=Ehrlich|first=David|date=October 19, 2015|website=Rolling Stone|publisher=Rolling Stone|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> Some critics identify the character with body positivity. According to Michaela Glover of ''The Odyssey'', ''\"''Ursula portrays a bold business woman, not being afraid to show off her curves and use them, which defies the typical standards of beauty by also being a full figured woman.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theodysseyonline.com/spelman/its-good-to-be-bad/260365|title=Why Disney Female Villains Are Iconic Feminists|last=Glover|first=Michaela|date=December 27, 2015|website=The Odyssey|publisher=Olympia Media Group|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Appearances==\n\n===Film===\nUrsula debuted in ''[[The Little Mermaid (1989 film)|The Little Mermaid]]'' (1989) as a sea witch who is scheming to take advantage of the ambitions of King Triton's youngest daughter Princess Ariel in order to usurp the throne and turning merpeople into polyps for her garden. When Ariel saves and falls in love with a human named Prince Eric much to her father's chagrin, Ursula temporarily grants Ariel's wish to live as a human for three days in return for her voice. If she successfully earns a kiss from Eric by the end of the third day, Ariel will remain human permanently; if she fails, she will turn back into a mermaid and belong to Ursula forever. However, Ursula is determined to sabotage Ariel's and Eric's budding romance at any cost; when she realizes that Ariel and Eric are falling in love, Ursula transforms herself into a beautiful young woman named \"Vanessa\" and hypnotizes Eric, tricking him into agreeing to marry her instead. Ariel manages to thwart Ursula and Eric's wedding. Eric realizes that it was Ariel who saved him when her voice returns to her and is about to kiss her, but as the sun sets Ariel transforms back into a mermaid and is captured by Ursula. Triton confronts Ursula and agrees to give up himself and his magical trident in return for Ariel's freedom. Ursula then uses the trident to expand into monstrous proportions and attempts to kill Ariel and Eric, but Eric manages to impale Ursula with the splintered bowsprit of a wrecked ship, and she dies. With Ursula defeated, her power's cease, the merpeople turn back to normal, Triton's power is restored, and Ariel marries Eric once she is permanently transformed into a human.\n\n===Television series===\n{{main|The Little Mermaid (TV series)}}\nUrsula appears as the antagonist in four episodes of ''[[The Little Mermaid (TV series)|The Little Mermaid]]'' prequel television series: \"Against the Tide\", \"Tail of Two Crabs\", \"Heroes\" and \"Ariel's Treasures\". In all four episodes, she executes various plans to antagonize King Triton and take over Atlantica, but all fail.  \n\n===''The Little Mermaid II: Return to the Sea''===\n{{Main|The Little Mermaid II: Return to the Sea}}\n\nUrsula does not appear in the direct-to-video film ''[[The Little Mermaid II: Return to the Sea]]'' because she is killed in the first film, but she is mentioned many times, mostly by her younger sister [[Morgana (The Little Mermaid)|Morgana]], also voiced by Pat Carroll. In the family portrait during the cut song \"Gonna Get My Wish\", Ursula was also depicted with light green skin similar to Morgana and their mother.\n\n==In other media==\nUrsula appears in Disney park attractions such as the ''[[Fantasmic!]]'' show debuted in 1992 at Disneyland Park, as one of the [[Disney Villains]] summoned to destroy [[Mickey Mouse]]. A massive Ursula [[Audio-Animatronics|Audio-Animatronic]] appears in [[The Little Mermaid ~ Ariel's Undersea Adventure]], a dark ride at [[Disney California Adventure]], and [[Magic Kingdom]]. Ursula is a central character in the annual [[Halloween]]-themed [[fireworks]] show [[HalloWishes]] at the [[Walt Disney World]] [[Magic Kingdom]] ''[[Mickey's Not-So-Scary Halloween Party]]'' \"hard ticket\" event. Ursula also appears at the tail end of the ''Little Mermaid'' unit in [[Walt Disney's Parade of Dreams]] at [[Disneyland]].\n\nIn the ''[[Kingdom Hearts (video game)|Kingdom Hearts]]'' video game, Ursula appears as one of [[Maleficent (Disney)|Maleficent]]'s co-conspirators, using the power of the [[Heartless (Kingdom Hearts)|Heartless]] to attack Atlantica and gain power. In this version of events, the official walkthrough states that Ursula was King Triton's fortuneteller before she was banished. Ursula is eventually defeated by [[Sora (Kingdom Hearts)|Sora]], Ariel, [[Donald Duck]] and [[Goofy]]. In ''[[Kingdom Hearts: Chain of Memories]]'', she appears as a [[facsimile]] created from Sora's memories. In ''[[Kingdom Hearts II]]'', Ursula mysteriously returns through the powers of darkness and appears to Ariel, and recreates her film role. As the film's storyline is retold in the game, Ursula does not recognize Sora and company, and Ariel makes no mention of her defeat in the original ''Kingdom Hearts''. In fact, when Ursula arrives to make the deal with Ariel, the latter reacts as though she has seen Ursula for the first time. Sora, however, does note that Ursula \"got what she deserved\" in the first game. At the story's climax, she is defeated when Eric hurls the trident straight through Ursula's chest, destroying her seemingly once and for all. However, she reappears in the ''[[Kingdom Hearts 3D: Dream Drop Distance]]'', confronting Sora and Riku out at sea in her giant form from the end of the movie. The game gives conflicting hints on whether or not this Ursula is the \"real one,\" and serves a very small role, providing the tutorial to the game's battle system and delivering a line that foreshadows the plot of the game's main antagonist, Xehanort.\n\nShe has appeared for the concept art from [[Epic Mickey]] in 2010. When Ursula tries to kidnap Gremlin Gus, Mickey comes to the rescue and saved him from trying to let go of her clutches.\n\nUrsula appeared occasionally in the animated television series ''[[Disney's House of Mouse]]'' (2001) as one of Mickey's guests at the night club. In the feature film ''[[Mickey's House of Villains]]'' she participated in the musical number \"It's Our House Now\" alongside other Disney villains, and is one of Jafar's henchmen.<ref>{{cite AV media|people =Jamie Mitchell|title =Mickey's House of Villains|medium =Television production|publisher =Walt Disney Television Animation|location =USA|date = 2002}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, [[Rebel Wilson]] performed the role of Ursula at a stripped-down concert version of ''The Little Mermaid'' at the [[Hollywood Bowl]], which featured the songs from the film and four songs from the Broadway musical.<ref>{{ cite web | first=Jenelle | last=Riley | date=2016-06-04 | title=L.A. Theater Review: \u2018The Little Mermaid in Concert\u2019 at the Hollywood Bowl | url=https://variety.com/2016/legit/reviews/little-mermaid-in-concert-at-the-hollywood-bowl-1201788875/ | publisher=Variety.com | accessdate=2016-06-22 }}</ref> Wilson was praised for her performance, which was described by The Huffington Post as \"pitch perfect\".<ref>{{ cite web | first=Hayley | last=Cuccinello | title=Rebel Wilson Is The Ursula We Always Wanted In \u2018The Little Mermaid Live\u2019 | date=2016-06-06 | url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/rebel-wilson-is-the-ursula-we-always-wanted-in-the-little-mermaid-live_us_57556b31e4b0c3752dce06b9 | accessdate=2016-06-22 }}</ref> [[Queen Latifah]] portrayed Ursula in the 2019 television special, ''[[The Little Mermaid Live!]]'' which used a similar format of the live concerts at the Hollywood Bowl, by combining a screening of the film with live accompaniment by guest musicians and celebrities.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/little-mermaid-live-starring-aulii-cravalho-set-at-abc-1229130 |title=Little Mermaid' Live Starring Auli'i Cravalho Set at ABC |last=Bentley |first=Jean |date=August 5, 2019 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016044739/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/little-mermaid-live-starring-aulii-cravalho-set-at-abc-1229130 |archive-date=October 16, 2019 |access-date=October 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Books===\nUrsula has appeared in various Disney Press novels and tie-ins for the franchise. A comic book series \"Disney's The Little Mermaid\" was released in 1992, revolving around the adventures of Ariel living under the sea as a mermaid. Ursula appears in a few issues, notably \"Serpent Teen\", which depicts how Ursula obtained the sea serpent carcass that makes her home.<ref>{{cite comic|writer=Peter David|penciller=Bill Fugate|inker=Dave Hunt|title=Serpent Teen|volume=1|issue=1|date=1992|publisher=Walt Disney Magazine Publishing Group}}</ref> ''My Side of the Story: Ursula'' (2004) retells the plot of the film from Ursula's point of view, and depicts Ursula having romantic feelings for Triton.<ref>{{cite book|last=Skinner|first=Daphne|title=My Side of the Story: Ursula|publisher=Disney Press|date=2004|location=New York|isbn=0-7868-3503-6|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/mysideofstory00skin}}</ref> ''The Villain Files'' (2005) depicts Ursula's youth living in Triton's castle while Ariel was a baby.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pringle|first=Betsy Henry|title=Disney Villains: The Top Secret Files|publisher=Disney Press|date=2005|location=New York|isbn=0-7868-3603-2}}</ref>\n\nUrsula is a main character in the 2016 [[young adult fiction|young adult]] novel ''Poor Unfortunate Soul: A Tale of the Sea Witch'' by [[Serena Valentino]].<ref>{{ cite web | title=Poor Unfortunate Soul: A Tale of the Sea Witch | url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/1484724054 | publisher=amazon.com | accessdate=2016-04-10 }}</ref><ref>{{ cite web | title=Serena Valentino (official website): Poor Unfortunate Soul | url=http://www.serenavalentino.com/projects/ursula/ | accessdate=2016-04-10 }}</ref> The novel is the third entry of the \"Villains\" series, a shared universe that [[Crossover (fiction)|crosses over]] various theatrical Disney films including ''[[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]'', ''[[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937 film)|Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs]]'' and ''[[Sleeping Beauty (1959 film)|Sleeping Beauty]]''. In this novel, Ursula is King Triton's younger sister who was betrayed by him as a child for choosing a tentacled form instead of a mermaid's tail, and grew up as a human in the town of Ipswich with an adoptive human father. Ursula returned to the sea when her adopted father was killed by the townsfolk for protecting her, befriending Athena, Queen of Atlantica, but was denied her inheritance by Triton and banished to the shadows. Ursula conspires with three other witches to steal Triton's soul and become ruler of all the seas, but is ultimately defeated.<ref>{{ cite book | first=Serena | last=Valentino | date=2016 | title=Poor Unfortunate Soul | publisher=Disney Press | ISBN=9781484724057 }}</ref>\n\n===Broadway musical===\n{{main|The Little Mermaid (musical)}}\nIn the [[The Little Mermaid (musical)|musical version]] of the original film, [[Sherie Rene Scott]] originated the live role, which she played until January 25, 2009. Other actresses who played the role are [[Heidi Blickenstaff]]  and [[Faith Prince]].\n\nIn this version, Ursula is King Triton's sister, a concept for the original film that was eventually dropped.<ref>(2006) ''Treasures Untold: The Making of Disney's 'The Little Mermaid'' [Documentary featurette]. Bonus material from ''The Little Mermaid: Platinum Edition'' DVD. Walt Disney Home Entertainment.</ref> When Ursula and Triton's father died, the pair were given equal share of the sea plus two magical items: Triton received the trident while Ursula received the magic Nautilus shell. Though the two were meant to rule the seas together, Ursula's greed and use of dark magic to usurp Triton led to her being banished. The desire for revenge and power is her motivation for the show. The musical's plot is similar to the film, with the exceptions that Ursula doesn't transform into Vanessa, and Ursula is ultimately defeated by Ariel, when the mermaid destroys the Nautilus shell that contains Ursula's power. In the revamped version of the musical developed by Glenn Casale in 2012, Ursula and Triton's backstory was changed, making them the seventh and eighth of eight siblings respectively. Ursula killed their older siblings one by one until she became a queen, and she forgot about Triton until he became old enough to depose her and become king. Ursula's motivation for revenge otherwise remains similar to the original book of the musical, with the addition that she was the one who killed Ariel's mother.\n\nIn addition to her song from the film, [[Alan Menken]] and [[Glenn Slater]] wrote new songs for Ursula: \"I Want the Good Times Back\", which introduces Ursula and her backstory, \"I Want the Good Times Back (reprise)\", where Ursula orders Flotsam and Jetsam to sabotage Ariel's attempt to get Eric to kiss her, and a reprise of \"Poor Unfortunate Souls\", where Ursula forces Triton to sign a deal and claims the trident. In the workshop stage, Ursula had a different introductory song: \"Wasting Away\", and its reprise featured Ursula preparing to transform into Vanessa.<ref name=\"book\">{{cite book|last=Lassell|first=Michael|title =The Little Mermaid: A Broadway Musical - From the Deep Blue Sea to the Great White Way|publisher =Disney Editions New York|year =2009|isbn =978-1-4231-1272-3}}</ref> [[Emily Skinner (actress, born 1970)|Emily Skinner]] provided vocals for Ursula in the workshop.<ref name=\"book\" /> In the 2012 revamped version of the musical, \"I Want the Good Times Back\" is replaced with a new song, \"Daddy's Little Angel\".<ref name=\"casale\">{{ cite web | last=Hill | first=Jim | title=How Glenn Casale Helped The Little Mermaid Find Her Feet After This Disney Stage Show Stumbled on Broadway | date=2014-07-23 | url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/jim-hill/how-glenn-casale-helped-t_b_5612802.html | publisher=Huffington Post | accessdate=2016-08-05 }}</ref>\n\n===''Once Upon a Time''===\n{{Infobox character\n|color      = #d6d6ff\n|series     = Once Upon a Time\n|name       = Ursula the Sea Witch\n|image      = Ursula once upon a time.png\n|first      = \"[[Heroes and Villains (Once Upon a Time)|Heroes and Villains]]\" (4.11)\n|last       = \"[[Best Laid Plans (Once Upon a Time)|Best Laid Plans]]\" (4.16)\n|creator    = [[Edward Kitsis]] & [[Adam Horowitz]]\n|portrayer  = [[Merrin Dungey]]<br>[[Tiffany Boone]] (young)\n|alias      = Sea Witch\n|species    = Cecaelia\n|title      = Queen of Darkness\n|family     = [[Poseidon]] (father, arguably deceased/dead)<ref name=\"actor\">{{cite web|title=Ernie Hudson To Play Poseidon On \u2018''Once Upon a Time''\u2019|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/ernie-hudson-cast-poseidon-once-upon-a-time-abc-1201330792/|accessdate=February 3, 2015|date=December 19, 2014|website=deadline.com|publisher=Deadline|last=Brooks|first=Larry}}</ref><br />Mother without name (deceased/dead)\n|extra-hdr  = Centric episodes\n|data31     = {{plainlist|\n*\"[[Darkness on the Edge of Town (Once Upon a Time)|Darkness on the Edge of Town]]\"\n*\"[[Poor Unfortunate Soul]]\"\n}}\n\n}}\nTwo live-action versions of Ursula appear in the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] television series ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]]''.\n\n;The Sea Goddess\nUrsula the Sea Goddess appears in Season 3, where she is voiced by [[Yvette Nicole Brown]]. In the episode \"[[Ariel (Once Upon a Time)|Ariel]]\", Ursula is described as a sea goddess whom no one has seen for a thousand years. According to Ariel, Ursula gave merfolk the ability to gain legs once a year, when the tide is highest. Ariel uses this ability to visit Prince Eric at his castle, where he is having a ball honoring Ursula. Later, the [[Evil Queen (Disney)|Evil Queen]] ([[Lana Parrilla]]) disguises herself as Ursula in order to make a deal with Ariel and trick her into capturing Snow White. This physical disguise includes short white hair and tentacles, similar to Ursula's animated appearance. Although the Queen considers Ursula to be \"a long-dead octopus\", she is shocked when the real Ursula possesses a statue and warns the queen not to impersonate her again.\n\n;The Sea Witch\nUrsula the Sea Witch is an antagonist who appears in the second half of Season 4, where she is portrayed as an adult by [[Merrin Dungey]], and as a teenager by [[Tiffany Boone]].\n\nThe episode \"[[Poor Unfortunate Soul (Once Upon a Time)|Poor Unfortunate Soul]]\" contains further flashbacks to Ursula's youth, when she was a teenage [[mermaid]] living under the sea with her father King [[Poseidon]] ([[Ernie Hudson]]). Ursula was gifted with a beautiful voice, which Poseidon wanted her to use to lure pirates to their death, in order to avenge the murder of Ursula's mother at the hands of an unnamed pirate. Ursula refused and instead befriended a pirate, Captain Hook ([[Colin O'Donoghue]]), who supported her desire for freedom. Ursula and Hook's friendship fell apart when Hook sealed Ursula's singing voice inside an enchanted shell, in order to punish Poseidon for destroying a weapon Hook wanted for himself. Ursula, angered and disappointed with both merfolk and humans, used Poseidon's trident to transform her tail into tentacles, emulating the ancient sea goddess that she was named after.\n\nThe episodes \"[[Heroes and Villains (Once Upon a Time)|Heroes and Villains]]\" and \"[[Darkness on the Edge of Town (Once Upon a Time)|Darkness on the Edge of Town]]\" contain flashbacks to the Enchanted Forest past, where Ursula teamed up with fellow witches [[Maleficent#Once Upon a Time|Maleficent]] ([[Kristin Bauer van Straten]]) and [[Cruella de Vil#Once Upon a Time|Cruella De Vil]] ([[Victoria Smurfit]]). The three of them worked together to try to defeat the heroes and find their happy endings, but failed. In the episode \"[[Best Laid Plans (Once Upon a Time)|Best Laid Plans]]\", while trying to rescue Maleficent's baby from Snow and Charming, Ursula and Cruella fell into a portal that lead into the non-magical world. Three decades later, in modern day New York, Ursula is working as a cleaner in an aquarium when she is recruited by Rumplestiltskin, who also reunites her with Cruella. Ursula, Cruella and Rumplestiltskin then trick their way into entering the magical town of Storybrooke. In the episode \"[[Unforgiven (Once Upon a Time)|Unforgiven]]\", they resurrect Maleficent to join their group.\n\nIn the episode \"[[Best Laid Plans (Once Upon a Time)|Best Laid Plans]]\" flashback it was shown that she and Cruella were sent from Enchanted Forrest before Dark Curse to World Without Magic because of [[Snow White]] ([[Ginnifer Goodwin]]) and [[Prince Charming]] ([[Josh Dallas]]). \n\nIn the episode's \"Poor Unfortunate Soul\" present time, a remorseful Hook makes a deal with Ursula to get her singing voice back. They are only successful when Ariel intercedes, bringing Poseidon to Storybrooke so that he and Ursula can reconcile, and the enchantment is broken. Having achieved her happy ending, Ursula then tells Hook the full plan Rumplestiltskin has for the heroes, and afterward returns to the sea with her father.\n\n===''Descendants 2''===\n{{Main|Descendants 2}}\n\nUrsula makes an appearance in the movie, voiced by [[Whoopi Goldberg]]. In the film, her daughter Uma is the main antagonist. During one scene, Ursula whips her tentacle out from the kitchen of her Fish and Chips shop and yells at Uma to stop singing and come to wash the dishes.\n\nTwenty years prior to the movie, Ursula had been banished on the Isle of the Lost with other villains. It's also revealed that Ursula and Maleficent had a rivalry over who gets to be the ruler of the island. Now, she has a daughter named Uma, who is feisty and manipulative just like her mom and she works at her mother's fish and chips shop. Uma and her archenemy, Mal, who is Maleficent's daughter, have a heated rivalry on the island. On ''Rise of the Isle of the Lost'', Uma befriends with Harry, son of [[Captain Hook]], who's also Uma's first mate at her pirate crew and Gil, son of [[Gaston]], who's also in Uma's pirate crew. Uma, Harry, and Gil are on a quest to find King Triton's trident to get out of the island for good until Mal retrieve it and Uma swears that she will get her revenge on Mal.\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\nUrsula has earned a positive reception from entertainment critics. When ''The Little Mermaid'' was first released in 1989, film critics and audiences alike immediately embraced Ursula as one of Disney's best villains,<ref name=\":0\" /> as well as one of the studio's strongest and most powerful villains in several years.<ref name=\":22\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familyhometheater.com/2013/10/01/the-little-mermaid-1989-3d-blu-ray-combo/|title=THE LITTLE MERMAID (1989) (3D Blu-ray combo)|last=|first=|date=October 1, 2013|website=Family Home Theater|publisher=|access-date=April 18, 2016|quote=Ursula\u2014one of the stronger Disney villains in the past several decades\u2014gets her to sign on the dotted line of a Mephistophelean bargain.}}</ref> Film critic [[Roger Ebert]] dubbed Ursula Disney's \"most satisfying villainess since\" ''[[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937 film)|Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs]]''<nowiki/>' [[Evil Queen (Disney)|Evil Queen]], who debuted in 1937.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-little-mermaid-1989|title=THE LITTLE MERMAID|last=Ebert|first=Roger|date=November 17, 1989|website=Roger Ebert|publisher=Ebert Digital LLC|access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> Critics agree that Ursula played an important role in the overall success of ''The Little Mermaid''<nowiki/>.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dustinputman.com/bluray/89_littlemermaid.htm|title=The Little Mermaid  (1989)|last=Putman|first=Dustin|date=October 1, 2013|website=TheBluFile|publisher=Dustin Putman|access-date=April 18, 2016}}</ref> Samantha Rullo of ''[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]'' reviewed Ursula as a \"way more interesting\" character than Ariel herself, while praising her for \"rocking the best hair and makeup of any Disney villain.\"<ref name=\":31\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/26194-6-disney-villains-with-more-movie-potential-than-maleficent|title=6 Disney Villains With More Movie Potential Than 'Maleficent'|last=Rullo|first=Samantha|date=May 29, 2014|website=Bustle|publisher=|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref> Also writing for ''Bustle'', Caitlyn Callegari appreciated Ursula for \"tell[ing] it like it is.\"<ref name=\":33\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/25743-angelina-jolies-maleficient-premiere-is-upon-us-gear-up-with-our-top-10-favorite-villains|title=Angelina Jolie's 'Maleficient' Premiere Is Upon Us: Gear Up With Our Top 10 Favorite Villains|last=Callegari|first=Caitlyn|date=May 28, 2014|website=Bustle|publisher=|access-date=April 28, 2016}}</ref> <nowiki/>Jay Boyar of the ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'' hailed Ursula as \"A total success\" despite sharing some similarities with previous Disney villains.<ref name=\":19\">{{cite web|url = http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1999-08-08/entertainment/9908050509_1_mermaid-shop-of-horrors-ariel|title = Dive Into Disneys Delightful 'Mermaid'|date = August 8, 1999|accessdate = September 14, 2014|website = Orlando Sentinel|publisher =|last = Boyar|first = Jay}}</ref> [[Janet Maslin]] of ''[[The New York Times]] ''described Ursula as \"a fabulously [[Camp (style)|campy]] creation embodying the film's well-developed sense of mischief.\"<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=950DE2DE1331F936A25752C1A96F948260&partner=Rotten%2520Tomatoes|title = The Little Mermaid (1989) Review/Film; Andersen's 'Mermaid,' by Way of Disney|date = November 15, 1989|accessdate = September 14, 2014|website = The New York Times|publisher = The New York Times Company|last = Maslin|first = Janet}}</ref> Describing the character as an \"inventive high-camp villainess,\" the ''[[New York Daily News]]''<nowiki/>' Kathleen Carroll cited Ursula as a prime example of the film's \"outstanding\" animation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/mermaid-sea-1989-review-article-1.2429392|title=\u2018The Little Mermaid\u2019 is a must sea: 1989 review|last=Carroll|first=Kathleen|date=November 15, 1989|website=New York Daily News|publisher=NYDailyNews.com|access-date=April 6, 2016}}</ref> Hailing the character as \"a visual feast,\" ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' considered Ursula to be among \"the film\u2019s more inspired inventions\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/1988/film/reviews/the-little-mermaid-1200427784/|title=Review: \u2018The Little Mermaid\u2019|last=|first=|date=December 31, 1988|website=Variety|publisher=Variety Media, LLC|access-date=April 20, 2016}}</ref><nowiki/>\n\n{{rquote|right|Actress Pat Carroll and the Ursula animators pump astonishing gobs of rotten-flirty menace and perversity into Witch Ursula, who looks a bit like the late actor Divine pasted over with an evil [[Jack Nicholson]] leer and squeezed into a cleavage-popping black evening gown, tailing off startlingly into eight squiggling black octopus tentacles. With her pet moray eels, she is a genuine nightmare, an obese lavender voluptuary peeling off lines like \"Life's full of hard choices . . . I'n't it?\" with blowzy relish or erupting from the ocean like [[Moby Dick (whale)|Moby Dick]] on [[bonbons]].|The ''Los Angeles Times''' Michael Wilmington}}\nWilliam Thomas of ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' described Ursula as \"truly quake-inducing\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/little-mermaid/review/|title=The Little Mermaid Review|last=Thomas|first=William|date=January 1, 2000|website=Empire|publisher=|access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> while ''Time''<nowiki/>'s Eliana Dockterman enjoyed the fact that, unlike previous Disney villains, \"Ursula doesn\u2019t even pretend to be good ... Right off the bat, she owns her evil witchiness\".<ref name=\":16\" /> Kilmeny Fane-Saunders, writing for ''[[Radio Times]]'', warned parents that Ursula could possibly frighten young children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/film/nbmmk/the-little-mermaid|title=The Little Mermaid|last=Fane-Saunders|first=Kilmeny|date=1989|website=Radio Times|publisher=Immediate Media Company|access-date=April 6, 2016}}</ref> However, ''[[The Huffington Post]]''<nowiki/>'s Hilary Sheinbau believes that \"there are many of these people who walk ... talk and strive among us\", concluding, \"it\u2019s important for kids to know that not everyone is going to look out for their best interests, however tempting some offers may be.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/hilary-sheinbaum/the-little-mermaid_b_1694342.html|title=Why My Kids Will Not Be Watching The Little Mermaid|last=Sheinbaum|first=Hilary|date=September 22, 2012|website=The Huffington Post|publisher=TheHuffingtonPost.com, In|access-date=April 22, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]''<nowiki/>'s Duncan Lindsay agreed that Ursula teaches children \"that binding contracts are a necessary part of every deal. We can thank her for all of our business sense as we are always sure to triple check that paperwork when ... securing deals.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2015/06/20/12-valuable-lessons-disney-villains-taught-all-children-5255431/|title=12 valuable lessons Disney villains taught all children|last=Lindsay|first=Duncan|date=June 20, 2015|website=Metro|publisher=|access-date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> Dave Smith of the [[Disney.com|Disney Archives]] wrote, \"When anger does bring out her true emotion, the effects are staggering. Her look of stark hatred, even while her face is still human, must certainly have brought nightmares to young children. And when she finally changes into a giant, towering up through the waves and over puny mortals, the embodiment of fury is quite breathtaking.\" Smith concluded, \"Earlier we may have chuckled at her villainy; at this moment, there is no laughter ... only genuine fear.\"<ref name=\":13\" /> Meanwhile, [[Smosh|SMOSH]]'s Francesco Marciuliano praised the character as \"one of the most gleefully evil characters Disney has ever created.\"<ref name=\":34\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.smosh.com/smosh-pit/articles/6-more-disney-villains-should-get-their-own-movies|title=6 Disney Villains That Should Get Their Own Movies|last=Marciuliano|first=Francesco|date=2014|website=SMOSH|publisher=Defy Media, LLC|access-date=May 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCarroll's vocal performance as Ursula has been met with similar praise.<ref name=\":0\" /> Michael Wilmington of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' predicted that the actress \"will make [the film] a hit\".<ref>{{cite web|url = https://articles.latimes.com/1989-11-15/entertainment/ca-1802_1_big-leap|title = MOVIE REVIEW : 'Little Mermaid' Makes Big Splash|date = November 15, 1989|accessdate = September 14, 2014|website = Los Angeles Times|publisher = Los Angeles Times|last = Wilmington|first = Michael}}</ref> <nowiki/>Roger Hurlburt of the ''[[Sun-Sentinel]] ''enthused, \"If [[Academy Awards]] were given for vocal talents, then Pat Carroll ... certainly is deserving.\" Hurlburt went on to extol Carroll as \"a tour de force ... making such previous Disney villainesses -- [[Cruella de Vil]]le ([[sic]]) (''[[One Hundred and One Dalmatians|101 Dalmatians]]'') and the Evil Queen (''Snow White'') -- pale in comparison\",<ref>{{cite web|url = http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1989-11-17/features/8902100289_1_mermaid-animation-whippet|title = `Mermaid` Is Magic|date = November 17, 1989|accessdate = September 19, 2014|website = Sun-Sentinel|publisher = Roger|last = Hurlburt|first =}}</ref> while the ''[[Deseret News]]''<nowiki/>' Chris Hicks described her performance as \"delightful\".<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.deseretnews.com/article/700001061/Little-Mermaid-The.html|title = Film review: Little Mermaid, The|date = November 14, 1997|accessdate = September 14, 2014|website = Deseret News|publisher =|last = Hicks|first = Chris}}</ref> To-date, Carroll's interpretation of Ursula remains so respected that it has ultimately eclipsed her previous [[body of work]] as an actress, of which she is \"most proud\" nonetheless, not minding that she is associated with the role almost exclusively.<ref name=\":0\" /> Carroll explained that she continues to sign [[autograph]]s \"Dear Sweetlips: I hug you with my tentacles. Oceans of love, Ursula.' And then, underneath, in parentheses, I put 'Pat Carroll,' very small\" because her fans are more likely to identify with her character than her.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Accolades and legacy===\nRevered as a fan favorite,<ref name=\":35\" /> Ursula has established herself as one of Disney's most iconic characters;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxofficescoop.com/top-ten-animated-disney-villains/|title=Top Ten Animated Disney Villains|last=|first=|date=January 14, 2014|website=Box Office Scoop|publisher=BoxOfficeScoop.com|access-date=April 26, 2016|quote=Ursula is a truly iconic character in the Disney franchise.}}</ref><ref name=\":39\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/10/16/showbiz/movies/disney-villains-gallery/|title=Disney's scariest villains|last=Burdette|first=Kacy|last2=France|first2=Lisa Respers|date=October 16, 2013|website=CNN|publisher=Cable News Network|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref> she is widely regarded as one of the studio's \"classic\" villains.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":29\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/28/disney-villains_n_4661417.html|title=A Definitive Ranking Of 25 Classic Disney Villains|last=Duca|first=Lauren|date=January 28, 2014|website=The Huffington Post|publisher=TheHuffingtonPost.com, Inc|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.popoptiq.com/20-greatest-classic-disney-villians/|title=20 Greatest Classic Disney Villains|last=Reese|first=Kyle|date=June 11, 2009|website=PopOptiq|publisher=PopOptiQ|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":30\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/new/11-Classic-Disney-Villains-Ranked-By-How-They-Survive-Jail-70202-p9.html|title=11 Classic Disney Villains, Ranked By How Well They\u2019d Survive In Jail|last=Romano|first=Nick|date=|website=Cinemablend|publisher=Gateway Media News & Entertainment|access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> Author Corey Sandler described Ursula as a popular \"anti-favorite\" in his book ''Econoguide Disneyland Resort, Universal Studios Hollywood: And Other Major Southern California Attractions Including Disney's California Adventure''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5rx5dKbVU78C&pg=PT95&dq=ursula+anti-favorites+disney&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiP3bmIqKnMAhVKt4MKHZaGCkMQ6AEIHDAA#v=onepage&q=ursula%20anti-favorites%20disney&f=false|title=Econoguide Disneyland Resort, Universal Studios Hollywood: And Other Major Southern California Attractions Including Disney's California Adventure|last=Sandler|first=Corey|publisher=Globe Pequot|year=2007|isbn=9780762741670|location=United States|pages=}}</ref> The character's impact as a villainness has ultimately eclipsed those of her predecessors.<ref name=\":13\" /> According to Laura Rosenfeld of Tech Times, Ursula has had the most profound influence out of all animated characters in the [[Disney canon]].<ref name=\":37\" /> The character is considered to be one of the greatest Disney villains of all-time,<ref name=\":23\" /><ref name=\":33\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/travel/attractions/the-daily-disney/os-best-disney-villains-pictures-photogallery.html|title=Pictures: Best Disney villains|last=|first=|date=|website=Orlando Sentinel|publisher=|access-date=May 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/travel/attractions/the-daily-disney/os-greatest-disney-villains-story.html|title=The 30 greatest Disney villains of all time|last=Mauney|first=Matt|date=May 30, 2014|website=Orlando Sentinel|publisher=|access-date=May 26, 2016}}</ref> and continues to be ranked highly on [[Countdown|countdown lists]] compiled by various publications. Ursula topped [[E!]]'s Disney villains ranking; author John Boone concluded that \"There will never be a Disney villain more wickedly wonderful than\" Ursula.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/ca/news/542233/all-of-the-disney-villains-ranked|title=All of the Disney Villains, Ranked|last=Boone|first=John|last2=Mullins|first2=Jenna|date=May 15, 2014|website=E!|publisher=Entertainment Television, LLC|access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> [[Yahoo! Movies]] ranked Ursula third, praising her \"for being the first female Disney baddie to get her own song.\"<ref name=\":18\" /> On ''The Huffington Post''<nowiki/>'s \"Definitive Ranking Of 25 Classic Disney Villains\", Ursula was also ranked third.<ref name=\":29\" /> [[About.com]] placed the character at number four in the website's \"Top 10 Disney Villains\" article.<ref name=\":17\" /> [[Babble.com]] ranked the character the fifth greatest Disney villain \"From Bad to Worst\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.babble.com/mom/the-top-15-disney-villains-ranked-from-bad-to-worst/|title=THE TOP 15 DISNEY VILLAINS RANKED FROM BAD TO WORST|last=Castiglia|first=Carolyn|date=2013|website=Babble.com|publisher=Disney|access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> [[Moviefone]] ranked Ursula seventh on the website's list of the thirty greatest Disney villains of all-time.<ref name=\":36\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.moviefone.com/2014/05/25/disney-villains/#slide=2641807|title=Disney Villains: Ranking the Top 30 of All Time|last=Susman|first=Gary|date=May 25, 2014|website=Moviefone|publisher=Aol Inc|access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> [[TVOvermind]] also ranked Ursula seventh in its article \"Ranking the Top 10 Animated Disney Villains\".<ref name=\":26\" /> Recognizing Ursula among \"8 Disney villains who are better than the heroes\", [[Beamly]]'s Sophie Hall believes that the character \"had more charisma than Ariel\".<ref name=\":28\" /> By extension, Ursula is also often considered to be among the greatest animated villains of all-time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.themarysue.com/seven-best-animated-female-fillans/|title=Bad and Drawn That Way: The Seven Best Animated Female Villains|last=Goodwin|first=Sara|date=September 17, 2015|website=The Mary Sue|publisher=The Mary Sue|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref> [[Sky Movies]] included the character on the website's list \"Despicable Them: Top Animated Villains\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sky.com/tv/channel/skymovies/gallery/top-animated-villains|title=Despicable Them: Top Animated Villains|last=|first=|date=|website=Sky Movies|publisher=Sky UK|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref> The ''[[Toronto Sun]]'' ranked Ursula the third \"top animated [villain] of all time\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2013/07/04/our-top-animated-villains-of-all-time|title=Our top animated villains of all time|last=Braun|first=Liz|date=July 4, 2013|website=Toronto Sun|publisher=Postmedia Network|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nUrsula is also considered to be one of Disney's most terrifying villains.<ref name=\":37\" /><ref name=\":35\" /><ref name=\":36\" /><ref name=\":39\" /> [[Disney.com|Oh My Disney]] ranked Ursula's line \"Triton\u2019s daughter will be mine and then I\u2019ll make him writhe. I\u2019ll see him wriggle like a worm on a hook!\" the fifth \"Most Sinister Disney Villain Quote\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ohmy.disney.com/movies/2015/01/27/the-definitive-ranking-of-the-most-sinister-disney-villain-quotes/|title=THE DEFINITIVE RANKING OF THE MOST SINISTER DISNEY VILLAIN QUOTES|last=|first=|date=2015|website=Oh My Disney|publisher=Disney|access-date=April 24, 2016}}</ref> Meanwhile, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' included the [[Climax (narrative)|climactic]] sequence in which Ursula grows into a giant on the magazine's list of the \"12 Scariest Moments in Kids' Films\", comparing the sequence to the iconic [[shower scene]] in the horror film ''[[Psycho (1960 film)|Psycho]]'' (1960),<ref name=\":24\" /> while [[BuzzFeed]] ranked the character's death fifth on the website's \"Definitive Ranking Of The Most Horrific Disney Villain Deaths\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/jamesgrebey/jeez-these-movies-are-supposed-to-be-for-children#.gm4zJ4MoK|title=A Definitive Ranking Of The Most Horrific Disney Villain Deaths|last=Grebey|first=James|last2=Nedd|first2=Alexis|date=July 25, 2014|website=BuzzFeed|publisher=BuzzFeed, Inc|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref> In the wake of the release of ''[[Maleficent (film)|Maleficent]]'' (2014), a [[Live action|live-action]] remake of Disney's ''Sleeping Beauty'' (1959) told from the perspective of the film's villain, several publications voted for Ursula among Disney villains who deserve to star in their own films,<ref name=\":34\" /> including [[Yahoo! Movies]], [[MTV]], ''[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]'' and the ''[[New York Post]].''<ref name=\":32\" /><ref name=\":31\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1835420/7-disney-villains-who-deserve-live-action-movies/|title=7 DISNEY VILLAINS WHO WOULD MAKE THEIR OWN PRETTY WICKED MOVIES|last=Myers|first=Janelle|date=May 31, 2014|website=MTV|publisher=Viacom International Inc|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2014/05/27/5-disney-villains-who-should-get-their-own-movies/|title=5 Disney villains who should get their own movies|last=Miller|first=George E|date=May 27, 2014|website=New York Post|publisher=|access-date=April 26, 2016}}</ref> David Crow of [[Den of Geek]] selected actor [[John Travolta]] as his first choice for the role of Ursula because of his drag performance as Edna Turnblad in the film ''[[Hairspray (2007 film)|Hairspray]]'' (2007), a role actually originated by Divine, the actor upon whose appearance Ursula's design was based.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.us/movies/disney-villains/231142/6-disney-villains-who-deserve-their-own-movie|title=6 Disney Villains Who Deserve Their Own Movie|last=Crow|first=David|date=January 21, 2014|website=Den of Geek|publisher=|access-date=April 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nUrsula's body type has been positively embraced by the public; the character has since been recognized as a symbol of body positivity.<ref name=\":38\">{{Cite web|url=http://hellogiggles.com/life-lessons-learned-disney-villains/2/|title=6 Life Lessons I Learned From Disney Villains|last=|first=|date=July 22, 2014|website=HelloGiggles|publisher=|access-date=May 29, 2016}}</ref> [[HelloGiggles]] believes that \"Ursula has the most positive body image\" out of all of Disney's villainnesses: \"She may not be a size zero, like the other villains and heroines, but she\u2019s equally as confident. She is sexy, she is glamorous and she shows of her curves with no apology.\"<ref name=\":38\" /> From 2007 onwards, Disney launched an advertising campaign called ''Disney Dreams Portraits'' featuring celebrities dressed up as various Disney characters and photographer [[Annie Leibovitz]]; [[Queen Latifah]] was photographed as Ursula for this campaign in 2011.<ref>{{ cite web | first=Ann | last=Oldenburg | date=March 3, 2011 | title=Queen Latifah, Olivia Wilde become Disney characters | url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2011/03/queen-latifah-olivia-wilde-become-disney-characters/1#.V_2_siQw3D4 | publisher=USAToday.com | accessdate=October 12, 2016 }}</ref> In 2012 Disney released a Disney Villain line of dolls and make-up, and its revamped imagery was criticized for \"slimming down\" of Ursula to make her \"marketable\" and ignoring body diversity.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gray|first=Emma|date=2012-06-29|title=Disney Villains: Ursula Gets Slimmed Down For The New 'Designer Collection'|publisher=Huffington Post|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/emma-gray/disney-villains-little-mermaid-ursula-slimmed-down-designer-collection_b_1638895.html|accessdate=2009-12-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Leach|first=Michelle|date=2012-07-04|title= The Little Mermaid's Ursula gets controversial makeover|publisher=She Knows Entertainment|url=http://www.sheknows.com/entertainment/articles/965185/the-little-mermaids-ursula-gets-controversial-makeoverl|accessdate=2009-12-23}}</ref> For Halloween of 2013, [[Amber Riley]] portrayed Ursula in a celebrity parody/tribute of \"[[Cell Block Tango]]\" from ''[[Chicago (musical)|Chicago]]'' titled \"Spell Block Tango\", directed by [[Todrick Hall]], which was praised for its highlighting Disney villains.<ref>{{cite web|last=Emmanuele|first=Juana|title=5 Reasons We Love the Disney Animation/'Chicago' Masup Video 'Spell Block Tango'| publisher=Hollywood.com| date=2013-10-28|url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/celebrities/55039054/spell-block-tango-todrick-hall-chicago-disney|accessdate=2013-11-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Eby|first=Margaret|title=Disney villains sing 'Chicago' parody 'Spell Block Tango'|publisher=New York Daily News|date=2013-10-30|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music-arts/disney-villains-sing-chicago-parody-spell-block-tango-article-1.1502061|accessdate=2013-11-05}}</ref> [[Lady Gaga]] wore an Ursula-inspired dress during [[ArtRave: The Artpop Ball]]. In the 2015 season of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]'', [[Rumer Willis]] dressed up as Ursula to perform a samba set to \"[[Poor Unfortunate Souls]]\".<ref>{{cite web | first=Hal | last=Boedeker | title=Disney Night scores for 'Dancing,' ABC | date=2015-04-14 | url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/tv/tv-guy/os-disney-night-dancing-abc-20150414-post.html | publisher=OrlandoSentinel | accessdate=2015-04-15 }}</ref> As arguably \"the most famous example of a direct tie to the [[LGBT community]],\" Ursula has also become something of a [[gay icon]], due in part to sharing Divine's appearance and personality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/14-disney-characters-you-had-no-idea-were-gay051013/#gs.Iq6YR3k|title=The 16 Disney characters you had no idea were gay|last=Morgan|first=Joe|date=October 5, 2013|website=Gay Star News|publisher=Gay Star News|access-date=May 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{The Little Mermaid}}\n\n[[Category:The Little Mermaid (franchise) characters]]\n[[Category:Kingdom Hearts characters]]\n[[Category:Female characters in animation]]\n[[Category:Female film villains]]\n[[Category:Female characters in television]]\n[[Category:Film characters introduced in 1989]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who use magic]]\n[[Category:Fictional kidnappers]]\n[[Category:Fictional octopuses]]\n[[Category:Fictional shapeshifters]]\n[[Category:Fictional witches]]\n[[Category:Disney animated villains]]\n", "name_user": "50.26.143.155", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(Added contact)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ursula_(The_Little_Mermaid)"}
{"title_page": "Myofibril", "text_new": "{{short description|Contractile element of muscle}}\n{{Infobox microanatomy\n| Name        = Myofibril\n| Latin       = myofibrilla\n| Greek       = \n| Image       = Blausen 0801 SkeletalMuscle.png\n| Caption     = [[Skeletal striated muscle|Skeletal muscle]], with myofibrils labeled at upper right.\n| Width       = 300px\n| Image2      = \n| Caption2    = \n}}\n[[Image:Myofibril.svg|300px|thumb|A diagram of the structure of a myofibril (consisting of many myofilaments in parallel, and sarcomeres in series]] \n[[Image:Sarcomere.svg|300px|thumb|Sliding filament model of muscle contraction]]\nA '''myofibril''' (also known as a '''muscle fibril''') is a basic rod-like unit of a muscle cell.<ref>{{cite book|last=McCracken|first=Thomas|title=New Atlas of Human Anatomy|year=1999|publisher=Metro Books|location=China|isbn=1-5866-3097-0|pages=1\u2013120}}</ref>  Muscles are composed of tubular cells called [[myocyte]]s, known as muscle fibers in [[striated muscle]], and these cells in turn contain many chains of myofibrils.  They are created during [[embryogenesis|embryonic development]] in a process known as [[myogenesis]].\n\nMyofibrils are composed of long proteins including [[actin]], [[myosin]], and [[titin]], and other proteins that hold them together. These proteins are organized into thick and thin filaments called [[myofilament]]s, which repeat along the length of the myofibril in sections called [[sarcomere]]s. [[Muscle contraction|Muscles contract]] by [[sliding filament theory|sliding the thick (myosin) and thin (actin) filaments]] along each other. This is by sumit kumar sah.\n\n==Structure==\nThe filaments of myofibrils, [[myofilament]]s, consist of two types, thick and thin:\n*Thin filaments consist primarily of the protein [[actin]], coiled with [[nebulin]] filaments. Actin, when polymerized into filaments, forms the \"ladder\" along which the myosin filaments \"climb\" to generate motion\n*Thick filaments consist primarily of the protein [[myosin]], held in place by [[titin]] filaments. Myosin is responsible for force generation. It is composed of a globular head with both ATP and actin binding sites, and a long tail involved in its polymerization into myosin filaments.\n\nThe protein complex composed of actin and myosin is sometimes referred to as \"actinomyosin\".\n\nIn striated muscle, such as [[skeletal muscle|skeletal]] and [[cardiac muscle]], the actin and myosin filaments each have a specific and constant length on the order of a few micrometers, far less than the length of the elongated muscle cell (a few millimeters in the case of human skeletal muscle cells). The filaments are organized into repeated subunits along the length of the myofibril. These subunits are called [[sarcomere]]s. The muscle cell is nearly filled with myofibrils running parallel to each other on the long axis of the cell. The sarcomeric subunits of one myofibril are in nearly perfect alignment with those of the myofibrils next to it. This alignment gives rise to certain optical properties which cause the cell to appear striped or striated. In [[smooth muscle]] cells, this alignment is absent, hence there are no apparent striations and the cells are called smooth.<ref>[http://muscle.ucsd.edu/musintro/fibril.shtml Muscle Physiology \u2013 Myofilament Structure<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Exposed muscle cells at certain angles, such as in [[cuts of meat|meat cuts]], can show [[structural coloration]] or [[iridescence]] due to this periodic alignment of the fibrils and sarcomeres.<ref name=foods>{{cite journal | journal=Foods | title=Iridescence in Meat Caused by Surface Gratings | date=November 2013 | author=Martinez-Hurtado, J L | volume=2 | pages=499\u2013506 |doi=10.3390/foods2040499 | pmid=28239133 | issue=4| last2=Akram | first2=Muhammad | last3=Yetisen | first3=Ali | pmc=5302279 }}</ref>\n\n===Appearance===\n[[Image:sarcomere.gif|thumb|left|450px]]\n\nThe names of the various sub-regions of the sarcomere are based on their relatively lighter or darker appearance when viewed through the light microscope.  Each sarcomere is delimited by two very dark colored bands called Z-discs or Z-lines (from the German ''zwischen'' meaning between). These Z-discs are dense protein discs that do not easily allow the passage of light. The [[T-tubule]] is present in this area.  The area between the Z-discs is further divided into two lighter colored bands at either end called the I-bands, and a darker, grayish band in the middle called the A band.\n\nThe I bands appear lighter because these regions of the sarcomere mainly contain the thin actin filaments, whose smaller diameter allows the passage of light between them. The A band, on the other hand, contains mostly [[myosin]] filaments whose larger diameter restricts the passage of light. A stands for [[anisotropic]] and I for [[isotropic]], referring to the optical properties of living muscle as demonstrated with [[polarized light]] microscopy.\n\nThe parts of the A band that abut the I bands are occupied by the both actin and myosin filaments (where they interdigitate as described above). Also within the A band is a relatively brighter central region called the H-zone (from the German ''helle'', meaning bright) in which there is no actin/myosin overlap when the muscle is in a relaxed state.  Finally, the H-zone is bisected by a dark central line called the M-line (from the German ''mittel'' meaning middle).\n\n==Development==\nA study of the developing leg muscle in a 12-day chick embryo using electron microscopy proposes a mechanism for the development of myofibrils. Developing muscle cells contain thick (myosin) filaments that are 160\u2013170 [[Angstrom|\u00c5]] in diameter and thin (actin)filaments that are 60\u201370 \u00c5 in diameter. Young myofibers contain a 7:1 ratio of thin to thick filaments. Along the long axis of the muscle cells in subsarcolemmal locations, free myofilaments become aligned and aggregate into hexagonally packed arrays. These aggregates form regardless of the presence of Z band or M band material. Aggregation occurs spontaneously because the tertiary structures of actin and myosin monomers contain all the \"information\" with the ionic strength and ATP concentration of the cell to aggregate into the filaments.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Fischman, Donald A. |title=An electron microscope study of myofibril formation in embryonic chick skeletal muscle|journal= The Journal of Cell Biology|volume= 32|issue=3|year=1967|pages= 558\u201375|doi=10.1083/jcb.32.3.557|pmc=2107275|pmid=6034479}}</ref>\n\n==Function==\nThe [[myosin]] heads form cross bridges with the [[actin]] myofilaments; this is where they carry out a 'rowing' action along the actin. When the muscle fibre is relaxed (before contraction), the myosin head has ADP and phosphate bound to it.\n\nWhen a nerve impulse arrives, Ca<sup>2+</sup> ions cause [[troponin]] to change shape; this moves the troponin + tropomyosin complex away, leaving the myosin binding sites open.\n\nThe myosin head now binds to the actin myofilament.  Energy in the head of the myosin myofilament moves the head, which slides the actin past.  hence ADP is released.\n\nATP presents itself (as the presence of the calcium ions activates the myosin's ATPase), and the myosin heads disconnect from the actin to grab the ATP. The ATP is then broken down into ADP and phosphate. Energy is released and stored in the myosin head to utilize for later movement.  The myosin heads now return to their upright relaxed position.  If calcium is present, the process is repeated.\n\nWhen a muscle contracts, the actin is pulled along myosin toward the center of the [[sarcomere]] until the actin and myosin filaments are completely overlapped.  The H zone becomes smaller and smaller due to the increasing overlap of actin and myosin filaments, and the muscle shortens.  Thus when the muscle is fully contracted, the H zone is no longer visible.  Note that the actin and myosin filaments themselves do not change length, but instead slide past each other.  This is known as the sliding filament theory of muscle contraction.<ref>Marieb, E. N., Hoehn, K., & Hoehn, F. (2007). Human Anatomy & Physiology. (7th ed., pp. 284\u201387). San Francisco, California: Benjamin-Cummings Pub Co.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Motor protein]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/19970720143944/http://www.nismat.org/physcor/muscle.html Muscle Physiology Primer]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081217143932/http://msjensen.cehd.umn.edu/1135/Links/Animations/Flash/0008-swf_sarcomere_shor.swf Animation of sarcomere contraction]\n\n{{Cellular structures}}\n{{Muscle tissue}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Organelles]]\n[[Category:Protein complexes]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Contractile element of muscle}}\n{{Infobox microanatomy\n| Name        = Myofibril\n| Latin       = myofibrilla\n| Greek       = \n| Image       = Blausen 0801 SkeletalMuscle.png\n| Caption     = [[Skeletal striated muscle|Skeletal muscle]], with myofibrils labeled at upper right.\n| Width       = 300px\n| Image2      = \n| Caption2    = \n}}\n[[Image:Myofibril.svg|300px|thumb|A diagram of the structure of a myofibril (consisting of many myofilaments in parallel, and sarcomeres in series]] \n[[Image:Sarcomere.svg|300px|thumb|Sliding filament model of muscle contraction]]\nA '''myofibril''' (also known as a '''muscle fibril''') is a basic rod-like unit of a muscle cell.<ref>{{cite book|last=McCracken|first=Thomas|title=New Atlas of Human Anatomy|year=1999|publisher=Metro Books|location=China|isbn=1-5866-3097-0|pages=1\u2013120}}</ref>  Muscles are composed of tubular cells called [[myocyte]]s, known as muscle fibers in [[striated muscle]], and these cells in turn contain many chains of myofibrils.  They are created during [[embryogenesis|embryonic development]] in a process known as [[myogenesis]].\n\nMyofibrils are composed of long proteins including [[actin]], [[myosin]], and [[titin]], and other proteins that hold them together. These proteins are organized into thick and thin filaments called [[myofilament]]s, which repeat along the length of the myofibril in sections called [[sarcomere]]s. [[Muscle contraction|Muscles contract]] by [[sliding filament theory|sliding the thick (myosin) and thin (actin) filaments]] along each other.\n\n==Structure==\nThe filaments of myofibrils, [[myofilament]]s, consist of two types, thick and thin:\n*Thin filaments consist primarily of the protein [[actin]], coiled with [[nebulin]] filaments. Actin, when polymerized into filaments, forms the \"ladder\" along which the myosin filaments \"climb\" to generate motion\n*Thick filaments consist primarily of the protein [[myosin]], held in place by [[titin]] filaments. Myosin is responsible for force generation. It is composed of a globular head with both ATP and actin binding sites, and a long tail involved in its polymerization into myosin filaments.\n\nThe protein complex composed of actin and myosin is sometimes referred to as \"actinomyosin\".\n\nIn striated muscle, such as [[skeletal muscle|skeletal]] and [[cardiac muscle]], the actin and myosin filaments each have a specific and constant length on the order of a few micrometers, far less than the length of the elongated muscle cell (a few millimeters in the case of human skeletal muscle cells). The filaments are organized into repeated subunits along the length of the myofibril. These subunits are called [[sarcomere]]s. The muscle cell is nearly filled with myofibrils running parallel to each other on the long axis of the cell. The sarcomeric subunits of one myofibril are in nearly perfect alignment with those of the myofibrils next to it. This alignment gives rise to certain optical properties which cause the cell to appear striped or striated. In [[smooth muscle]] cells, this alignment is absent, hence there are no apparent striations and the cells are called smooth.<ref>[http://muscle.ucsd.edu/musintro/fibril.shtml Muscle Physiology \u2013 Myofilament Structure<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Exposed muscle cells at certain angles, such as in [[cuts of meat|meat cuts]], can show [[structural coloration]] or [[iridescence]] due to this periodic alignment of the fibrils and sarcomeres.<ref name=foods>{{cite journal | journal=Foods | title=Iridescence in Meat Caused by Surface Gratings | date=November 2013 | author=Martinez-Hurtado, J L | volume=2 | pages=499\u2013506 |doi=10.3390/foods2040499 | pmid=28239133 | issue=4| last2=Akram | first2=Muhammad | last3=Yetisen | first3=Ali | pmc=5302279 }}</ref>\n\n===Appearance===\n[[Image:sarcomere.gif|thumb|left|450px]]\n\nThe names of the various sub-regions of the sarcomere are based on their relatively lighter or darker appearance when viewed through the light microscope.  Each sarcomere is delimited by two very dark colored bands called Z-discs or Z-lines (from the German ''zwischen'' meaning between). These Z-discs are dense protein discs that do not easily allow the passage of light. The [[T-tubule]] is present in this area.  The area between the Z-discs is further divided into two lighter colored bands at either end called the I-bands, and a darker, grayish band in the middle called the A band.\n\nThe I bands appear lighter because these regions of the sarcomere mainly contain the thin actin filaments, whose smaller diameter allows the passage of light between them. The A band, on the other hand, contains mostly [[myosin]] filaments whose larger diameter restricts the passage of light. A stands for [[anisotropic]] and I for [[isotropic]], referring to the optical properties of living muscle as demonstrated with [[polarized light]] microscopy.\n\nThe parts of the A band that abut the I bands are occupied by the both actin and myosin filaments (where they interdigitate as described above). Also within the A band is a relatively brighter central region called the H-zone (from the German ''helle'', meaning bright) in which there is no actin/myosin overlap when the muscle is in a relaxed state.  Finally, the H-zone is bisected by a dark central line called the M-line (from the German ''mittel'' meaning middle).\n\n==Development==\nA study of the developing leg muscle in a 12-day chick embryo using electron microscopy proposes a mechanism for the development of myofibrils. Developing muscle cells contain thick (myosin) filaments that are 160\u2013170 [[Angstrom|\u00c5]] in diameter and thin (actin)filaments that are 60\u201370 \u00c5 in diameter. Young myofibers contain a 7:1 ratio of thin to thick filaments. Along the long axis of the muscle cells in subsarcolemmal locations, free myofilaments become aligned and aggregate into hexagonally packed arrays. These aggregates form regardless of the presence of Z band or M band material. Aggregation occurs spontaneously because the tertiary structures of actin and myosin monomers contain all the \"information\" with the ionic strength and ATP concentration of the cell to aggregate into the filaments.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Fischman, Donald A. |title=An electron microscope study of myofibril formation in embryonic chick skeletal muscle|journal= The Journal of Cell Biology|volume= 32|issue=3|year=1967|pages= 558\u201375|doi=10.1083/jcb.32.3.557|pmc=2107275|pmid=6034479}}</ref>\n\n==Function==\nThe [[myosin]] heads form cross bridges with the [[actin]] myofilaments; this is where they carry out a 'rowing' action along the actin. When the muscle fibre is relaxed (before contraction), the myosin head has ADP and phosphate bound to it.\n\nWhen a nerve impulse arrives, Ca<sup>2+</sup> ions cause [[troponin]] to change shape; this moves the troponin + tropomyosin complex away, leaving the myosin binding sites open.\n\nThe myosin head now binds to the actin myofilament.  Energy in the head of the myosin myofilament moves the head, which slides the actin past.  hence ADP is released.\n\nATP presents itself (as the presence of the calcium ions activates the myosin's ATPase), and the myosin heads disconnect from the actin to grab the ATP. The ATP is then broken down into ADP and phosphate. Energy is released and stored in the myosin head to utilize for later movement.  The myosin heads now return to their upright relaxed position.  If calcium is present, the process is repeated.\n\nWhen a muscle contracts, the actin is pulled along myosin toward the center of the [[sarcomere]] until the actin and myosin filaments are completely overlapped.  The H zone becomes smaller and smaller due to the increasing overlap of actin and myosin filaments, and the muscle shortens.  Thus when the muscle is fully contracted, the H zone is no longer visible.  Note that the actin and myosin filaments themselves do not change length, but instead slide past each other.  This is known as the sliding filament theory of muscle contraction.<ref>Marieb, E. N., Hoehn, K., & Hoehn, F. (2007). Human Anatomy & Physiology. (7th ed., pp. 284\u201387). San Francisco, California: Benjamin-Cummings Pub Co.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Motor protein]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/19970720143944/http://www.nismat.org/physcor/muscle.html Muscle Physiology Primer]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081217143932/http://msjensen.cehd.umn.edu/1135/Links/Animations/Flash/0008-swf_sarcomere_shor.swf Animation of sarcomere contraction]\n\n{{Cellular structures}}\n{{Muscle tissue}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Organelles]]\n[[Category:Protein complexes]]\n", "name_user": "Sumitkumarsah123", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(For any quires contact me on gmail.  Sumitsah02432@gmail.com)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Myofibril"}
